I use TortoiseSVN to access file based local repo. In all my commits an author is my Windows login name. Is it possible to use different name?

I know how to change author after commit but how to change before? Installing apache/svnserver is not an option.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Yes, you can set the `svn:author` property in TortoiseSVN for use in local file-based repositories. To change the commit author before making a commit, follow these steps:

1. Right-click on your working copy and pick `TortoiseSVN → Properties`.

2. In the `Properties` dialog, click on `New` and select `svn:author` from the `Property name` drop-down menu.

3. Enter the author name you wish to use in the `Property value` field and click `OK`.

4. Click `OK` again to close the `Properties` dialog.

From now on, all commits you make will have the specified author name. 

Please note that this won't change the commit author for existing revisions in the repository – only for revisions created after the `svn:author` property has been set as described above.

Additionally, the `svn:author` property change only affects the working copy in which it was set. If you check out a new working copy, you’ll need to set the `svn:author` property again.

Note: This change is local to your repository. If you're collaborating with others, they won't see this change on their end. They will continue to see your Windows login name as the author. There's no built-in, standard way in Subversion to set the commit author to something other than the authenticated user.
<|end|>


