If you need to encode each value separately, you could use a One hot encoding or a MultiLabelBinarizer, transforming each different value as a unique integer. 

For instance, you could design a function that gather each unique string across all columns, assign an integer to each one of them, and finally replace across your dataset each string by its corresponding numerical representation.

Below is an example of how this could be achieved:

```python
from sklearn.preprocessing import MultiLabelBinarizer

def encode_multilabel(dataframe: pd.DataFrame) -> pd.DataFrame:
    mlb = MultiLabelBinarizer()
    
    # Splits strings of each column on commas, gather unique strings, fit & transform them using mlb
    dataframe = dataframe.apply(lambda x: [i.split(",") for i in x])
    all_values = np.unique(np.concatenate(dataframe.values).flatten())
    mlb.fit(all_values)
    dataframe = dataframe.apply(lambda x: [mlb.transform(i) for i in x])
    
    return dataframe
```  

Please adjust it according to your data and requirements. It's also suggested to keep track of the mapping of your original categories to the new integer values. You can do this simply by preserving the object returned by the encoder's fit method, which should have a method or attribute allowing you to see the original categories. For example, after fitting, the MultiLabelBinarizer has the classes_ attribute.

Additionaly, word of caution, this approach would only make sense if the order and combinations of these substrings in each cell does not matter, and if you plan to use a machine learning algorithm that can handle categorical data encoded this way (e.g., most tree-based algorithms, neural networks).
