<|user|>
If I have multiple estimates, e.g. a set of regression coefficients or estimated means, each estimate associated with a standard error. I can easily average them to get an average estimate. However, how do I compute the average standard error based on the individual estimates and individual standard errors?
<|end|>
<|asst|>
The average standard error is not simply the average of all the individual standard errors. The reason behind this is that standard errors are a measure of variability or dispersion, and such measures do not average linearly.

If the estimates are independent, then sometimes you can calculate the pooled or combined standard error. The formula to calculate that is:

SE = sqrt[SE1^2/n1 + SE2^2/n2 + ... + SEn^2/nn]

where SE is the standard error, n is the sample size, and the sub-indices refer to the individual studies or estimates.

This formula assumes that the studies are independent, which means that if there's some sort of systematic error across all your studies, then the pooled standard error will not reflect the actual precision of your aggregated estimate.

Also note that this pooled standard error refers to the SEM of the pooled estimate (i.e., the estimate obtained by averaging the individual estimates), not the average of the standard errors. 

Lastly, you may want to consider performing a meta-analysis if you're trying to aggregate results across multiple studies. Performing a meta-analysis takes into account both the size of the effect as measured in each study, but also the sample size or precision of that estimate. 

Please consult with a statistician or refer to statistical literature for the applicable circumstances to use this formula, as well as the interpretation and limitations.
<|end|>


