I need to understand how this would be in Java:
lang
package main

import (
	"strings"
	"unicode"
)

type Extension struct {
	sturdiness float64
	name       string
}

func StrongestExtension(class_name string, extensions []string) string {
	var extensionList []Extension
	var strongest Extension

	for _, extensionName := range extensions {
		CAP, SM := counts(extensionName)
		sturdiness := (CAP - SM) / float64(len(extensionName))
		extensionList = append(extensionList, Extension{sturdiness, extensionName})
	}

	strongest = extensionList[0]
	for _, extension := range extensionList {
		if extension.sturdiness > strongest.sturdiness {
			strongest = extension
		}
	}

	return class_name + "." + strongest.name
}

func counts(s string) (float64, float64) {
	var upper, lower float64
	for _, char := range s {
		if unicode.IsUpper(char) {
			upper++
		}

		if unicode.IsLower(char) {
			lower++
		}
	}

	return upper, lower
}

func main() {
	extensions := []string{"AA", "Be", "CC"}
	class_name := "my_class"
	result := StrongestExtension(class_name, extensions)
	println(result)
}
Please add some explanatory comments in the Java code.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Here is a simple conversion of the equivalent Go code into Java:

```java
import java.util.ArrayList;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String[] extensions = {"AA", "Be", "CC"};
        String class_name = "my_class";
        String result = getStrongestExtension(class_name, extensions);
        System.out.println(result);
    }

    private static class Extension {
        double sturdiness;
        String name;

        public Extension(double sturdiness, String name) {
            this.sturdiness = sturdiness;
            this.name = name;
        }
    }

    private static String getStrongestExtension(String className, String[] extensions) {
        ArrayList<Extension> extensionList = new ArrayList<>();
        Extension strongest;

        for (String extensionName : extensions) {
            double[] counts = getCounts(extensionName);
            double sturdiness = (counts[0] - counts[1]) / extensionName.length();
            extensionList.add(new Extension(sturdiness, extensionName));
        }

        strongest = extensionList.get(0);
        for (Extension extension : extensionList) {
            if (extension.sturdiness > strongest.sturdiness) {
                strongest = extension;
            }
        }

        return className + "." + strongest.name;
    }

    /* Here we calculate the supply counts for a string s. The function returns an array of two elements,
       the first element represents the count of uppercase (CAP), the second represents the count of 
       lowercase (SM). */
    private static double[] getCounts(String s) {
        double upper = 0, lower = 0;
        for (char c : s.toCharArray()) {
            if (Character.isUpperCase(c)) {
                upper++;
            }
            if (Character.isLowerCase(c)) {
                lower++;
            }
        }
        return new double[]{upper, lower};
    }
}
```
Brief Explanation:
The given Go code is creating a struct `Extension` to hold two parameters, the sturdiness and name of an extension. The method `StrongestExtension` calculates `sturdiness` for each extension based on the count of uppercase and lowercase letters, then it determines the strongest extension (the one with the highest `sturdiness`), and returns the class name along with the strongest extension. 

The Java code is doing the same thing; `Extension` is represented as a private static class nested inside the `Main` class. The method `getStrongestExtension` is equivalent to `StrongestExtension` in Go. The function `counts()` is converted to `getCounts()`. The Java code is using ArrayLists<> as compared to slices in Go. Moreover, in Java, the function returns the count of uppercase and lowercase letters as an array of `double` instead of two separate `double` values. The basic working of both codes is the same but there may be translational differences due to the difference between both languages.
<|end|>


