Design an algorithm to search for specific words within two separate sentences, including any that may be missing or extra in either one. Sentence A = "The quick brown fox jumps over the lazy dog." Sentence B = "The quick dog jumps over the lazy fox."
<|end|>
<|asst|>
The first step is to convert these sentences into sets of words. Then, we can simply use set operations to find the differences between them.

Here's a Python algorithm for this problem:

```python
def find_extra_missing_words(sentence_a, sentence_b):
    words_a = set(sentence_a.split())
    words_b = set(sentence_b.split())
    
    extra_in_a = words_a - words_b
    extra_in_b = words_b - words_a
    
    print("Extra words in sentence A: ", extra_in_a)
    print("Extra words in sentence B: ", extra_in_b)

sentence_a = "The quick brown fox jumps over the lazy dog."
sentence_b = "The quick dog jumps over the lazy fox."

find_extra_missing_words(sentence_a, sentence_b)
```

This script first separates the sentences into individual words, then puts these words into sets (which automatically remove any duplicates). It then subtracts the set of words in Sentence B from the set in Sentence A to find any words that are in A but not in B, and vice versa. These are printed out as the "extra" words in the respective sentences.

Note: This script assumes words are separated by spaces and punctuation is not part of the word. If you have sentences with punctuation attached to the words or words separated by characters other than spaces, you need to modify the sentence splitting logic accordingly. If capitalization matters, you'll want to convert all words to lower or upper case before putting them into sets.
