Many websites, including this one, add what are apparently called  - descriptive but as far as I can tell useless bits of text - to the end of URLs.

For example, the URL the site gives for this question is:

[https://stackoverflow.com/questions/47427/why-do-some-websites-add-slugs-to-the-end-of-urls](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/47427/why-do-some-websites-add-slugs-to-the-end-of-urls)

But the following URL works just as well:

[https://stackoverflow.com/questions/47427/](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/47427/)

Is the point of this text just to somehow make the URL more user friendly or are there some other benefits?
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Yes, those "useless bits of text" are indeed meant to make the URL more user-friendly. They are typically referred to as "slugs." Here are a few reasons why websites use them:

1. Improved User Experience: It's easier for users to remember and understand what a page is about if the URL includes meaningful words, rather than just numbers or codes.

2. SEO Benefits: Search engines consider URL slugs as an important ranking factor. If a URL contains relevant keywords, it can help to improve the page's search engine visibility. 

3. Better Click-Through Rates: A URL that clearly indicates what the page is about can potentially attract more clicks. 

4. Shareability: They are easier and more intuitive to share, be it on social media or in an email; a recipient would be more inclined to click a link that gives them an idea about the content.
   
5. Analytics: When looking at analytics data or logs, descriptive slugs make it easier to identify and understand the traffic to different posts or pages on a website.

So, while it may indeed work just as well to omit the slug, it plays a significant role in user experience and SEO optimization. Therefore, most websites opt to keep them.
<|end|>


