My question is based on a previews post:
[How to train LSTM model on multiple time series data?](https://stats.stackexchange.com/questions/305863/how-to-train-lstm-model-on-multiple-time-series-data) .
The task is basically the same. However, my question builds on that: What does the model architecture look like for the Proposed Solution ? Does the agent_id have to be entered individually into the embedding layer and then linked to the other features, or are the other agent features also simply pushed into the embedding layer?  If someone has a code snippet that would be great!
<|end|>
<|asst|>
The architecture would very much depend on the exact dataset and task. However, generally, the way to handle categorical variables such as agent_id would be indeed to use an Embedding layer.

Here's an abstract picture of what the model might look like:

```
agent_id -> Embedding -> Flatten -> \
                                  LSTM -> Dense -> Output
other_features -------------------> /
```

This is the code snippet that should implement such kind of architecture:

```python
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Input, Embedding, LSTM, Dense, Flatten
from tensorflow.keras.models import Model
from tensorflow.keras.optimizers import Adam

# Assuming every agent_id is an integer in [0, N]
N = 1000 # The number of distinct agent_ids
D = 10 # The length of agent embeddings

agent_id_input = Input(shape=(1,), name='agent_id')
embed = Embedding(N+1, D)(agent_id_input)
flattened_embed = Flatten()(embed)

sequence_input = Input(shape=(10,1), name='sequence')  # Adjust this to your actual sequence shape
merged = Concatenate(axis=-1)([flattened_embed, sequence_input])

lstm = LSTM(10)(merged)
output = Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')(lstm)

model = Model(inputs=[agent_id_input, sequence_input], outputs=output)

model.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', 
              optimizer=Adam(0.01),
              metrics=['accuracy'])
```

Please remember to adjust N, D, and the shape of sequence_input to match your actual situation.

This code will concatenate the embeddings of agent_ids and the other time-series features before feeding them into the LSTM layer.

Note that if your "other features" aren't time-series (unlike agent_id), then you might want to concatenate on the second dimension after the LSTM as well.

```python
agent_id -> Embedding -> Flatten -> \
                                  Dense -> Output
sequence -> LSTM ----------------> /
```

In this case, non-time-series features do not pass through the LSTM, and the model might look like this:

```python
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Concatenate

sequence_input = Input(shape=(10,1), name='sequence')  # Adjust this to your actual sequence shape
sequence_features = LSTM(10)(sequence_input)

merged = Concatenate(axis=-1)([flattened_embed, sequence_features])

output = Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')(merged)
```

This way, both time-series and non-time-series features are considered separately until the final Dense layer, which might be a better approach depending on your data.
<|end|>


