The official documentation seems to be light on explanations of 'how to understand the SproutCore way' e. g., why things are done the way they are, how to intuit what to do from where you're at, etc.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
It’s true that learning to use a new framework, especially one as complex as SproutCore, can be challenging when the documentation isn’t as thorough or organized as you would like. 

SproutCore is based on key-value coding (KVC) and key-value observing (KVO) concepts - principles familiar to developers with Objective-C/Cocoa experience but possibly alien to those from a pure JavaScript background. It creates a powerful binding model but takes some time to grasp and use effectively. 

Its development approach also involves heavy use of the MVC (Model, View, Controller) design pattern, according to which your application should be divided into three interconnected parts. This architectural pattern encourages well-organized, manageable, and scalable code, but it can be difficult to get to grips with if you're not already familiar with it. 

So, one of the best ways to understand the SproutCore way is to firstly get comfortable with these overarching concepts (KVC, KVO, MVC). 

Additionally, remember that spending time reading existing codebases (on GitHub, for example) can be just as valuable as reading and following tutorials and guides, if not more so. This can give you a first-hand look at how the concepts you're learning are applied in real-world situations. 

Look for open-source projects or even your own old projects, and review the code. You can even try to replicate them in SproutCore or rewrite parts of them as SproutCore components to better understand how the architecture works.

Lastly, don't hesitate to be a part of community, engage in forums/communities dedicated for SproutCore. This will give a lot of perspective by seeing problems/issues faced by other developers and how they are solving them. This way, a lot of your queries will get resolved even before they arise.

Hope these suggestions help you understand 'the SproutCore way'. Happy learning!
<|end|>


