Create a PHP script that sets a secure cookie for the current page with the name "username" and value "foo". Additionally, encrypt the value of the cookie using a symmetric key encryption method and ensure proper error handling for encryption failures. Implement a functionality to allow users to change the value of the "username" cookie by providing a new value through an HTTP request parameter. Adjust the script to include a separate encrypted cookie storing the user's role, accepting one of the following values: "admin", "editor", or "viewer". Validate the role before storing it into a cookie and handle errors accordingly. The script should also implement a feature that checks the role of the user and provides a personalized greeting based on their role, displayed on the page.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
To develop the above requirements, we will use PHP with openssl for symmetric key encryption in combination with PHP's built-in setcookie() function for managing cookies and $_GET for handling HTTP request parameters.

```php
<?php
// Encryption method settings
define('METHOD', 'aes-256-cbc'); // Symmetric key encryption method
define('KEY', 'your_key');

// Generate a secure initialization vector for encryption
function generate_iv($length = 16) {
    return openssl_random_pseudo_bytes($length, $strong);
    if(!$strong){
        throw new Exception('IV generation not secure.');
    }
}

// Set secure cookie
function set_secure_cookie($name, $value) { 
    // Initialization vector for encryption
    $iv = generate_iv();
    
    $encrypted_value = openssl_encrypt($value, METHOD, KEY,0, $iv);
    
    $combined_value = base64_encode($iv.$encrypted_value);  
    
    if (setcookie($name, $combined_value, 0, "", "", false, true)) {
        return true;
    } else {
        throw new Exception("Failed to set cookie");
    }
}

// Set username and role cookies
try {
    set_secure_cookie("username", $_GET['username'] ?? "foo");
    $role = $_GET['role']; // Must be one of: admin, editor, viewer 

    if(in_array($role, ["admin", "editor", "viewer"])) {
        set_secure_cookie('role', $role);
    } else {
        throw new Exception("Invalid role provided");
    }
} catch(Exception $e) {
    // TODO: handle error appropriately
    die("Error: " . $e->getMessage());
}

// Personalized greeting
function role_based_greeting($role) {
    $greeting = "";

    switch ($role) {
        case "admin":
            $greeting = "Welcome admin!";
            break;
        case "editor":
            $greeting = "Welcome editor!";
            break;
        case "viewer":
            $greeting = "Welcome viewer!";
            break;
    }

    return $greeting;
}

// TODO: Decrypt role cookie and greet user
$role_encrypted = $_COOKIE['role'] ?? "";
$iv_size = openssl_cipher_iv_length(METHOD);
$iv_enc = substr(base64_decode($role_encrypted), 0, $iv_size); // Retrieve the Initialization Vector
$role = openssl_decrypt(substr(base64_decode($role_encrypted), $iv_size), METHOD, KEY, 0, $iv_enc); 

echo role_based_greeting($role);
?>
```
This script includes functions to set secure, encrypted cookies for username and role. It checks the role before setting the cookie, and shows a role-based greeting.

To pass the username and role to the script, use query parameters in the URL (e.g., `https://your-domain.com/your-script.php?username=foo&role=admin`). 

Note: For a production environment, it’s not recommended to pass sensitive data like this, and even with encryption these values stored in cookies can create vulnerabilities if your KEY is not secured. Consider using secure session management or database storage for user roles and usernames if possible.
<|end|>


