<|asst|>
The `html()` function in jQuery should return the html entity as a string. 

However, the issue you are facing might be due to using the Unicode arrow symbols - "&uArr;" and "&dArr;" to compare. These are actually represented as double up and double down arrows respectively. So `arrow == "&dArr;"` test might be failing always.

So, you may need to use single up and down arrow symbols, which are represented as "&uarr;" and "&darr;" respectively:

```javascript
function expandCollapse(id) {   
    var arrow = $("#"+id+" span").html(); 
    if(arrow == "&darr;") {     
        $("#"+id+" span").html("&uarr;");               
    } else {        
        $("#"+id+" span").html("&darr;");               
    }
}
```

If you want to keep using double arrows then you need to compare `arrow` variable with characters representing double arrows.

You may use `&uArr;` (double up arrow) which corresponds to character '⇑' and `&dArr;` (double down arrow) which corresponds to character '⇓'.

```javascript
function expandCollapse(id) {   
    var arrow = $("#"+id+" span").html(); 
    if(arrow == '⇓') {     
        $("#"+id+" span").html('⇑');               
    } else {        
        $("#"+id+" span").html('⇓');               
    }
}
```
