<|asst|>
Your intuition goes along the right path. 

In the Markowitz framework, the minimum variance frontier (also known as efficient frontier) shows the set of portfolios that will give the highest expected return for a given level of risk or the lowest risk for a given level of expected returns. The minimum variance frontier is formed by using all assets in the investment universe. When the universe is larger, there are more potential combinations of assets to minimize the overall risk, hence moving the frontier to the left.

In a formal setting, you can use the characteristics of convex sets to prove your claim. The set of feasible portfolios is a convex set, and adding an asset expands this set. That's because every portfolio can still be created, and new ones arise by investing in the additional asset. Thus, the new minimum variance frontier contains the old one (Portfolio with N-1 assets) and the rest of the portfolios which involves new asset. 

So your hypothesis is correct: The MV frontier generated by N assets dominates that generated by N-1 assets.

However, this does not imply that the global minimum variance portfolio gmv_N < gmv_(N-1). Only if the new asset has a risk-return trade off better than the existing assets gmv_N < gmv_(N-1).

If you want to verify this effect empirically, you can perform a backtest by constructing the minimum variance portfolios with a different number of assets at each period, then tracking and comparing their performances.
<|end|>


