I have a Java application which I want to shutdown 'nicely' when the user selects Start->Shutdown. I've tried using JVM shutdown listeners via Runtime.addShutdownHook(...) but this doesn't work as I can't use any UI elements from it.

I've also tried using the exit handler on my main application UI window but it has no way to pause or halt shutdown as far as I can tell. How can I handle shutdown nicely?
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Unfortunately, Java doesn't provide a clear way to handle system shutdown events and it is particularly hard in handling any UI tasks in that scenario. As per the documentation, JVM shutdown is initiated by either a program exit or by use of Ctrl+C on the command line. It's also initiated by system shutdown, but this will be platform and situation-specific because system translates a shutdown event into a kill signal to the JVM process and it might not have enough time to properly execute registered hooks before actual process termination.

Here are a few workaround suggestions:

1. Write a Service: One possibility is to write a service (Windows Service, *nix daemon). This service will run in background and catch the system shutdown event. On this event, it will send a message to your running Java application which, on receiving the message, will start the shutdown sequence. 

2. Native Solution: Use Java Native Interface (JNI) to handle platform specific system call or system hooks to handle the shutdown nicely.

3. JavaFX Platform: If you're using JavaFX for your app, it allows you to catch the close event on the main application window and handle it there.

Remember to keep in mind that system shutting down is a critical situation where a user probably don't want to wait for an application for too long. Never force the system to wait indefinitely for the app to shut down, always have a timeout to force close the app if it fails to shut down nicely in a certain amount of time. 

These solutions are advanced and require a significant understanding of working of Java with system level events and tasks. May not be directly supported and may have risks and challenges.
<|end|>


