<|user|>
&lt;p&gt;
Consider the character set $A$ constructed from the distinct characters of the term "$\text{project}$": $A=\{\text c,\text e,\text j,\text o,\text p,\text r,\text t\}$.&lt;br&gt;
Let $T(n)$ represent the quantity of character sequences of length $n$ composed of characters from $A$ that do not contain a subsequence equivalent to any of the $5040$ permutations of "$\text{project}$".
&lt;/p&gt;
$T(7)=7^7-7!=818503$.

&lt;p&gt;
Determine $T(10^{12})$. Provide the final $9$ digits of your solution.
&lt;/p&gt;
<|end|>
<|asst|>
The given question has a vast scale, thus we cannot find each sequence individually and remove the ones that contain a subsequence equivalent to any of the 5040 permutations of "project". This will be very time-consuming and not feasible. 

Therefore, we need to consider the problem as an inclusion-exclusion problem.

Considering all sequences of length n, there are 7^n possible sequences. We want to subtract out the sequences which contain a subsequence equivalent to a permutation of "project".

However, we have to consider that some sequences may contain more than one subsequence equivalent to a permutation of "project". Therefore, we cannot simply subtract the quantity of sequences containing a permutation of "project" from the total.

Instead, we subtract the sequences containing one permutation, then add back in the sequences containing two permutations (since we would have over-counted the sequences containing more than one permutation), and then subtract the sequences containing three permutations, and so on. This is the principle of Inclusion-Exclusion.

To implement this in Python, we generate a list of factorials since we will need them in our calculations. The count of each type of sequences (sequences containing 1 permutation, 2 permutations, etc) is given by (n choose k) * (k factorial) * (7^(n-k)). We can calculate n choose k iteratively as we go through each k. To get the last 9 digits, we reduce our calculations modulo 10^9 at each step to make our computations manageable.

Here is the python code that implements this:

```Python
mod = 10**9
fact = [1]
for i in range(1,8):
    fact.append((fact[-1]*i)%mod)
fact.append((fact[-1]*7)%mod)
for i in range(9,10**12+1):
    fact.append((fact[-1]*7)%mod)
n = 10**12
ans = 0
c = 1
for i in range(1,min(9,n+1)):
    c = c*(n-i+1)%mod*pow(i,mod-2,mod)%mod
    ans = (ans+c*fact[i])%mod
print(ans)
```
The script calculates the factorial of numbers from 1 to 10^12 (mod 10^9) and then applies the principle of Inclusion-Exclusion to compute the final result.
<|end|>


