My /wallet page api request in getServerSideProps falls on timeout. Even when the client goes to another route in nav bar for Link /wallet page getServerSideProps still continues and complete the request redirect to /wallet page again. How can i terminate getServerSideProps when it client goes to another route?

export async function getServerSideProps(context) {
    try {
        const smartcard = await axiosServer.get(`/user/wallet/${context.params.id}`);

        try {
            const transactions = await axiosServer.get(`/user/wallet/${context.params.id}/transactions`);
            return {
                props: {
                    wallet: wallet.data,
                    transactions : transactions.data,
                },
            };
        } catch (e) {
            return {
                props: {
                    wallet: wallet.data,
                    transactions: {},
                },
            };
        }
    } catch (e) {
        return {
            props: {},
        };
    }
}
<|end|>
<|asst|>
In Next.js, the `getServerSideProps` is always executed server-side, and there's no built-in way to cancel or stop its execution. It will always run to completion because it runs on the server side - even when the user navigates away, the execution continues.

It's recommended to make your `getServerSideProps` as efficient as possible to prevent long running processes or timeouts. If a particular API call or action is notably slow, you might consider:

1. Moving the slow operation to the client side, making the request from the client after page load, and handling loading states accordingly.
2. Implementing some sort of caching for the results of the operation, so that consecutive calls are faster.
3. Increasing your server resources, which can reduce the time taken to process requests.
  
Also, the catch blocks in your `getServerSideProps` might not behaving as intended. When the `smartcard` request fails, the execution goes to the first catch block and attempts to return `wallet.data`, but `wallet` isn't defined in that scope (only `smartcard`). This would probably lead to a ReferenceError. I would review the error handling strategy in this function to make sure it behaves as intended.

If you have some operations that are really time consuming and you have no other option but to do them server-side, you might want to look into next.js `Incremental Static Regeneration` feature, or explore a strategy involving background tasks.
<|end|>


