You can make part of an SVG semi-transparent by adding opacity to a specific `<path>` in the SVG element. The opacity property ranges from 0 to 1, where 0 means total transparency and 1 means fully opaque.

Here's an example of how to do this:

In the SVG markup, you can see several `<path>` elements each having a `fill` property that sets its color. To set the transparency, add the `opacity` attribute to the `path` you want to make semi-transparent. The value of the `opacity` attribute should be between 0 (completely transparent) and 1 (completely opaque).

For example, to make the 2nd path semi-transparent, add `opacity="0.5"` to it:

```SVG
<path d="M28.12 30H3.88C2.84 30 2 29.16 2 28.12V11.88C2 10.84 2.84 10 3.88 10H11L19 8L27 10H28.13C29.16 10 30 10.84 30 11.88V28.13C30 29.16 29.16 30 28.12 30Z" fill="#533566" opacity="0.5"/>
```

In this case, the `opacity` is set to 0.5, which will make the path 50% transparent.

You can do the same for any other paths, either making them entirely or partially transparent depending on the value you set. The same method would work for all SVG elements, not just paths.
<|end|>


