<|asst|>
Here's how you would do the equivalent in Perl. Perl has significantly different syntax from Go, but the overall logic is the same.

```perl
use strict;
use warnings;
use List::Util 'reduce';

# Defines a subroutine (equivalent to a function) named 'unique_digits'
sub unique_digits {
    my @x = @_;  # @x contains all arguments passed to the subroutine

    my @result;

    # Iterates through each element in @x
    foreach my $num (@x) {
        # Calls the subroutine 'all_digits_odd' with $num as the argument
        if (all_digits_odd($num)) {
            push @result, $num;  # Appends $num to @result
        }
    }

    # Perl does not have an inbuilt sorting function for numbers
    # Hence, a Sorted array is returned using sort function
    my @sorted = sort {$a <=> $b} @result;

    return @sorted;
}

# Defines a subroutine named 'all_digits_odd'
sub all_digits_odd {
    my $n = shift;  # Retrieves the first number passed to the subroutine

    # Uses a loop to keep removing the last digit from $n
    while ($n > 0) {
        # Checks if the last digit is even
        if (($n % 10) % 2 == 0) {
            # If we found an even digit, we return 0 (which is false in Perl)
            return 0;
        }
        $n = int($n / 10);
    }

    # If we got here, all digits were odd, so we return 1 (which is true in Perl)
    return 1;
}
```

Note that in Perl, the "return" statement is optional at the end of a subroutine; whatever the last statement in the subroutine evaluates to, is returned by default. This is why you don't see the "return" statement in the 'unique_digits' subroutine for the sorted array. `int` function in perl `int($num/10)` is used to imitate the floor division `num/10` as Perl does floating division by default unlike Go.
<|end|>


