The software should also be able to detect and manage the compatibility of different versions of OpenGL and Metal, and provide a mechanism to update or downgrade the OpenGL or Metal version if necessary. Include error handling for unsupported GPUs, generations, desktop operating systems, OpenGL and Metal versions.

Moreover, the software should be able to provide detailed reports on the performance of OpenGL and Metal-based applications, including but not limited to frame rate, memory usage, CPU usage, and GPU usage. The software should also provide recommendations on how to optimize the performance of these applications based on the detected GPU, generation, desktop operating system, OpenGL or Metal version, and the specific CPU model.

Additionally, the software should be able to simulate different GPU, CPU, and operating system environments to test the performance and compatibility of OpenGL and Metal-based applications. The software should also provide a user-friendly interface for managing these simulations and interpreting the results.

To increase the difficulty, the software should also be able to predict the performance of OpenGL and Metal-based applications on future GPU and CPU models based on their specifications and the trends in their development. The software should also be able to simulate these future environments and provide recommendations on how to optimize the performance of these applications in these environments.

Furthermore, the software should be able to detect and manage the compatibility of different versions of other graphics APIs, such as DirectX and Vulkan, and provide a mechanism to update or downgrade these versions if necessary. The software should also be able to provide detailed reports on the performance of applications based on these APIs, and provide recommendations on how to optimize their performance based on the detected GPU, generation, desktop operating system, API version, and the specific CPU model.

Finally, the software should be able to simulate different network environments to test the performance and compatibility of online applications, and provide a user-friendly interface for managing these simulations and interpreting the results. The software should also be able to detect and manage the compatibility of different versions of network protocols, such as TCP and UDP, and provide a mechanism to update or downgrade these versions if necessary.
