What value of ICC should I use when calculating the effective sample size of clustered data?
A previous publication conducting a similar study reported ICCs of 0.04 for the full mixed model (random intercept plus individual and household-level variables) and 0.19 for the null model (only the intercept term).
Which value should I use to calculate the effective sample size in my study? In terms of structure, their full model most closely resembles the data structure of the model I am working with, so my gut feeling is 0.04, but I am uncertain.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Intraclass correlation (ICC) indicates the proportion of total variation in a measurement that is due to group (or cluster) variation. If your study's analysis model will include both individual and household level variables like the full model in the previous study, then it would be appropriate to use the lower ICC value (0.04) for your effective sample size calculations. 

This is because the lower ICC reflects the decrease in correlation among cluster members (after accounting for individual and household level variables) compared to the null model which only included the intercept.

However, it's important to note that effective sample size calculations can be sensitive to the ICC assumed, so it might be helpful to do sensitivity analyses under a range of plausible ICC values just to understand how it might affect your results.
<|end|>


