Here is an example of how you can create an interactive webpage to count the views of a URL in HTML and JavaScript. Note that the following code will only work if you have a server-side script (e.g., Express/Node.js, Flask, Django, etc.) that can handle this GET request and respond with the correct count. For the purposes of this example, we'll use a dummy URL, replace it with your server-side script URL.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Page View Counter</title>
    <script src="https://ajax.googleapis.com/ajax/libs/jquery/3.5.1/jquery.min.js"></script>
</head>
<body>

<h1>Website View Counter</h1>

<form id="urlForm">
  <label for="url">Enter the URL:</label><br>
  <input type="text" id="url" name="url" required><br>
  <input type="submit" value="Submit">
  <p id="msg"></p>
</form>

<script>
$(document).ready(function(){
  
  // Listen for form submission
  $("#urlForm").on('submit', function(e){

    // Prevent default form submission behavior
    e.preventDefault();

    // Fetch URL to lookup from the form input
    const url = $('#url').val();  
    
    // Send an AJAX GET request to server with url in query parameter
    $.get('https://myserver.com/pageview?target=' + encodeURIComponent(url), function(data) {
            // Insert the returned count into the msg paragraph
            $('#msg').html('The page has been viewed ' + data.count + ' times.');
        })
        .fail(function() {
            // If the request fails, display an error message
            $('#msg').html('An error occurred while trying to fetch the page view count.');
        });  
  }); 
});
</script>
</body>
</html>
```
The server-side handling depends on your backend language. Basically, you need to catch the GET request on '/pageview' endpoint, decode the URL, look up views in your database, and send the count back as a JSON. Here is an example of how you could handle this in an Express/Node.js application with a fictitious db object representing your database (you will need to replace it with actual database logic):

```js
const express = require('express')
const app = express()
const port = 3000

app.get('/pageview', (req, res) => {
  const targetUrl = decodeURIComponent(req.query.target);
  
  db.getPageViews(targetUrl)
    .then(count => {
      res.json({count: count});
    })
    .catch(err => {
      res.status(500).json({error: err.message});
    });
})

app.listen(port, () => {
  console.log(`Server running at http://localhost:${port}`)
})
```
There are many security considerations and improvements can be done, this is just a simple mockup for demonstration purposes.
