<|user|>
Employ JavaScript programming language to devise a function whose solitary task is to yield all the mathematical divisors, not including the original number itself, of any provided numeral. You've been given 12 as the initial numerical input.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Here's a simple JavaScript function that does exactly that:

```js
function findDivisors(n) {
    var divisors = [];
    for (var i = 1; i <= Math.floor(Math.sqrt(n)); i++) {
        if (n % i === 0) {
            divisors.push(i);
            if (n / i !== i && n/i !== n) {
                divisors.push(n / i);
            }
        }
    }
    return divisors;
}

console.log(findDivisors(12)); // Outputs: [1, 12, 2, 6, 3, 4]
```

This function works by looping from 1 to the square root of the number (since no divisor can be larger than the square root), and checking each number to see if it's a divisor (i.e., if the remainder when the number is divided by it is zero). If a divisor is found, it's added to the 'divisors' array. The function finally returns this array.
<|end|>


