<|user|>
What's the best way in c# to determine is a given QFE/patch has been installed?
<|end|>
<|asst|>
You can use the Windows Management Instrumentation (WMI) classes in C# to query the list of installed patches on the system and look for a specific one. Here is a simple example:

```csharp
using System;
using System.Management;

class Program
{
    static void Main(string[] args)
    {
        ManagementObjectSearcher searcher = new ManagementObjectSearcher("SELECT * FROM Win32_QuickFixEngineering");
        foreach (ManagementObject quickFix in searcher.Get())
        {
            string hotFixID = quickFix["HotFixID"].ToString();
            if(hotFixID == "KBxxxxx") // Replace KBxxxxx with the QFE/patch ID you need
            {
                Console.WriteLine("Patch is installed");
                return;
            }
        }
        Console.WriteLine("Patch is not installed");
    }
}
```
In this code, "KBxxxxx" should be replaced with the ID of the patch you are looking for. The code scans through all installed patches and outputs a message if it finds the patch.

Please note, this code requires the `System.Management` namespace. If it's not available, you have to add reference to `System.Management` in your project. 

Also, this approach requires that your program run with administrative rights, and might not work for all Quick Fix Engineering (QFE) patches, as not all patches are registered in Win32_QuickFixEngineering. 

Lastly, WMI may not be the most reliable or performant way to acquire this information as it heavily depends on how well the provider for specific classes (here `Win32_QuickFixEngineering`) is implemented. If performance is a concern, you might want to use OS built-in tooling (e.g: `systeminfo.exe`) or third-party libraries designed for system info retrieval.
<|end|>


