We're at the beginning of a new ERP-ish client-server application, developed as a Python rich client.  We're currently evaluating Dabo as our main framework and it looks quite nice and easy to use, but I was wondering, has anyone used it for medium-to-big sized projects?
Thanks for your time!
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Dabo might not be as popular as some other Python frameworks like Django or Flask. However, it is designed to be an application development platform mainly used by business database application developers. This means it has been framed with database-centric applications in mind, such as ERP solutions.

It does have a large base of developers who actively contribute to its development. Several applications are built using Dabo, ranging from small scale to extensive projects. It is an effective tool for developing cross-platform applications, especially desktop applications.

However, your decision should depend on the specific requirements of your project and team's skill set. Dabo provides a flexibility that might be particularly beneficial if your application requires rich client-side functionality with a Python-heavy tech stack. However, if your team is comfortable with a more "web-standard" approach (HTML, CSS, Javascript, etc.), something like Django or Flask might be more suitable. The size of the project is not an issue with any of these tools - they can all handle "medium-to-big" sized applications with appropriate engineering.

Also worth considering is the community support and available resources for learning and troubleshooting. Dabo's smaller community might make finding specific solutions or guidance a bit challenging as compared to giants like Django or Flask.

To sum up, while Dabo can certainly be used for medium-to-large projects, it is important to consider whether it's the best fit based on the project needs and team expertise.
<|end|>


