I'm having trouble coming up with the correct regex string to remove a sequence of multiple ? characters. I want to replace more than one sequential ? with a single ?, but which characters to escape...is escaping me.

Example input:

> Is this thing on??? or what???

Desired output:

> Is this thing on? or what?

I'm using [preg_replace()](http://php.net/preg_replace) in PHP.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
You want to replace any occurrence of more than one '?' with a single '?'. 

Here is a way to do it using regular expressions with the `preg_replace()` function in PHP:

```php
$input = "Is this thing on??? or what???";
$output = preg_replace('/\?+/', '?', $input);
echo $output;
```

The `/\?+/` is the regex pattern that will match one or more '?' characters. 

- The `\?` is necessary to escape the '?' character, which is a special character in regex.
- The `+` is a quantifier in regex that means "one or more of the preceding element", so `\?+` matches one or more '?' characters.
<|end|>


