Is there some way I can use URLs like: 

[http://www.blog.com/team-spirit/](http://www.blog.com/team-spirit/)

instead of

[http://www.blog.com/?p=122](http://www.blog.com/?p=122)

in a Windows hosted PHP server?
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Yes, this can be achieved by using a process known as URL Rewriting.

URL Rewriting can convert dynamic URLs to static URLs and vice versa. You could use it to change your URL from "http://www.blog.com/?p=122" to "http://www.blog.com/team-spirit/".

When using a Windows Server and Internet Information Services (IIS), you'll need to use the URL Rewrite module. Here's how you can do that:

1. Install the URL Rewrite Module, if it is not already installed.

2. Using the IIS Manager, open the URL Rewrite feature.

3. Click "Add Rule(s)" and create the necessary rules to rewrite your URLs.

Here is a simple example of how the rules might look like in your `Web.Config` in XML format:

```xml
<rewrite>
    <rules>
        <rule name="Rewrite to article.php">
            <match url="^article/([0-9]+)/?$" />
            <conditions>
                <add input="{REQUEST_FILENAME}" matchType="IsFile" negate="true" />
                <add input="{REQUEST_FILENAME}" matchType="IsDirectory" negate="true" />
            </conditions>
            <action type="Rewrite" url="article.php?id={R:1}" />
        </rule>
    </rules>
</rewrite>
```

This would rewrite "www.blog.com/article.php?id=122" to "www.blog.com/article/122". You would need to adjust this based on the specifics of your site and its structure.

Please note this process requires knowledge of regular expressions and the rewrite module rules and functions. If the settings are configured incorrectly, they can potentially bring down your website or cause unexpected behavior.

Apart from URL Rewriting, changing URL structure often involves modifications in the code base, specifically at places which generate URLs. You will need to modify the code to ensure that the newly rewritten URLs being generated are correct and follow the structure you've defined.

Also, remember to make sure that the new URLs are properly redirected using 301 redirection from the old URLs to maintain SEO indexing.
<|end|>


