I'm trying to split my data into a testing and a training set. There are lots of variables that I want to ensure are well represented in both the training and testing sets (say, 15 covariates). But when I go to sample using `rsample::initial_split()`, it tells me: "Stratifying groups that make up [less than] 10% of the data may be statistically risky."
Theoretically, can someone explain why such a thing would be risky? I am aware that I can override this with `pool = 0`, I'm just trying to understand the concept here.
Update: Assume it is appropriate to do a test/train split based on the size of the data (many observations).
<|end|>
<|asst|>
The warning message is indicating that when you stratify (divide into groups) based on variables that make up less than 10% of your data, you're likely to have too few instances of that variable in your test or training set. This can be statistically risky because:

1. It can lead to imbalances in your training and testing dataset: Stratifying on a variety of variables can result in highly skewed splits where some categories of these variables end up being over-represented or under-represented. This can offer some groups more influence in the final model than others, which wouldn't be representative of an accurate model.

2. Too few instances can have impacts on the predictive power: If a category only has a few instances and they all end up in the training set (or vice versa), then your model won't have information on how to predict this category when it encounters it in the testing data (or in any future unseen data).

3. It increases the variance and unstable estimates: With too small samples, the variability in estimates of the model parameters will increase which can lead to unstable and unreliable predictions.

4. Overfitting: If your training set contains too few instances of a certain category, the model might learn patterns specific to these instances that don't generalize well to new data. This is an overfitting issue.

Overall, the sufficiency of your sample size to represent all categories of your variables is crucial to building a stable and generalizing model. Hence, division into groups should ideally involve categories that have substantial representations in your dataset.
<|end|>


