<|user|>
Is there are way to make ID fiels in MySql immutable?
It's possible in postgreSQL using PGAdmin for example.
ID field sets as primary key and auto incr but can be changed manually.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
While MySQL doesn't have an inbuilt feature to make a column immutable as PostgreSQL, it can still be achieved indirectly by using TRIGGER. You can set up a Trigger that would rollback any UPDATE commands tried on ID field. 

Here is an example of how you can do it:

```sql
CREATE TRIGGER immutable_id
BEFORE UPDATE ON your_table
FOR EACH ROW
    BEGIN
        IF NEW.id != OLD.id THEN
            SIGNAL SQLSTATE '45000'
            SET MESSAGE_TEXT = 'Cannot modify ID field';
        END IF;
    END;
```

In this code: your_table is where you want ID field to be immutable. Whenever an UPDATE event tries to change the value of ID Field, the TRIGGER automatically rolls it back, essentially making your ID field immutable.

Remember to replace 'your_table' with the actual table name.

Please note that this will prevent updates to the ID field, but it will not prevent direct deletions or insertions. Also, be aware that SIGNAL is only available from MySQL version 5.5 onwards.
<|end|>


