I am working on e-commerce like app. I have orderItem Schema

const orderItemsSchema = mongoose.Schema(
  {
    order: {
      type: mongoose.Schema.Types.ObjectId,
      ref: 'OrderItems',
      required: true,
    },
    product: {
      type: mongoose.Schema.Types.ObjectId,
      ref: 'Products',
      required: true,
    },
    quantity: {
      type: Number,
      default: 1,
    },
    subCost: {
      type: Number,
      required: true,
    },
  },
  {
    timestamps: true,
  }
);


Where product schema has a field "owner" which is also a reference.
I am expecting to get orderItems based on owners of the products.
For Example: A owner want to check which products of him has been sold. So he will query orderItems to get his sold items.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
To achieve your goal, you can use Mongoose's "populate" method to get related product data, then filter your result by owner Id.
Here is how you can do it:

```js
import OrderItem from "./models/orderItem";

// owner's id
let ownerId = '...';

OrderItem.find({})
    .populate({
        path: 'product',
        match: { owner: ownerId }  // filter
    })
    .exec((error, orderItems) => {
        if (error) {
            // handle error
            console.log(error);
            return;
        }

        // Filter out the items whose product is null after population
        orderItems = orderItems.filter(orderItem => orderItem.product != null);
        console.log(orderItems);
    });
```

This will find all OrderItems, populate their product fields, and only keep the products whose owner matches the provided ownerId. Then it filters out all populated OrderItems that had no matching product. 

Using the match option in populate can result in null populated paths (if they don't meet the condition), hence the need to filter out afterward.

This will return all the OrderItems which were placed for the products owned by the given ownerId.
<|end|>


