Write a JavaScript program that logs to the console a unique random number between 0 and 10, each time the program is run. Numbers cannot be repeated until all possible have been generated.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
There are a number of ways to achieve this, but most of them aren't straightforward or possible purely with JavaScript. You may need to use browser storage, like localStorage, to persist check on already generated numbers across different runs but it only works in a browser not on runtime of individual executions like in server-side Node.js. 

Here's an example where we serialize the tracker to localStorage:

```JavaScript
var min = 0;
var max = 10;

// Get the array if it exists, if not initialize it
var generated = JSON.parse(localStorage.getItem('generated')) || [];

// If all numbers have been generated, reset
if(generated.length == max + 1) {
    generated = [];
}

// Generate unique random numbers
var num;
do {
    num = Math.floor(Math.random() * (max - min + 1)) + min;
} while(generated.includes(num));

// Push the new number and save
generated.push(num);
localStorage.setItem('generated', JSON.stringify(generated));

console.log(num);
```
Remember that this code can only be executed in browser, since localStorage is a part of the Web Storage API meant solely for web browsers.

If you are not bound to use JavaScript, you might want to consider another language that have persistent storage and randomness inbuilt or in case of JavaScript you can create a file stream for tracking generated numbers on server-side(Node.js) executions.
<|end|>


