You can begin by creating a new React Native project using the following command:

```bash
npx react-native init MyApp
```

Once completed, navigate inside the directory of your new app.

Now create a list of users. In this case, we will just hard-code the users inside a file. However, in a real application you would have a database connected to retrieve user information.

```jsx
// Users.js 
const users = [
  {
    email: 'test@test.com',
    password: 'password'
  },
  {
    email: 'example@example.com',
    password: 'example'
  }
];

export default users;
```

Create LoginForm.js where login form will reside:

```jsx
import React, { Component } from 'react';
import { View, Button, TextInput, Alert } from 'react-native';
import users from './Users';

class LoginForm extends Component {

  constructor(props) {
    super(props);

    this.state = {
      email: '',
      password: ''
    };
  }

  handleLogin = () => {
    const {email, password} = this.state;
    if(users.find(user => user.email === email && user.password === password)) {
      this.props.onLogin();
    } else {
      Alert.alert('Error', 'Invalid email or password', [{ text: 'Okay' }]);
    }
  }

  render() {
    return (
      <View>
        <TextInput
          value={this.state.email}
          onChangeText={(email) => this.setState({ email })}
          placeholder={'Email'}
          style={{ height: 44, margin: 20 }}
        />
        <TextInput
          value={this.state.password}
          onChangeText={(password) => this.setState({ password })}
          placeholder={'Password'}
          secureTextEntry={true}
          style={{ height: 44, margin: 20 }}
        />
        <Button
          title={'Login'}
          onPress={this.handleLogin}
        />
      </View>
    );
  }
}

export default LoginForm;
```
Create Dashboard.js which will be displayed upon successful login:

```jsx
import React from 'react';
import { Text, View } from 'react-native';

const Dashboard = () => {
  return (
    <View>
      <Text>Welcome back to my mobile app!</Text>
    </View>
  );
};

export default Dashboard;
```

Finally, in App.js implement a conditional rendering of LoginForm or Dashboard based on the state of isLoggedIn.

```jsx
import React, {Component} from 'react';
import LoginForm from './LoginForm';
import Dashboard from './Dashboard';

class App extends Component {
  constructor(props) {
    super(props);
    this.state = {
      isLoggedIn: false
    };
  }

  handleLogin = () => {
    this.setState({isLoggedIn: true})
  }

  render() {
    if(this.state.isLoggedIn) {
      return <Dashboard/>
    } else {
      return <LoginForm onLogin={this.handleLogin}/>
    }
  }
}

export default App;
```

This basic app should now check for valid login credentials and navigate the user to the dashboard if the given details are valid.
