Edit the given C++ code for reversing a given string, ensuring it works with Unicode characters.
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main() 
{
    string str = "Hello World! äöü";
    cout << str;
    return 0;
}
<|end|>
<|asst|>
In the case, where internationalization comes into play like special German letters ä,ö,ü. You will need a bit more complex solution so as to properly handle Unicode characters. The C++ Standard Library does not directly support for Unicode, but we can make use of some third-party libraries like ICU (International Components for Unicode), Boost.Locale etc. But using these libraries just for string reversal is like overkill so, I'd suggest to use a UTF-8 decoder which can make string reversal for unicode more efficient and faster. Here is an example:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <algorithm>

bool is_utf8_continuation_byte(const char c)
{
    return (c & 0b11000000) == 0b10000000;
}

std::string reverse_string(const std::string& str)
{
    std::string reversed_str;
    for (std::string::const_reverse_iterator it = str.rbegin(); it != str.rend(); ++it)
    {
        if (!is_utf8_continuation_byte(*it))
        {
            reversed_str.append(it.base(), it.base() - 1);
        }
    }

    return reversed_str;
}

int main() 
{
    std::string str = u8"Hello World! äöü";
    str = reverse_string(str);

    std::cout << str;
    return 0;
}
```

This snippet will correctly interpret UTF-8 encoded strings and reverse them correctly according to the graphemes (visual characters) and not the individual UTF-8 bytes. This script checks if a byte is a continuation byte of a Unicode character. If not, it appends the Unicode character to the reversed string.
<|end|>


