Design a Perl program that intricailly filters and identifies any recurring pattern of three distinct lexemes from a given lengthy textual sequence. It should account for any variance of word frequencies and be case-insensitive. 

Sequential combination of characters: "I adore apples but not as much as I adore apricots because apricots are healthier than apples but not as sweet as apples. I suppose it's a good thing that apricots aren't as sweet as apples because then I'd probably like apricots more than apples."
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Creating a perl program for this problem would essentially involve breaking down the text into sequences of three words (lexemes) and maintaining a hash (associative array) for keeping track of the frequencies. Below you will find a simple Perl solution for your problem:

```perl
#!/usr/bin/perl
use strict;
use warnings;
use feature 'say';

# Convert the text into lowercase and split it into words
my $text = "I adore apples but not as much as I adore apricots because apricots are healthier than apples but not as sweet as apples. I suppose it's a good thing that apricots aren't as sweet as apples because then I'd probably like apricots more than apples.";
$text = lc $text;
my @words = split /\s+/, $text;

# Create a hash to track the frequency of each triplet
my %triplets;

for my $i (0 .. $#words - 2) {
    my $triplet = join ' ', @words[$i .. $i+2];
    $triplets{$triplet}++;
}

# Print the triplets that appear more than once
foreach my $triplet (sort { $triplets{$b} <=> $triplets{$a} } keys %triplets) {
    if ($triplets{$triplet} > 1) {
        say "'$triplet' - $triplets{$triplet} times";
    }
}
```

This script will first normalize the input text by converting it to lowercase, then split the text into individual words. It then creates sequences of three words (triplets) and increments a counter for each triplet in a hash. At the end, it sorts and prints the triplets that appear more than once along with their frequency.
<|end|>


