Create a responsive HTML page with a form to input the name, email address, and password of a user. The form should include validation checks for the email and password fields. The email field should check for a valid email format and the password field should check for a minimum length of 8 characters, at least one uppercase letter, one lowercase letter, one number, and one special character. The form should also have a submit button. On submission, the form should display a confirmation message on the same page without refreshing it. Use JavaScript for form validation and handling form submission.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Here's a simple HTML page with a form and JavaScript-based validation:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>User Registration</title>
    <script>
    function validateForm() {
        var name = document.forms["myForm"]["name"].value;
        var email = document.forms["myForm"]["email"].value;
        var password = document.forms["myForm"]["password"].value;

        if (name == "" || email == "" || password == "") {
            alert("All fields must be filled out");
            return false;
        }

        var emailReg = /\S+@\S+\.\S+/;
        if(!emailReg.test(email)) {
            alert("Invalid email format");
            return false;
        }

        var passwordReg = /^(?=.*[a-z])(?=.*[A-Z])(?=.*\d)(?=.*[@$!%*#?&])[A-Za-z\d@$!%*#?&]{8,}$/;
        if(!passwordReg.test(password)) {
            alert("Password must be minimum 8 characters long and should include at least one uppercase letter, one lowercase letter, one number, and one special character");
            return false;
        }
              
        document.getElementById("confirmMessage").innerHTML="Form Submitted Successfully!";
        return false;
    }
    </script>
</head>
<body>
    
    <h2>User Registration Form</h2>
    <form name="myForm" onsubmit="return validateForm()" action="#" method="post">
        <label for="name">Name:</label><br>
        <input type="text" id="name" name="name" required><br>
        <label for="email">Email:</label><br>
        <input type="text" id="email" name="email" required><br>
        <label for="password">Password:</label><br>
        <input type="password" id="password" name="password" required><br>
        <input type="submit" value="Submit">
    </form>

    <p id="confirmMessage"></p>

</body>
</html>
```
This page creates a form that asks for the user's name, email, and password. When the form is submitted, the JavaScript first checks that all fields have been filled. Then, it tests the format of the email with a regular expression, and if it doesn't match the proper format, it shows an alert and stops. If the email format is correct, it checks the format of the password and provides appropriate message if it does not meet the criteria. If all checks pass, it displays a success message. Notice that the page is not actually sent to a server owing to our use of JavaScript's preventDefault. The form submission instead changes some text on the page.
