Given a list of numbers, write a function that returns the index of the minimum element. Additionally, below is a piece of erroneous code provided as a reference. Analyze the code and determine the error to avoid any misdirection. Then, implement the correct solution.

Erroneous code:
```python
def find_min_index(lst):
  min_index = 0
  for i in range(1, len(lst)):
    if lst[i] > lst[min_index]:
      min_index = i
  return min_index
```

Example input:
[22, 11, 13, 66]
<|end|>
<|asst|>
The erroneous code provided has one main mistake: it actually finds the index of the maximum value in this list, instead of the minimum value. This is due to the comparison operator ">" used in the if-statement which compares the current list item with the currently stored minimum value. It should use a "<" operator to identify the minimum number in the list.

Because Python allows negative indexing (which means if you put -1 as an index of a list, Python will return the last element of that list), the function should also handle an edge case when the input list is empty. It will return None in this case.

Here is the corrected function:

```python
def find_min_index(lst):
  if len(lst) == 0:
    return None
  min_index = 0
  for i in range(1, len(lst)):
    if lst[i] < lst[min_index]:
      min_index = i
  return min_index
```

Applying this function to the given example input [22, 11, 13, 66], it will return 1, which is the index of the minimum value in the input list.
<|end|>


