I have my web browsers set to save what I type into text boxes on forms.  I have a lot of search terms stored in the text box of my browser and would like to get at it via a program of some sort before I clear these values out.  There are far too many for me to go through one at a time.  

The web browser must store this data somewhere, does anyone know where?  Is it possible to retrieve these values?   , more so than IE -- but either, if anyone knows a script that can extract these values? Thanks.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
The text box autosuggestions saved in web browsers are known as 'Form History' in Google Chrome and 'Autocomplete Data' in Internet Explorer. 

Here's a method to extract this form history for Chrome:

1. Chrome stores this data in \Google\Chrome\User Data\Default\Web Data SQLite database. To access this file, you'll need an SQLite browser, such as DB Browser for SQLite.
2. Before accessing, make sure Chrome is closed, else you can't open the database file as it will be locked.
3. Once Chrome is closed, open the DB Browser for SQLite and select Open Database.
4. Navigate to the path: \Google\Chrome\User Data\Default\ and choose 'Web Data' file.
5. Click on 'Browse Data' tab, select 'autofill' from the dropdown, you can see all the saved form data.

As for Internet Explorer:

1. Going by the documentation, the Autocomplete data is saved in registry and isn't easily retrievable.
2. Microsoft provides no method to extract this data easily.

Note: Most web browsers cache form history locally, meaning the data isn't particularly easy to access programmatically. It's also worth noting retrieving such information could potentially violate privacy restrictions for some users, so always approach such tasks with a high degree of caution.

Lastly, the autosuggestions saved also depend on the settings of the browser used by the user. If the user disabled this autosuggestions feature, then the method will not work.
<|end|>


