I've worked with T-SQL for years but I've just moved to an organisation that is going to require writing some Oracle stuff, probably just simple CRUD operations at least until I find my feet. I'm not going to be migrating databases from one to the other simply interacting with existing Oracle databases from an Application Development perspective. Is there are tool or utility available to easily translate T-SQL into Oracle SQL, a keyword mapper is the sort of thing I'm looking for.

P.S. I'm too lazy to RTFM, besides it's not going to be a big part of my role so I just want something to get me up to speed a little faster.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
There are several tools that allow you to translate or convert T-SQL into Oracle SQL:

1. SWISSQL tool: It's an automated SQL Migration tool that can instantly convert SQL Server (T-SQL) queries into PL/SQL equivalent. It's a commercial tool though. Their website: http://www.swissql.com/

2. SQLines tool: SQLines provides tools and services to help you transfer data, convert database schema (DDL), views, stored procedures, functions, packages, triggers, queries and SQL scripts from Microsoft SQL Server to Oracle. SQLines tool is free. Their website: http://www.sqlines.com/

3. ISPIRER tool: Ispirer Migration and Modernization Toolkit (Ispirer MnMTK) converts stored procedures, functions, triggers, database schema (DDL) and data from Microsoft SQL Server to Oracle. Their website: http://www.ispirer.com/

4. SQLDeveloper tool: Oracle SQL Developer is a free, integrated development environment that simplifies the development and management of Oracle Database. SQL Developer offers complete end-to-end development of your PL/SQL applications, a worksheet for running queries and scripts, and a DBA console for managing the database. Their website: https://www.oracle.com/tools/downloads/sqldev-v192-downloads.html

Remember to always test the compiled scripts after conversion because there might be some slight differences or errors that these tools might not catch. And of course, these tools can't replace the value of understanding Oracle SQL but should help speed up basic translation tasks.
<|end|>


