Here's a piece of reference code, which you can use as a jumping-off point for building your function. Notice that there are some valid and invalid user objects in the array.

```javascript
var users = [
  {id: 1, name: 'John Doe', email: 'johndoe@example.com'},
  {id: 2, name: '', email: 'emptyname@example.com'},
  {id: 3, name: 'Jane Doe', email: 'janedoe@'},
  {id: 4, name: 'Baby Doe', email: 'babydoe@example.com'},
  {id: 1, name: 'John Doe', email: 'johndoe@example.com'}, //Duplicate
  {id: 5, name: 'Senior Doe', email: 'seniordoe@example'}  //Invalid email
];
```

Your task is to filter out the invalid users and return an array of valid user objects. You can consider an email to be valid if it contains at least one character before and after the '@' symbol, and ends with a domain after '.' such as '.com', '.net', '.org', etc.
