<|asst|>
Here is the JavaScript function that checks each user criteria in the given array of users:

```javascript
function filterValidUsers(users) {
  var uniqueUsers = [];
  var seenIds = {};

  for (var i = 0; i < users.length; i++) {
    var user = users[i];
    var isValidEmail = /^[\w-]+(\.[\w-]+)*@([a-z0-9-]+\.)+[a-z]{2,10}$/i.test(user.email);

    // User ID has not been encountered before, name is not empty, and email is valid
    if (!seenIds[user.id] && user.name && isValidEmail) {
      uniqueUsers.push(user);
      seenIds[user.id] = true;  
    }
  }

  return uniqueUsers;
}

var users = [
  {id: 1, name: 'John Doe', email: 'johndoe@example.com'},
  {id: 2, name: '', email: 'emptyname@example.com'},
  {id: 3, name: 'Jane Doe', email: 'janedoe@'},
  {id: 4, name: 'Baby Doe', email: 'babydoe@example.com'},
  {id: 1, name: 'John Doe', email: 'johndoe@example.com'}, //Duplicate
  {id: 5, name: 'Senior Doe', email: 'seniordoe@example'}  //Invalid email
];

var validUsers = filterValidUsers(users);

console.log(validUsers);
```

The function `filterValidUsers` filters out users that do not have unique IDs, have empty names, or have invalid email addresses. It uses a regular expression to check for a valid email address format. The resulting filtered list only contains valid users. 

Please note that this solution doesn't validate all aspects of an email address, it's a simplified validation only for demonstration purpose. In more realistic scenarios, you may want to use standard libraries like `validator.js` etc.
