<|asst|>
The problem with the provided code is not its inability to handle multiple levels of nesting. Actually, the recursive call of the function handles the multi-level nesting of arrays properly.

The problem lies in the handling of single string within the arrays. The unexpected output occurs when an array contains a single string element. More specifically, the code does not correctly handle arrays where there is a single string along with a nested array. 

The following updated code corrects the above issue:

```php
$array = [[["apple", "banana"], "pear"], "orange"];

function printArray($array){
    if (is_array($array)) {
        foreach($array as $value){
            printArray($value);
        }
    } else {
        echo $array . "\n";
    }
}

printArray($array);
```
This code will produce the following output:

```
apple
banana
pear
orange
```

This properly handles all possible scenarios: arrays, nested arrays, and single string values. It performs recursion whenever an array is found and outputs any individual strings it encounters. By performing a preliminary check to see if the passed parameter is an array, we can avoid any undefined behavior when the parameter is a single string. The addition of "\n" after $array in the echo statement makes each result print on a new line for clarity.
