Below is a python script that does just that using pandas for data handling and matplotlib for data visualization.

```python
# Import necessary libraries
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Read data from the provided CSV file
df = pd.read_csv('https://github.com/organisciak/Python-DS/raw/master/data/winemag_data_first150k.csv')

# Preprocess the data:
# Drop rows with missing 'country' values
df = df.dropna(subset=['country'])

# Analyze 'country' column

## Create the histogram
plt.figure(figsize=[10, 8])
plt.hist([df[df['country'] == country]['points'] for country in df['country'].unique()], stacked=True, bins=10)
plt.title('Points distribution per Country')
plt.xlabel('Points')
plt.ylabel('Frequency')
plt.legend(df['country'].unique(), title='Countries')
plt.show()

## Create the bar chart
plt.figure(figsize=[10, 8])
df['country'].value_counts().plot(kind='bar')
plt.title('Wine counts per Country')
plt.xlabel('Country')
plt.ylabel('Wine counts')
plt.xticks(rotation=90)
plt.show()
```

This script first reads the wines data from the CSV file into a pandas DataFrame. It then drops the rows where the 'country' value is missing (NaN). A histogram is plotted to show the distribution of wine 'points' per country. Notice that the 'bins' argument for plt.hist is set to 10, this means that the range of 'points' has been divided into 10 equal intervals. Stacking is enabled for better visualization when countries have similar points. Then a bar chart is plotted to show the count of wines from each country. Counties on the x-axis are rotated by 90 degrees for better readability as there are many countries to show. Following these steps, all specifications of the task are fulfilled.

