Convert the following JavaScript code snippet into a Promise using the new Promise constructor. Additionally, modify it to handle multiple failed promises using Promise.allSettled. Make sure to handle both fulfilled promises and rejected promises accordingly.

function checkStatus(response) {
    if (response.status >= 200 && response.status < 300) {
        return response.text();
    } else {
        throw new Error(response.statusText);
    }
}
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Here is a way to convert the mentioned function into a promise using the new Promise constructor. And to handle multiple promises, Promise.allSettled is used which settles every promise.

```javascript
function checkStatus(response) {
    return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
        if (response.status >= 200 && response.status < 300) {
            resolve(response.text());
        } else {
            reject(new Error(response.statusText));
        }
    });
}

// Handle multiple promises
const promises = [checkStatus(response1), checkStatus(response2), checkStatus(response3)];

Promise.allSettled(promises)
    .then(results => {
        results.forEach(result => {
            if (result.status === "fulfilled") {
                console.log(result.value);
            } else {
                console.log(result.reason);
            }
        });
    });
```
Please replace `response1`, `response2`, `response3` with actual response objects. This code will now handle the case when multiple promises get rejected and/or resolved. It waits for all promises to settle(i.e either fulfilled or rejected), then logs their response text or error message accordingly.
<|end|>


