Here is an example of how to execute a basic exploratory data analysis on the Boston housing dataset using Python and its libraries such as Scikit-learn, Numpy, Pandas, and Matplotlib. 

We'll focus on critical housing attributes such as median home values, crime rates, and average numbers of rooms per dwelling.

```python
# Importing the libraries
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn import datasets

# Loading the Boston housing dataset
boston = datasets.load_boston()

# Transforming the dataset into a DataFrame
df = pd.DataFrame(boston.data, columns=boston.feature_names)

# Adding the target variable (Median Home Value) to the DataFrame
df['MEDV'] = boston.target

# Displaying the first five rows of the DataFrame
print(df.head())

# Displaying the statistics of the DataFrame
print(df.describe())

# Analyzing the correlation between the MEDV, CRIM, and RM attributes
corr_medv_crim = df['MEDV'].corr(df['CRIM'])
corr_medv_rm = df['MEDV'].corr(df['RM'])
print('Correlation between median home values and crime rate:', corr_medv_crim)
print('Correlation between median home values and average number of rooms:', corr_medv_rm)

# Visualizing the relationship between MEDV and CRIM
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
plt.scatter(df['CRIM'], df['MEDV'])
plt.title('Crime Rate vs Median Home Value')
plt.xlabel('Crime Rate')
plt.ylabel('Median Home Value')
plt.show()

# Visualizing the relationship between MEDV and RM
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
plt.scatter(df['RM'], df['MEDV'])
plt.title('Average Number of Rooms vs Median Home Value')
plt.xlabel('Average Number of Rooms')
plt.ylabel('Median Home Value')
plt.show()
```

This script will load the dataset, convert it to a pandas DataFrame, print out the first five rows and some basic statistics of the data. 

The script calculates the correlation between the average number of rooms per dwelling (RM), medv (Median value of owner-occupied homes in $1000's) and crime rates per capita (CRIM). 

The matplotlib library makes two scatter plots displaying the relationship between the median value of homes and the crime rate, and between the median value of homes and the average number of rooms, respectively. 

Remember that in a scatter plot, a positive slope shows a positive correlation and a negative slope shows a negative correlation. If the plot seems to form a line (either increasing or decreasing), there is high linear correlation. 

Based on the correlation values calculated from data analysis, you can also understand the relationship between different features - a correlation closer to 1 means strong positive correlation while a correlation closer to -1 means strong negative correlation. A correlation near 0 means there is no linear relationship between the variables. 

Please replace the corresponding print and plt calls with your own analysis and visualization code if needed.
