Compose a Java script to instantiate a new thread of execution and concurrently execute the operations within independent threads.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
I propose to create two classes. One class called 'MyRunnable' which implements 'Runnable' interface and another main class that initiates two threads and sets them to run independently.

Here is an example:

First, create a class called MyRunnable.

```java
public class MyRunnable implements Runnable {
   private String myThreadName;

   public MyRunnable(String myThreadName) {
        this.myThreadName = myThreadName;
   }

   @Override
   public void run() {
      for(int i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
         System.out.println(myThreadName + " is running. Count : " + i);
         try {
            Thread.sleep(1000);
         } catch (InterruptedException e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
         }
      }
   }
}
```
Here, 'MyRunnable' class implements Runnable interface and provides implementation for the 'run' method. Inside the 'run' method, we simply print a statement of the thread name and its count. We also add delay of one second in each iteration for the purpose of demonstration.

Next is our main class from where we initiate two threads.

```java
public class MainClass {
   public static void main(String[] args) {
      Thread thread1 = new Thread(new MyRunnable("Thread 1"));
      Thread thread2 = new Thread(new MyRunnable("Thread 2"));

      thread1.start();
      thread2.start();
   }
}
```
In the 'main' method from our second class we instantiate two Thread objects 'thread1' and 'thread2'. We pass new objects of 'MyRunnable' as parameters setting different names for the threads. By calling 'start' method these threads begin executing concurrently.

These threads will continue running independently and concurrently until they exhaust all their iterations.
<|end|>


