Craft a sequence that displays the 20 numbers in the Fibonacci series, utilizing object-oriented programming in Java. Incorporate array data structures and exception handling within your solution. Also, as a reference to spot potential errors, consider the following piece of erroneous code:

```Java  
public class FibonacciSeries {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int[] fib = new int[20];
        fib[0] = 0;
        fib[1] = 1;
        for(int i=2; i<20; i++)
        {
            fib[i] = fib[i-1] + fib[i]; // Potential error is here.
        }
        for(int i=0; i<20; i++)
        {
            System.out.println(fib[i]);
        }
    }
}
```

Fix the error in the given code and optimize it where necessary. Also, refactor the code to achieve the same result using object-oriented principles. Additionally, handle any exceptions that may arise in your program.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
In the erroneous code, the problem lies in the Fibonacci sequence calculation `fib[i] = fib[i-1] + fib[i];`. It should be `fib[i] = fib[i-1] + fib[i-2];`.

To refactor it into an object-oriented form, we create a `FibonacciSeries` class with an array field to store calculation results and a method to generate the sequence.

In terms of exception handling, plausible exceptions could be `ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException` when accessing an array with an invalid index. However, as the size of the array and indices are well controlled in this code, such exceptions are unlikely. For purposes of this exercise though, we can still incorporate exception handling code.

Below is the refactored code:

```Java
public class FibonacciSeries {

    private final int[] fib;

    public FibonacciSeries(int size) {
        if(size < 1) {
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Size should be greater than 0");
        }
        fib = new int[size];
    }

    public void generateSeries() {
        fib[0] = 0;
        if(fib.length > 1) { 
            fib[1] = 1;
            for(int i=2; i<fib.length; i++) {
                fib[i] = fib[i-1] + fib[i-2];
            }
        }
    }

    public void printSeries() {
        for(int i=0; i<fib.length; i++) {
            System.out.println(fib[i]);
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            FibonacciSeries fibSeries = new FibonacciSeries(20);
            fibSeries.generateSeries();
            fibSeries.printSeries();
        } catch (ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException ex) {
            System.out.println("Error while generating Fibonacci series: " + ex.getMessage());
        } catch (IllegalArgumentException ex) {
            System.out.println("Invalid argument: " + ex.getMessage());
        }
    }
}
```

In this code, the `FibonacciSeries` class is initialized with a specific size for the series. The `generateSeries` method populates the array with Fibonacci numbers and the `printSeries` method prints out the series. The error handling in the main method will ensure that any unexpected situations are handled gracefully.
<|end|>


