I need the Perl equivalent for this:
def assemble(letters: str, string_connector: str) -> str:
    if string_connector.isdigit():
        string_connector = ''
    result = ""
    for i in range(len(letters)):
        result += letters[i]
        if i < len(letters)-1:
            result += string_connector
    return result
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Below is the Perl equivalent of your Python function:

```perl
sub assemble {
    my ($letters, $string_connector) = @_;
    
    if ($string_connector =~ /^\d+$/) {
        $string_connector = '';
    }
    my $result = "";
    my @letters_array = split //, $letters;
    for my $i (0 .. $#letters_array) {
        $result .= $letters_array[$i];
        if ($i < $#letters_array) {
            $result .= $string_connector;
        }
    }
    return $result;
}
```
This Perl function does the same thing as the Python function: it iterates over each character of the string `letters`, appends the character to the result string and, if the character is not the last one in `letters`, appends `string_connector` as well.

In Perl, strings are not treated as arrays of characters like they are in Python, so to be able to iterate over each character of a string, we first need to split the string into an array of characters using the `split //` function. The `..` operator is used to create a range from 0 to the index of the last element in the array (returned by `$#letters_array`). Perl uses the `.` operator to concatenate strings.
<|end|>


