<|end|>
<|asst|>
Quantifying the efficiency of UDP over TCP varies based on the specific use case and can mainly be seen in cases where speed is prioritized over reliability. UDP doesn't have the overhead of TCP such as three-way handshakes for connection establishment, acknowledgments for successful packet receipt, and retransmission of lost packets, making UDP often cited as being more "efficient." It's also stateless, meaning it doesn't keep track of data leaving no room for network congestion. However, this doesn't necessarily mean it's more efficient in all scenarios, rather it's more suitable for specific cases where data loss can be tolerated, such as video streaming or gaming. 

Without quantifying this in percentage terms or time saved as it varies on many factors, some estimate UDP can be up to 50% more efficient considering the reduced overhead only. It's important to note that TCP is often more suitable when data integrity is prioritized over speed, like loading a web page or sending an email. It also has built-in congestion control and avoidance mechanisms, which UDP lacks.
<|end|>


