Firstly, the value should be of `double` type instead of `int`. Secondly, there is no return type in the getValue function. Finally, it lacks a function to set the value and there are no necessary error and exception handling. Here is the corrected code:

```cpp
#include <stdexcept>

class DoubleValue {
private: 
    double value;

public: 

    // Constructor
    DoubleValue(double init_val = 0.0) {
        if (isnan(init_val)) {
            throw std::invalid_argument("Cannot initialize DoubleValue with NaN");
        }
        if (isinf(init_val)) {
            throw std::invalid_argument("Cannot initialize DoubleValue with infinity");
        }
        value = init_val;
    } 

    // To set the value ensuring it's neither NaN nor infinity
    void setValue(double val) {
        if (isnan(val)) {
            throw std::invalid_argument("Cannot set DoubleValue with NaN");
        }
        if (isinf(val)) {
            throw std::invalid_argument("Cannot set DoubleValue with infinity");
        }
        value = val;
    }

    // To retrieve the value
    double getValue() {
	return value;
    }
};
```
This code also implements a constructor for `DoubleValue` which takes an initial value as an argument, defaulting to 0.0 if not provided. The constructor and `setValue()` function check if the provided value is `NaN`(Not a Number) or `infinity`, throwing an exception if it is. 

This provides a basic error and exception handling in the case of incorrect initialization or value assignment for the `DoubleValue` object.
