Here is a Python function which uses list comprehension to accomplish this task:

```python
# Function to find common elements in two lists
def find_common_elements(list1, list2):
    # Use list comprehension to find common elements
    common_elements = [element for element in list1 if element in list2]
    return common_elements

# Define two lists
list1 = [2, 3, 4, 5]
list2 = [1, 4, 6]

# Call the function and print the result
print(find_common_elements(list1, list2)) 
```
In this case, the output will be [4] as 4 is the only element present in both lists.

A more optimized solution would use sets as they have a faster lookup time:

```python
# Function to find common elements in two lists using sets
def find_common_elements(list1, list2):
    # Convert lists to sets
    set1 = set(list1)
    set2 = set(list2)

    # Return the intersection of the two sets as a list
    return list(set1 & set2)

# Define two lists
list1 = [2, 3, 4, 5]
list2 = [1, 4, 6]

# Call the function and print the result
print(find_common_elements(list1, list2)) 
```
The output will still be [4] but this version of the function will perform better for larger lists.
