Develop a Python-based software routine that can distinguish and enumerate the distinct lexemes present within a text segment. You can use the following text paragraph as a reference for your task.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Here is the simple solution using Python with NLTK module, which is a set of libraries for natural language processing.

For the sake of this demonstration, let's use the first paragraph of your problem description as our text input.

```python
import nltk
from collections import Counter

# You need to download 'punkt' if you haven't already
# Execute the next line just once to download 'punkt'
#nltk.download('punkt')

def lexeme_report(text):
    # Tokenizes the input string and removes the non-alphabetical tokens
    tokens = [word for word in nltk.word_tokenize(text) if word.isalpha()]
    # Calculates frequency distribution
    lexeme_counter = Counter(tokens)

    return lexeme_counter

text = "Develop a Python-based software routine that can distinguish and enumerate the distinct lexemes present within a text segment."
print(lexeme_report(text))
```

The output of this program will be a dictionary where the keys are the distinct lexemes and the values are the frequencies of those lexemes. The `.isalpha()` function is used to remove punctuation and other non-alphabetical tokens. Take note that NLTK splits contractions into separate tokens by default (i.e., "it's" = "it" + "'s").

Consider that this solution doesn't normalize the text, so words with different capitalization are considered different (e.g., 'Develop' and 'develop'). Also, this won't perform stemming or lemmatization, which means that words with the same root but different forms (e.g., 'run', 'ran', 'running') will be counted separately.

If you want to add any of these functionalities, revisit NLTK documentation, as it covers these topics thoroughly.
<|end|>


