Articulate a regular expression that accurately targets a verified Media Access Control (MAC) address configuration.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
In python, the regular expression for finding a verified MAC address in a text can be described as follows:

```python
import re

# This is the regular expression pattern for a MAC address
pattern = r"([0-9A-Fa-f]{2}[:-]){5}([0-9A-Fa-f]{2})"

# Here we compile the pattern
mac_address_pattern = re.compile(pattern)

text = "My MAC address is 00:0a:95:9d:68:16"

# Now we can find all MAC addresses in the text
mac_addresses = re.findall(mac_address_pattern, text)

for mac in mac_addresses:
    print(mac)
```

This pattern considers a MAC address to be any string that contains six pairs of alphanumeric characters (letters between A-F (case insensitive) and digits from 0-9), separated by either hyphens (-) or colons (:). Each pair (except the last one) is followed by a hyphen or colon. We can then use this pattern to find or validate MAC addresses in a text.
<|end|>


