<|asst|>
Making an SVG responsive involves setting the `width` and `height` attributes to `100%`, rather than a fixed pixel value, and adding a `preserveAspectRatio` attribute to maintain the aspect ratio of the SVG when it scales. Here's how your SVG would look:

```
<svg width="100%" height="100%" viewBox="0 0 32 32" fill="none" preserveAspectRatio="xMinYMin meet" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
<path d="M2.57357 16.3839C2.68525 19.096 3.82618 21.7581 5.80766 24.1057V27.009C5.66784 26.8771 5.52946 26.7427 5.39256 26.6058C2.52092 23.7341 0.729358 20.2084 0.575259 16.4662C0.420407 12.7057 1.92514 8.86158 5.39256 5.39415C8.85999 1.92672 12.7041 0.421994 16.4646 0.576846C20.2068 0.730945 23.7325 2.52251 26.6042 5.39415C26.6826 5.47256 26.7602 5.55145 26.837 5.63082H23.8891C21.5946 3.75933 19.0119 2.68344 16.3823 2.57515C13.2609 2.44662 9.9398 3.67534 6.80678 6.80836C3.67375 9.94139 2.44503 13.2625 2.57357 16.3839Z" fill="#212121"/>

...

</svg>
```

Remember to adapt the SVG's container dimensions accordingly.

But be aware that making an SVG responsive only controls the dimensions, not the actual SVG graphic itself, which means that the paths in the SVG do not dynamically adapt or change shape based on the SVG's size. The graphic itself remains the same; it just scales up or down. If you want different SVG graphics displayed at different widths, you'll need to use Javascript or look into using CSS media queries to swap the SVG out at certain breakpoints.
<|end|>


