<|user|>
Design an efficient data structure that can accommodate the first 10000 Fibonacci numbers, ensuring rapid storage and retrieval operations. The structure should also be optimized to prevent exceeding memory constraints, requiring careful consideration of space complexity.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Data Structure: Array

Design:

An Array can be a perfect data structure to store the first 10000 Fibonacci numbers.

1) Initialize the first two numbers of the series (0 and 1). This will take O(1) time.
2) Generate the next Fibonacci numbers iteratively and store them in the array. Fibonacci sequence is a function of the preceding two numbers, so only two numbers need to be stored in memory at a time. Hence, we can optimize it further to have a constant space complexity of O(1); however, to accommodate the requirement of storing the first 10000 numbers, we would need an array of that size, bringing the space complexity to O(n).
3) Fibonacci numbers rapidly increase as the sequence progresses, and the 10000th Fibonacci number has 2090 digits, which exceeds the limit of any primitive data type. Therefore, to store these large numbers, each Fibonacci number in the array can be represented by a linked list or a dynamic array of integers, where each node or element represents a digit in the number. This will ensure we can store and process large numbers efficiently, but will increase the space complexity.
4) The retrieval operation in the array is O(1) because we can directly access any nth Fibonacci number if the index is known.

Given the constraints (storing first 10000 Fibonacci numbers), this approach is a compromise between space and time complexities. The space complexity is O(nk) where n is the number of Fibonacci numbers and k is the average number of digits in these numbers (which could be quite large), and the time complexity for retrieval is O(1) which is efficient.
<|end|>


