How can I compute the derivative of the payoff function for an American put option?
In the paper ["Smoking adjoints: fast Monte Carlo Greeks" by Giles and Glasserman (2006)](https://www0.gsb.columbia.edu/faculty/pglasserman/Other/RiskJan2006.pdf) they compare two methods to calculate pathwise derivatives:

- Forward method

- Adjoint method


Both of these methods requires the derivative of the payoff function wrt. the parameter. E.g. to approximate the delta, one needs to compute
$$\frac{\partial g}{\partial X(0)}$$
where $g$ is the payoff function and $X(0)$ is the (spot) value of the underlying at time 0. However, they do not specify how this is done for American options. I am concerned that it very well might depend on the optimal stopping time $\tau^*$.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
The American put option payoff is typically given by
$$g(X) = \max_{0 \leq t \leq T} \left(e^{-rt} (K - X(t))\right)_+$$
where $X(t)$ is the value of the underlying at time $t$, $K$ is the strike price, $r$ is the risk free rate and the $(\cdot)_+$ notation stands for the positive part of its argument, meaning $(x)_+ = \max(x, 0)$.

The derivative of the American option payoff with respect to the underlying asset price at time 0, $X(0)$, can be challenging to compute, partly because it involves the derivative of the maximum operator. The computation indeed depends on the optimal stopping time $\tau^*$.

Suppose that the optimal stopping time is $\tau$, the partial derivative of the function becomes,
$$ \frac{\partial g}{\partial X(0)} = \frac{\partial}{\partial X(0)}\left(e^{-r \tau} (K - X(\tau))\right)_+ .$$
If the optimal stopping rule $\tau^*$ makes the put in-the-money at $\tau^*$ (i.e. $K > X(\tau^*)$), the derivative will be 
$$ \frac{\partial g}{\partial X(0)} = - e^{-r\tau} \frac{\partial X(\tau)}{\partial X(0)},$$
which is typically computed through the use of Itô's Lemma or the Feynman-Kac theorem.

If the option is out-of-the-money at $\tau$ (i.e. $K \leq X(\tau)$), the derivative is 0 because there's no sensitivity of the payoff to changes in the underlying.

In practice, given the complexity of the path-dependent nature of the problem, many prefer to use numerical derivative approximation methods, like bumping the underlying price and re-computation, or using adjoint algorithmic differentiation (AAD) as suggested in the paper of Giles and Glasserman. Do note, however, that the application of these methods can also be complex due to the early exercise feature of American options.
<|end|>


