Given the following code section that triggers an error while attempting to install a package on an Ubuntu-based system, analyze the issue, provide a corrected version, and explain the corrected code. Identify the programming vernacular typically used for executing package installations in Ubuntu and other Linux-based systems. Also, discuss its main functionalities within this system.

Error-prone code: 

```bash
APT GET install python3
```

Ensure your explanation includes the protocol to execute this operation, the common errors that might occur, and the necessary precautions to prevent these errors.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
The issue in this code lies in the incorrect usage of the "apt-get" command. This command is intended for package handling in Linux-based systems like Ubuntu. It's used for automated upgrade, install, configure of packages and more. The erroneous code has a space between "APT" and "GET" which is causing an issue. 

Corrected code:

```bash
sudo apt-get install python3
```

The corrected code uses "apt-get" as a single command instead of dividing it as "apt get". The sudo command is utilized to execute operations that need root privileges. 

By adding the sudo command, it ensures this code is executed with superuser privileges, which typically resolves this kind of issue. Commonly you might get errors stating that permission is denied or unable to lock the administration directory, both of these can generally be solved by using sudo.

The "apt-get" is a powerful command-line tool used in Ubuntu and other Debian-based Linux distributions for handling packages. It provides functions such as installing new software packages, upgrading existing software packages, updating the package list index, and even upgrading the entire Ubuntu or Linux systems.

Some common errors that might occur include: not having enough disk space for the package installation, the sudo command not being recognized if it is being run from a non-administrative account, or the apt package repository lists are out-of-date.

To prevent errors, make sure to start the line with "sudo" when installing or upgrading software packages to ensure you're using administrative rights. Always check you have enough storage space before installing anything new. Additionally, you can use the "apt-get update" command to refresh your package lists before installing new software, avoiding out-of-date repository issues. Ensure you run scripts from accounts with enough rights to install software system-wide.
<|end|>


