/^([a-z0-9]{1,29})-([a-z0-9]{1,29})$/
```

This pattern says that there should be a group of 1-29 alphanumeric characters followed by a single hyphen, and then followed again by a group of 1-29 alphanumeric characters. This will only allow for a single hyphen in the string and no hyphen at the beginning or end of the string.

Please note that this pattern would restrict the total length to a minimum of 3 and a maximum of 60 characters (29 alphanumeric characters + 1 hyphen + 29 alphanumeric characters). 

If you need to restrict length of the domain to a maximum of 30 characters including hyphen, regex becomes a bit complicated:

```
/^([a-z0-9]{1,29}-?[a-z0-9]{0,29})$/
```
This pattern allows for a maximum overall length of 30 characters, but it also permits either portion of the domain name to be completely omitted (for example, "-domain" or "domain-"). To check for overall length, a separate operation may be needed if exact string length limits are a requirement. Regex alone may not be able to fulfil all the requirements here.
<|end|>


