Write a JavaScript function that accepts any object. If the object corresponds to a data type in JavaScript that represents a finite set of distinct values, return the name of that data type. If the object doesn't correspond to such a data type, return 'undefined'. Use introspection to determine the data type of the object, don't rely on static type checking or the typeof operator.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Here's a JavaScript function that introspects an object to determine if its type represents a finite set of distinct values:

```javascript
function finiteTypeCheck(obj) {
  const finiteTypes = ["Boolean", "Null", "Undefined", "Number"]; 
  // These are potential finite types according to ECMAScript specification 
  // Note: Number is questionable, but JavaScript has a finite set of number (IEEE-754)

  const objectType = Object.prototype.toString.call(obj).slice(8, -1);

  return finiteTypes.includes(objectType) ? objectType : 'undefined';
}
```

Testing this function:

```javascript
console.log(finiteTypeCheck(true)); // logs: "Boolean"
console.log(finiteTypeCheck(null)); // logs: "Null"
console.log(finiteTypeCheck(undefined)); // logs: "Undefined"
console.log(finiteTypeCheck(12)); // logs: "Number"
console.log(finiteTypeCheck('Hello')); // logs: "undefined"
```

This function uses Object.prototype.toString method with call to get the type of the given object. But please note that determining a finite type in JavaScript is a bit tricky so we assumed finite types like "Boolean", "Null", "Undefined", "Number".

Keep in mind, technically number is infinite in mathematical concepts but in JavaScript we actually have a finite set of distinct numeric values due to the IEEE-754 standard for floating point arithmetic. Definitely these types are a bit arbitrary, and you would tweak this list according to your requirements.
