I am reading SOFR USER Guide - [https://www.newyorkfed.org/medialibrary/Microsites/arrc/files/2019/Users_Guide_to_SOFR.pdf](https://www.newyorkfed.org/medialibrary/Microsites/arrc/files/2019/Users_Guide_to_SOFR.pdf)
I am having trouble understanding SOFR payment in arrears, especially lockout and lookback.
Lockout or Suspension Period: Use the averaged SOFR over current interest period with last rates set
at the rate fixed k days before the period ends (a 2-5 day lockout has been used in most SOFR
FRNs).
Lookback: For every day in the current interest period, use the SOFR rate from k days earlier. (a
3-5 day lookback has been used in SONIA FRNs)
Does anyone has an example or point to source to explain lockout and lookback ?
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Sure, let's try to break it down with simple examples.

Lockout or Suspension Period: This is typically used in the calculation of floating interest rate products, such as Floating Rate Notes (FRN), the rate for the last few days of the interest period is held constant as the 'locked rate.' For example, if you have a 5-day lockout period, the interest rate used for the last 5 days of the period will be the same as the rate fixed 5 days prior.

Let's say the interest period is for 10 days with a 2-day lockout. Interest rates for the first 8 days are different each day according to daily SOFR. For the last two days (day 9 and 10), we would use the SOFR of day 8, since the rate is 'locked out' for the final 2 days.

Lookback: In this approach, the interest rate applied on a given day will be the rate from a certain number of days ago (the 'lookback' period). For instance, if you have a 3-day lookback, the interest rate you apply today will be the rate from 3 days ago.

For a 10-day interest period with a 3-day lookback, On Day 1, you don't have SOFR, since we don't have historical data. Same for Day 2 and Day 3. Starting Day 4, we apply SOFR of Day 1. On Day 5, we use the rate from Day 2, and so on. On Day 10, we apply the rate from Day 7. 

In both cases, the aim is to provide a certain level of predictability to the payments to be made and reduce the risk that the last few day's interest rate movements will severely impact the overall interest payable. The choice to use either a Lockout or Lookback is determined by the terms of the contract underlying the FRN. Also, note that these mechanism can also be applied to other overnight rates such as SONIA, ESTR etc. and not only to SOFR.
<|end|>


