## Part 1: Load, Prepare and Preprocess the Dataset

Let's start by loading the necessary libraries and the wine dataset.

```python
# Import necessary libraries
import pandas as pd
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn import preprocessing
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn import metrics
from sklearn.pipeline import make_pipeline
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler

# Load wine dataset
from sklearn.datasets import load_wine
wine = load_wine()

# Prepare feature and target vectors
X=wine.data
y=wine.target
```

## Part 2: Split the data into train and test sets

```python
# Split data into train and test sets
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=0)
```

## Part 3: Create logistic regression model without feature engineering

Before applying any feature engineering, let's create a logistic regression model and get baseline results.

```python
# Create logistic regression model
model = LogisticRegression()
model.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Predict on test set
y_pred = model.predict(X_test)

# Get accuracy, precision, recall, F1-score, AUC-ROC
print('Accuracy:', metrics.accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred))
print('Precision:', metrics.precision_score(y_test, y_pred, average='weighted'))
print('Recall:', metrics.recall_score(y_test, y_pred, average='weighted'))
print('F1-Score:', metrics.f1_score(y_test, y_pred, average='weighted'))
y_pred_proba = model.predict_proba(X_test)[::,1]
print('AUC-ROC:', metrics.roc_auc_score(y_test, y_pred_proba))
```

## Part 4: Apply normalization and PCA on the train and test sets

Normalization scales the features such that they have a mean of 0 and a standard deviation of 1. PCA reduces the dimensionality while retaining most of the information.

```python
# Apply normalization
scaler = preprocessing.StandardScaler().fit(X_train)
X_train_transformed = scaler.transform(X_train)
X_test_transformed = scaler.transform(X_test)

# Apply PCA
pca = PCA(n_components=2) 
X_train_pca = pca.fit_transform(X_train_transformed)
X_test_pca = pca.transform(X_test_transformed)
```

## Part 5: Create logistic regression model with feature engineering

Now, let's evaluate the model after applying the feature engineering steps.

```python
# Create logistic regression model
model = LogisticRegression()
model.fit(X_train_pca, y_train)

# Predict on test set
y_pred_pca = model.predict(X_test_pca)

# Get accuracy, precision, recall, F1-score, AUC-ROC
print('Accuracy:', metrics.accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred_pca))
print('Precision:', metrics.precision_score(y_test, y_pred_pca, average='weighted'))
print('Recall:', metrics.recall_score(y_test, y_pred_pca, average='weighted'))
print('F1-Score:', metrics.f1_score(y_test, y_pred_pca, average='weighted'))
y_pred_proba_pca = model.predict_proba(X_test_pca)[::,1]
print('AUC-ROC:', metrics.roc_auc_score(y_test, y_pred_proba_pca))
```

## Part 6: Cross-validation and hyperparameter tuning

In this part, we will implement a cross-validation scheme to fine-tune the model and select the hyperparameters that give the best performance.

```python
# Define hyperparameters to search
hyperparameters = {'logisticregression__C': [0.01, 0.1, 1, 10, 100]}

# Create logistic regression with PCA and normalization pipeline
pipeline = make_pipeline(StandardScaler(), PCA(n_components=2), LogisticRegression())

# Use GridSearchCV to fine-tune model
gridsearch = GridSearchCV(pipeline, hyperparameters, cv=5)
gridsearch.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Predict on test set
y_pred_gridsearch = gridsearch.predict(X_test)

# Get accuracy, precision, recall, F1-score, AUC-ROC
print('Accuracy:', metrics.accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred_gridsearch))
print('Precision:', metrics.precision_score(y_test, y_pred_gridsearch, average='weighted'))
print('Recall:', metrics.recall_score(y_test, y_pred_gridsearch, average='weighted'))
print('F1-Score:', metrics.f1_score(y_test, y_pred_gridsearch, average='weighted'))
y_pred_proba_gridsearch = gridsearch.predict_proba(X_test)[::,1]
print('AUC-ROC:', metrics.roc_auc_score(y_test, y_pred_proba_gridsearch))
```

## Part 7: Analyze feature importance

We can use coefficients from the logistic regression model to indicate feature importance.

```python
# Get feature importance
feature_importance = model.coef_[0]

# Create a data frame of feature names and importance
features_df = pd.DataFrame({'Features': wine.feature_names, 'Importance': feature_importance})

# Sort by the absolute value of the importance score
features_df = features_df.sort_values(by='Importance', key=abs, ascending=False)

# Print the feature importance dataframe
print(features_df)
```

You may want to adjust the codes above depending on the actual performance of the model, the specifications of the dataset, or the requirements of your project. Also, remember to justify your results, interpret the logistic regression model's outputs, and discuss the findings.
