I need to run a `PowerShell` like this:

Connect-SomeServer localhost;
Import-SomeTemplate C:\temp\info.zip


This action opens a progress bar in `PowerShell ISE`. Sometimes the action can pass after 30 seconds, and sometimes it can take 7 minutes or even more.
How can I check that the progress bar (action) has ended?
<|end|>
<|asst|>
There is no explicit function in PowerShell to check when a progress bar has ended because the progress bar just represents the operation being carried out and does not report its status back to the script or command that invoked it. 

However, what you can do is to check the status of the operation being carried out. With that said, the best solution is often to create a loop which checks the status of the command at intervals and acts only when it has completed its action. 

This would look something like:

```Powershell
# Connect to server
Connect-SomeServer localhost;

# Import the template, asign result to variable
$action = Import-SomeTemplate C:\temp\info.zip 

# Continue checking if $action is running
while($action.Status -eq 'Running'){
    # Sleep for a short duration to prevent excessive resource usage
    Start-Sleep -Seconds 5
}

if ($action.Status -eq 'Completed') {
    Write-Host "Action Completed Successfully!"
} 
else {
    Write-Host "Action Failed!"
}
```
Please note that `$action.Status` is just a placeholder. You should replace it with the actual line that checks the status of your `Import-SomeTemplate` operation.

Disclaimer: Not all commands return an object that has a `Status` property. This is a general concept commonly used in scripting to check a command's status periodically. Whether you can use it depends on the operations you run.
<|end|>


