So here is my problem. I made a game in ue5 with few levels. But the problem is when i want to pack and export it, but when i do it, unreal pack and export only one level and skip the rest.
I exported every single level to check where is a problem but it wasnt possible to export whole game
<|end|>
<|asst|>
There could be several reasons why Unreal Engine 5 is only packing and exporting one level. Here is how you can troubleshoot and solve this problem:

1. **Ensure All Levels Are Included in the Build Process:**
Make sure all your levels are listed in "Maps To Include In A packaged Build" under project settings. It's located in the Packaging session. 

2. **Correct Level Streaming Setup:**
If you are using level streaming, make sure that your persistent level is correctly configured and that all sub-levels are being loaded properly. 

3. **Level References:**
Check your level references. Usually, if UE5 isn't packaging certain elements, there's an issue with the references. Debug any Null References that might be causing the issue.

4. **Game Default Map and Transition Map:**
In your project settings, ensure you've set the correct maps under 'Maps & Modes' specifically, where it says 'Game Default Map' and 'Transition Map'.

5. **Missing or Incorrect Assets/Blueprints:**
Check for any assets/blueprints on the levels that are being excluded from export. Sometimes incorrect or missing assets/blueprints can cause packaging issues

6. **Review Error Message:**
Always look at the output log for any error messages. Epic Games has great documentation on their website to help you decipher the error message if you don't understand it.

7. **Defected Project Files:**
If you've tried everything else it might be that your project files are corrupted. Try setting up a new project and start by importing one level at a time, and see if the problem continues.

Remember, you should always make sure to fix all the errors and the warnings before packaging your project. A clean and error-free project significantly reduces the chances of running into issues during the packaging process.
<|end|>


