I have a free standing set of files not affiliated with any C# project at all that reside in a complicated nested directory structure.

I want to add them in that format to a different directory in an ASP.NET web application I am working on; while retaining the same structure. So, I copied the folder into the target location of my project and I tried to “add existing  item” only to lose the previous folder hierarchy.

Usually I have re-created the directories by hand, copied across on a one-to-one basis, and then added existing items. There are simply too many directories/items in this case.

So how do you add existing directories and files in Visual Studio 2008?
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Follow these steps:

1. Open your project in Visual Studio
2. In Solution Explorer, choose the project or folder you want to add the files to
3. Right-click on it and choose 'Open Folder in File Explorer'. This opens the folder where your project is stored.
4. Copy the nested directory structure you need to add into this location in the file explorer
5. Switch back to Visual Studio
6. Right-click on the project or folder you want to add the files to and choose 'Refresh'. 
7. Visual Studio should now show the added files and directories in Solution Explorer

Please note that the files won't be automatically included in the project. To include them, you have to:

1. Select the parent folder in Solution Explorer.
2. In the top menu, select 'Project' -> 'Show All Files'
3. Right click the grayed out files or folders you just added.
4. 'Include In Project'

This way allows the files to retain the nested directory format. 

These steps should help you achieve your desired result without any loss of data or additional copying.
