Running VS2003/05 under Vista makes the former screw up the display at least 50% of the time - you start debugging, VS kicks in and you see the windows/docking panes screwed up, not refreshing, etc... I've contacted Microsoft about this, but they weren't much help, I was wondering if someone knows any fixes?

I'm running VS with visual styles turned off under Vista, so that it doesn't hang when you try to do a "find in files".

All the latest updates/service packs are installed.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
You might try a workaround by starting Visual Studio in Windows XP Compatibility mode. 

Follow these steps to add the XP Compatibility Mode to Visual Studio:

1. Navigate to the Visual Studio executable (for instance C:\Program Files (x86)\Microsoft Visual Studio 9.0\Common7\IDE\devenv.exe for VS2008). 

2. Right-click on the executable and select 'Properties'.

3. Switch to the 'Compatibility' tab.

4. Check the 'Run this program in Compatibility mode for:' checkbox and select 'Windows XP (Service Pack 2)' from the dropdown.

5. Click the 'OK' button to close the dialog.

If the problem still exists, there is another setting that you can try disabling (although this has less of a chance of solving the problem). In the Tools->Options dialog of Visual Studio, under the 'Environment' category, there is a ‘General' sub-category. In this page, there is an option for 'Use hardware graphics acceleration if available'. If this option is checked, you can try unchecking it to see if that makes a difference.

It is also worth pointing out that VS 2003/2005 are not officially supported on Vista and later operations systems, so it might worth considering an upgrade to a later version of Visual Studio if possible.
<|end|>


