<|user|>
In time series forecasting we are removing the "seasonal" component to fit models better and have better forecasting. But why? if I should give an extreme example: if I have a sin wave, I wouldn't remove the seasonal component of it. Because it is much easier to forecast with its own structure (because it has an easily recognizable pattern). Am I wrong?
<|end|>
<|asst|>
You're not wrong, but it depends on the specific case or problem you're dealing with. Removing the seasonal component can be beneficial when you want to identify the underlying trend in the data. Seasonal components can sometimes "hide" trends since they introduce variability into the data. 

For instance, in a retail setting, sales might be higher during holiday periods but this could disguise an overall downward trend in sales. By removing the seasonal component, this trend becomes easier to identify and model.

However, in other cases like your sine wave example, the seasonal component itself could actually be the main driver of the pattern. In such scenarios, removing the seasonal component would not be very meaningful and can actually lead to worse forecast accuracy.

So in summary, whether or not to remove the seasonal component is a decision that should be made based on understanding of the specific time-series data at hand.
<|end|>


