BeautifulSoup Python Question:
Hello all, webscraping beginner here! I am trying to extract the url of an element on a specific website. I click inspect, and it only shows the abbreviated version of the url on the Chrome inspect element area. If it's shorter, the link will show in full. When I click the url on the html on Chrome's inspect element area, it takes me to the desired link on Chrome.
When I try to extract it as an a.['href'] it only returns the abbreviated link. (Fake example: 'https://pizza.com/pepperonis/mozzarella/../onions'.)
You can see how the fake link above has those dots and it gives me an error when I  the   which doesn't work when I try to use it in my python program.
Anyone encountered this and can help?
I tried to use a f string and it didn't work to estimate what the string would be.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
The abbreviated URL you're seeing (with the ".." in it) is likely a relative URL, which is common on many websites. To get the full URL, you typically need to combine the base URL of the website (in your example: 'https://pizza.com') with the relative URL.

Here's a simple example:

```python
from urllib.parse import urljoin

base_url = 'https://pizza.com'
relative_url = '/pepperonis/mozzarella/../onions'

full_url = urljoin(base_url, relative_url)
print(full_url)  # https://pizza.com/pepperonis/onions
```

In the above code, `urllib.parse.urljoin()` is used to combine the base URL with the relative URL, handling any ".." or similar navigations as needed. So if you find relative URLs when web scraping with BeautifulSoup, you can use this approach to get the full URLs.
  
Applying to BeautifulSoup:

```python
from urllib.parse import urljoin
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup
import requests

base_url = 'https://pizza.com'

response = requests.get(base_url)
soup = BeautifulSoup(response.text, 'html.parser')

# Assuming a_tag is the `<a>` tag you have.
a_tag = soup.find('a')

relative_url = a_tag['href']
full_url = urljoin(base_url, relative_url)
print(full_url)
```
This will print the actual full URL you're looking for instead of the relative URL. Make sure to replace `soup.find('a')` with however you're finding the specific `<a>` tag you're looking for.
  
Notice that relative links starting with a single slash are relative to the root domain, while those starting with double dots are relative to the current page or directory.
  
Also note that URL parsing and joining capabilities may vary across different Python libraries, so your mileage may vary depending on the complexity of the URLs and the specific website structure. In the most of the cases `urllib.parse.urljoin` should suffice.
<|end|>


