Extend the functionality of the given programming task by identifying the second smallest element in the array instead of just outputting the element in the second position. Assume that the array is unsorted and may have duplicate elements. Apply the most efficient sorting algorithm you know and return the second smallest number.

Array: [4, 8, 5, 2, 11, 2, 16]
<|end|>
<|asst|>
The problem can be solved using Python built-in functions for list. Here is the solution:

Python:

```python
def second_smallest(arr):
    arr = list(set(arr))
    arr.sort()
    return arr[1] if len(arr) > 1 else None

print(second_smallest([4, 8, 5, 2, 11, 2, 16]))
```

This program works by first converting the array to a set to remove any duplicate elements. Afterwards, it sorts the set (converted back to a list, since sets can't be sorted), and returns the second element. 

The Python built-in `sort` function is a hybrid sorting algorithm, called Timsort, that derives from merge sort and insertion sort, specially designed to perform well on many kinds of real-world data, with a worst-case time complexity is O(n log n).

But remember, if the list have less than or equal to one unique element, we can't find the second smallest element. That's why there is a condition checking the length of the list before returning the second element.

Please make sure to handle the case when array has only one distinct number, as it'll return None, that can cause an error in your further code.
<|end|>


