Write a Python program that prompts the user to input 10 different items. These items can vary, from integers, floats, to strings. Your program has to make sure that all items are unique. If a user enters a duplicate item, notify the user and urge them to enter a new unique one. After the user has entered all items, your program should store them in an array and display the last five items in reversed order.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Here is a Python solution for the problem:

```python
unique_items = set()
while len(unique_items) < 10:
    item = input('Enter a unique item: ')
    if item not in unique_items:
        unique_items.add(item)
    else:
        print('Item already exists, please enter a new unique item.')

# convert the set to a list
items_list = list(unique_items)
print('Last five items in reversed order: ', items_list[-1:-6:-1])
```
In the code above, a set is used to store the 10 different items. Since a set inherently does not allow duplicate items, it's very easy to check if an item already exists. A while loop is used to prompt the user to input a different item as long as there are not yet 10 items in the set. After 10 unique items have been gathered, the set gets converted to a list since sets do not support indexing or slicing (which we need for getting the last five items in reverse order). The last line prints the last five items in reversed order with the help of Python's negative slicing.
Keep in mind that the order of elements in a set is not guaranteed, so if you need to maintain the input order, consider using a list for storage and manually check for duplicates each time.
<|end|>


