Fabricate a C programming code segment that solicits a numerical figure from the user. This code is tasked with calculating and printing the cumulative multiplication of individual integers that constitute the provided input.
n = 347
<|end|>
<|asst|>
First of all, please note that C programming doesn't support getting individual digits directly from an integer. A number is taken as an integer, not as a set of separate digits. To obtain individual digits from the number, we will convert the integer to a string and then process each character of the string (as a digit of the number) separately.

Here's a concise C code that meets the requirements:

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <string.h> // to use strlen() function

int main()
{
    char num[10];
    int i, res = 1;

    printf("Enter a number: ");
    fgets(num, 10, stdin); // using fgets instead of scanf for better handling of newline character

    for(i = 0; i < strlen(num) - 1; i++) {
        res *= num[i] - '0'; // subtracting '0' to convert char type digit to int type
    }

    printf("The cumulative multiplication of individual integers: %d\n", res);

    return 0;
}
```
In this code, the program accepts input as a character array (string in other words) instead of an integer. Then it loops through the string calculating the multiplication by converting every character into an integer (with `num[i] - '0'`) and multiplying it to the result. Then it prints out the result.
<|end|>


