Design a comprehensive and accurately defined XML schema that encapsulates the unique health-related data points of an individual. 
Patient's Name: Jane Smith
Number of Allergies: 2
Blood Type: AB+
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Below is a simple and comprehensive XML schema that defines data points related to a patient's health:

```xml
<?xml version="1.0"?>
<xs:schema xmlns:xs="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema">

<xs:element name="Patient">
  <xs:complexType>
    <xs:sequence>
      <xs:element name="Name" type="xs:string"/>
      <xs:element name="TotalNumberOfAllergies" type="xs:integer"/>
      <xs:element name="BloodType" type="xs:string"/>
      <xs:element name="Allergies" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded">
        <xs:complexType>
          <xs:attribute name="name" type="xs:string" use="required"/>
        </xs:complexType>
      </xs:element>
    </xs:sequence>
    <xs:attribute name="id" type="xs:integer" use="required"/>
  </xs:complexType>
</xs:element>

</xs:schema>
```
This schema represents a 'Patient' element that has a string 'Name', an integer 'TotalNumberOfAllergies', and a string 'BloodType'. Aside from these, the Patient could have zero or more 'Allergies' sub-elements, each of which uses a required 'name' attribute. An identity attribute 'id' is also required for the 'Patient' element.

For example, patient Jane Smith who has 2 allergies and a blood type of AB+ would be represented like this:

```xml
<Patient id="1">
  <Name>Jane Smith</Name>
  <TotalNumberOfAllergies>2</TotalNumberOfAllergies>
  <BloodType>AB+</BloodType>
  <Allergies name="Allergy1"/>
  <Allergies name="Allergy2"/>
</Patient>
```
You may replace "Allergy1" and "Allergy2" with the appropriate allergy names.
<|end|>


