<|user|>
everyone. After clicking on an ImageView, I would like to change it depending on what kind of drawable is currently displayed. To do this, I compare the currently set image in the ImageView with one from the drawable folder. Unfortunately, it is currently the case that only the else branch is executed. The image changes after the first click, but then it no longer switches. What am I doing wrong?

bookmark_site.setOnClickListener{
        vibrator.vibrate(50);

        var draw = bookmark_site.drawable.constantState


        if(draw == ContextCompat.getDrawable(this,R.drawable.ic_baseline_bookmark_filled_24)?.constantState)
        {
            bookmark_site.setImageDrawable(resources.getDrawable(R.drawable.ic_outline_bookmark_border_outline_24))
        }
        else{

         //Only this two is ever executed
            bookmark_site.setImageDrawable(resources.getDrawable(R.drawable.ic_baseline_bookmark_filled_24))
        }
    }
<|end|>
<|asst|>
The main reason that is happening is because you're getting the Drawable's constant state at the start of the ClickListener, before you change the Drawable of the ImageView, and using it in your if-else check. Instead, you should get the Drawable's constant state inside the if-else block each time before you reference it.

This way, you're always checking the latest Drawable set in the ImageView.

Here's the updated code:

```kotlin
bookmark_site.setOnClickListener{
     vibrator.vibrate(50)

     var draw = bookmark_site.drawable.constantState

     if(draw == ContextCompat.getDrawable(this,R.drawable.ic_baseline_bookmark_filled_24)?.constantState)
     {
         bookmark_site.setImageResource(R.drawable.ic_outline_bookmark_border_outline_24)
     }
     else{
         bookmark_site.setImageResource(R.drawable.ic_baseline_bookmark_filled_24)
     }
     
     draw = bookmark_site.drawable.constantState
}
```

Moreover, it's recommended to use setImageResource(int) instead of setImageDrawable(Drawable) if you're referencing a Drawable resource id.

This still can fail sometimes because of Drawable.ConstantState instances not being the same. Drawable resources might have different id after each build.

A more reliable way to handle this situation is not to depend upon comparing drawables. Instead, you can use a Boolean variable to keep track of whether your Image is bookmarked or not. Then you can set your Image based on the Boolean value and change it every time the ImageView is clicked.

Here's the updated code using a Boolean:

```kotlin
var isBookmarked = false

bookmark_site.setOnClickListener{
    vibrator.vibrate(50);
    
    if(isBookmarked)
    {
        bookmark_site.setImageResource(R.drawable.ic_outline_bookmark_border_outline_24)
    }
    else{
        bookmark_site.setImageResource(R.drawable.ic_baseline_bookmark_filled_24)
    }
    
    isBookmarked = !isBookmarked // invert the bookmarked state
}
```
This approach avoids ambiguity and would behave as expected.
<|end|>


