How would you express this in Java?
def advanced_sort_elements(array):
    return sorted(array, key = lambda x: (len(x), x))

array = [["cat", "dog", "elephant"], ["apple", "banana"], ["green", "yellow", "blue", "red"], ["a", "aa", "aaa"], [0, 1, 2, 3, 4], [5, 6]]
print("Sorted array is: ", advanced_sort_elements(array))
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Below is the implementation in Java:

```java
import java.util.Arrays;
import java.util.Collections;
import java.util.Comparator;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Object[][] array = {
            {"cat", "dog", "elephant"}, 
            {"apple", "banana"}, 
            {"green", "yellow", "blue", "red"}, 
            {"a", "aa", "aaa"}, 
            {0, 1, 2, 3, 4}, 
            {5, 6}
        };

        Arrays.sort(array, new Comparator<Object[]>() {
            @Override
            public int compare(Object[] o1, Object[] o2) {
                int c = Integer.compare(o1.length, o2.length);
                if (c != 0) return c;
                else return Arrays.toString(o1).compareTo(Arrays.toString(o2));
            }
        });

        for (Object[] row : array) {
            System.out.println(Arrays.toString(row));
        }
    }
}
```

Please note that Java does not do a deep comparison on array content. Here we manually convert the array to a string before comparison.

Also, remember that lists are an easier and better alternative in Java to do such operations due to the power of Collections. An example of this is ArrayList, which is commonly used due to its flexibility and ease of use over standard arrays.
<|end|>


