Write an HTML and JavaScript code snippet to create an interactive dropdown menu. Additionally, the dropdown menu should contain submenu items. Your solution should also handle all events such as highlighting the submenu when hovered. The dropdown menu should hide itself when clicked outside of it, and also remember it's last selected item when it is reopened.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
You can simply achieve this by using JavaScript, HTML, and CSS.
Here is the last part of the solution regarding retaining the last selected item even after closing the dropdown. This case is handled via localStorage.

Here, we use localStorage to remember the last selected item. The selected item is stored in localStorage when it is clicked on, and upon re-opening the same dropdown, the last selected item is retrieved back from localStorage.

HTML:
```html
<div class="dropdown">
    <button class="dropbtn" id="dropbtn">Dropdown</button>
    <div class="dropdown-content" id="dropdown-content">
        <a href="#">Link 1</a>
        <a href="#">Link 2</a>
        <a href="#">Link 3</a>
        <a href="#">Link 4</a>
    </div>
</div>
```
CSS:
```css 
.dropdown {
    position: relative;
    display: inline-block;
}
.dropdown-content {
    display: none;
    position: absolute;
    background-color: #f1f1f1;
    min-width: 160px;
    box-shadow: 0px 8px 16px 0px rgba(0,0,0,0.2);
    z-index: 1;
}
.dropdown-content a {
    color: black;
    padding: 12px 16px;
    text-decoration: none;
    display: block;
}
.dropdown-content a:hover {
    background-color: #ddd;
}
```
JavaScript:
```javascript 
window.onload = function() {
    const dropdownContent = document.getElementById('dropdown-content');
    const dropbtn = document.getElementById('dropbtn');

    dropbtn.addEventListener('click', function() {
        dropdownContent.style.display = dropdownContent.style.display === 'block' ? 'none' : 'block';
        this.innerText = localStorage.getItem('lastItem') || 'Dropdown';
    });

    dropdownContent.addEventListener('click', function(e) {
        if (e.target && e.target.nodeName === 'A') {
            localStorage.setItem('lastItem', e.target.innerText);
            dropbtn.innerText = localStorage.getItem('lastItem');
        }
    })
}

window.onclick = function(event) {
    if (!event.target.matches('.dropbtn')) {
        const dropdowns = document.getElementsByClassName("dropdown-content");
        for (let i = 0; i < dropdowns.length; i++) {
            const openDropdown = dropdowns[i];
            if (openDropdown.style.display === 'block') {
                openDropdown.style.display = 'none';
            }
        }
    }
}
``` 

We are using event delegation for performance and memory reasons. Instead of attaching an event listener to each link, we are attaching a single event listener to the dropdown content, and then we're checking if a link was clicked using the event object. But you also could add a click event to each links inside dropdown menu.
<|end|>


