&lt;p&gt;Take into account all the triangles that satisfy the following conditions:
&lt;/p&gt;&lt;ul&gt;&lt;li&gt;All their vertices are located on &lt;strong class=&#34;tooltip&#34;&gt;lattice points&lt;span class=&#34;tooltiptext&#34;&gt;Integer coordinates&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong class=&#34;tooltip&#34;&gt;circumcentre&lt;span class=&#34;tooltiptext&#34;&gt;Centre of the circumscribed circle&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; is positioned at the origin $O$.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong class=&#34;tooltip&#34;&gt;orthocentre&lt;span class=&#34;tooltiptext&#34;&gt;Point where the three altitudes intersect&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; is at the point $H(5, 0)$.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;p&gt;There exist nine such triangles with a perimeter not exceeding $\le 50$.&lt;br&gt;
In ascending order of their perimeters, these triangles are:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;table&gt;&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td&gt;$A(-4, 3)$, $B(5, 0)$, $C(4, -3)$&lt;br&gt;
$A(4, 3)$, $B(5, 0)$, $C(-4, -3)$&lt;br&gt;
$A(-3, 4)$, $B(5, 0)$, $C(3, -4)$&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
$A(3, 4)$, $B(5, 0)$, $C(-3, -4)$&lt;br&gt;
$A(0, 5)$, $B(5, 0)$, $C(0, -5)$&lt;br&gt;
$A(1, 8)$, $B(8, -1)$, $C(-4, -7)$&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
$A(8, 1)$, $B(1, -8)$, $C(-4, 7)$&lt;br&gt;
$A(2, 9)$, $B(9, -2)$, $C(-6, -7)$&lt;br&gt;
$A(9, 2)$, $B(2, -9)$, $C(-6, 7)$&lt;br&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;resources/images/0264_TriangleCentres.gif?1678992056&#34; class=&#34;dark_img&#34; alt=&#34;0264_TriangleCentres.gif&#34;&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/table&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The aggregate of their perimeters, approximated to four decimal places, is $291.0089$.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Identify all such triangles with a perimeter not exceeding $\le 10^5$.&lt;br&gt;
Submit as your response the aggregate of their perimeters approximated to four decimal places.&lt;/p&gt;
<|end|>
<|asst|>
The given condition for a triangle to have circumcentre $(0,0)$ and orthocentre at $(5,0)$ corresponds to the fact that this can only be possible when the triangle is right angled and hypotenuse lies on x-axis. This is because the midpoint of hypotenuse is always the circumcenter in a right-angled triangle, and the orthocentre of a right-angled triangle is always the vertex of the right angle. 

From here, we can deduce that the vertices will be of the form $(h, k), (h, -k), (5, 0)$ since $k$ will be equal to height of the triangle. Therefore, the length of hypotenuse which will be equal to $2*k$ can acquire values from $1$ to $10^5/2$. 

Python will be an appropriate programming language to solve this problem because it supports big integers right out of the box and has a simple and natural syntax. The following python code finds all such triangles by iterating over all possible lengths of hypotenuse.

```python
from math import gcd, sqrt

def is_q(x):
    sq = sqrt(x)
    return sq == int(sq)

n = 10**5//2
res = set()
s = 0.0

for i in range(1,n+1):
    e = 2*i
    h = 25 + e*e
    if is_q(h):
        w = int(sqrt(h))
        if gcd(e, w) != 1: continue
        if w % 2 == 0:
            a, b, c = w//2, - (e * e - 1)//2, (e * e + 1)//2
        else:
            a, b, c = (e * e - 1)//2, w // 2, - (e * e + 1)//2
        if (b,c) not in res:
            res.add((b,c))
            s += (e + abs(b - a) + abs(c - a))
            
print("%.4f" % s)
```
This python code first checks whether the square of the length of the hypotenuse lies in set of perfect squares or not. If yes, then it moves ahead and checks whether the length of base is a multiple of length of perpendicular. If this condition is also satisfied, then it calculates the coordinates of remaining vertices and add them to the set if both vertices aren't already present in the set. In end, it calculates perimeter of triangle and adds it to the sum of perimeters initialized as 0.0 in the beginning of code.
<|end|>


