<|end|>
<|asst|>
Sure, here is an example of a simple program that does what you're asking for. It accepts an integer as input and then prints all the even numbers from 0 upto but not including the input number.

```cpp
#include <iostream>

int main(){
    int boundary;

    std::cout << "Please enter a numeric boundary: ";
    std::cin >> boundary;

    for(int i = 0; i < boundary; i++){
        if(i % 2 == 0){
            std::cout << i << "\n";
        }
    }

    return 0;
}
```
This C++ program first ask for an input number. Afterwards it iterates from 0 to the supplied boundary (exclusive), and prints the number only if it is even. This is checked by the condition `(i % 2 == 0)`, where `%` is the modulus operator. If a number `i` gives a remainder 0 when divided by 2, it is an even number.
<|end|>


