Complete the ensuing computational script:
/*
brackets refers to a character string composed of '<' and '>'.
The function should ascertain and reaffirm if every introductory bracket has a complementary closing bracket, effectively ensuring a balanced use of these symbols. 

For instance, 
correct_bracketing("<") output should be false
correct_bracketing("<>") output should be true
correct_bracketing("<<><>>") output should be true
correct_bracketing("><<>") output should be false
*/

#include<stdio.h>
#include<string>
using namespace std;
bool correct_bracketing(string brackets){
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Here is a C++ solution using a stack data structure. We push every '<' into the stack and for every '>' we check if there is any '<' in the stack and pop it out. If stack is empty at the end then we return true else false.

```cpp
#include <stack>
bool correct_bracketing(string brackets){
    stack<char> s;
    for(int i = 0; i < brackets.size(); i++){
        if(brackets[i] == '<'){
            s.push('<');
        } else {
            if(s.empty()){
                return false;
            }else{
                s.pop();
            }
        }
    }
    if(s.empty()){
        return true;
    }else{
        return false;
    } 
}
```

This code works by going through the string and treating each '<' as an opened bracket and each '>' as a closed bracket. When it encounters a '<', it adds it to the stack. When it encounters a '>', it checks if there is a corresponding '<' on the stack and removes it. If the stack is empty at the end, this means all brackets have been closed and the function returns true. If there are still items on the stack at the end, this means there are some unclosed brackets and the function returns false.
<|end|>


