I do multi-label text classification using Bi-LSTM classifier, that means there are instances in the dataset of 11 classes that have more than 1 label. When I use the "sigmoid" activation function with "binary_crossentropy" loss function, I get higher accuracy than using "softmax" activation function with "categorical_crossentropy" loss function. why?
<|end|>
<|asst|>
This has to do with the nature of your classification problem and the mathematical properties of the different loss functions and activation functions.

1. Your problem is of multi-label classification, where each example can belong to more than one class simultaneously. 

In such problems, it's generally more beneficial to treat each class as an independent Bernoulli distribution rather than mutually exclusive classes which is the assumption with softmax and categorical cross entropy. 

2. Sigmoid activation with binary cross entropy allows the model to choose more than one class. If a neuron's output is above the threshold for several classes, then all those classes will be selected. 

In contrast, softmax activation enforces that the sum of the probabilities of your classes must equal one. This activation is used when you know exactly one class is applicable, which is not your case.

3. Binary Cross Entropy loss (used with sigmoid) does not assume that the classes are exclusive which means it will not penalize the model when several classes are predicted for a single observation.

On the other hand, categorical cross entropy (paired with softmax) will penalize the model if it finds other true classes for an observation.

4. Mathematically, the sigmoid activation function provides a more gradual gradation in the output matrix that allows the model to better differentiate between multi-label classes compared to the softmax function which gives a more abrupt gradation in outputs. 

All these reasons explain why sigmoid activation with binary cross entropy might perform better than softmax with categorical cross entropy for your multi-label text classification problem.
<|end|>


