Below is a Java code snippet to accomplish the required task:

```Java
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Define initial multi-dimensional array
        int[][] arr = {{1,2}, {3,4}, {5,6}};

        // Print out initial array
        System.out.println("Initial array: ");
        printArray(arr);

        // Define insertion element and its coordinates
        int element = 7;
        int row = 1, column = 1;

        // Insert defined element at the defined position
        arr[row][column] = element;

        // Print out array after the insertion
        System.out.println("\n\nArray after insertion: ");
        printArray(arr);
    }

    // Define method to print multi-dimensional array
    public static void printArray(int[][] arr) {
        for (int i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
            for (int j = 0; j < arr[i].length; j++) {
                System.out.print(arr[i][j] + " ");
            }
            System.out.println();
        }
    }
}
```

When you run this code, you will first see the initial array printed:
```
Initial array: 
1, 2
3, 4
5, 6
```
And then you will see the array after the insertion:
```
Array after insertion: 
1, 2
3, 7
5, 6
```
As expected, the element 7 has been inserted at the position (1, 1). This program is based on 0-based index, so the position (1, 1) refers to the second row, second column.
