<|asst|>
C# does not have an equivalent to Python's `Union` that would allow a method to return different types of variables. Because of this, we'll need to use `dynamic` in C#. Also, exceptions are handled a bit differently in C#. Here's the C# equivalent:

```C#
public dynamic MathOperator(dynamic a, dynamic b, string operator, bool handleException = false)
{
    try
    {
        switch (operator)
        {
            case "+":
                return a + b;
            case "-":
                if (a < b && handleException) return "Error: Cannot subtract a larger number from a smaller one.";
                return a - b;
            case "*":
                return a * b;
            case "/":
                if (b == 0 && handleException) return "Error: Division by Zero.";
                return a / b;
            default:
                return "Invalid operator.";
        }
    }
    catch (Exception e)
    {
        if (handleException) return e.Message;
        throw;
    }
}
```

This will work similarly to your Python function but note that with `dynamic`, the types of `a` and `b` will not be checked at compile-time like they would be with `Union[int, float]` in Python. This function also assumes that `a` and `b` can be added, subtracted, multiplied and divided, which might not be the case if they're not numbers. Consider adding some kind of type check if you expect other types as inputs.
