I am thinking about buying an iPod touch to make some money on developing apps for the iPhone. I like the concept of the App Store and had a quick look at it with iTunes.
Looks like applications are categorized, to be iPhone OR iPod applications.
Some apps which are free for the iPod seem to cost for iPhone users.

What is the difference of both platforms, or why is the App Store separating them ?
Does it make sense to develop for the iPhone using an iPod touch (beside phone/location related apps) ?

On developer.apple.com I can sign up for selling my Applications on the AppStore for 99$.
Do I have to expect any further costs ?
Is it a problem to develop from outside the US (in my case Germany) ?
<|end|>
<|asst|>
There are no separate applications for iPod Touch and iPhone. The applications are the same for both platforms, they are just labeled as "iPhone Applications" on the App Store. The pricing difference that you're seeing is probably due to some older content which has since been standardized across platforms.

Developing for the iPhone using an iPod Touch can be beneficial, as the majority of applications will run on both devices. However, you will not be able to test certain features such as cellular network usage and GPS functionality.

As for the $99 developer program membership, it's a yearly cost and it's all you need to pay to submit apps to the App Store. The cost includes access to App Store Connect, where you'll submit your apps and updates, as well as access to beta software and extensive development resources.

Developing from outside the U.S. isn't a problem. Once you sign up for the iOS Developer Program, you can sell your apps worldwide on the App Store. However, you must have a bank account in a country where iTunes Connect business supports, which includes Germany.
<|end|>


