Execute the provided Java code which employs multiple inheritance and elucidates the Diamond Problem. Use the given structure of classes and interfaces - A, B, C, D. Analyze step by step what happens when you attempt to run the `main` method inside class D, especially noting which `display` method will be invoked due to the inherent ambiguity created by the multiple inheritance from interfaces B and C:

class A {
    public void display() {
        System.out.println("Class A");
    }
}

interface B extends A {
    default void display() {
        System.out.println("Class B");
    }
}

interface C extends A {
    default void display() {
        System.out.println("Class C");
    }
}

class D implements B, C {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        D obj = new D();
        obj.display();
    }
}
<|end|>
<|asst|>
The given code will not execute successfully due to a compiler error in Java.

Java doesn't allow interfaces to extend classes, i.e., interfaces can only extend other interfaces. Hence, the declaration `interface B extends A` and `interface C extends A` is incorrect and leads to a compile-time error.

The corrected implementation should have all A, B, and C as interfaces or ideally A as class, B and C as interfaces, and D can be a class that implements both B and C. However Java does not support multiple inheritance with respect to classes but it provides partial support for multiple inheritance with interfaces using default methods.

So, an assumed corrected version may look like this:

```java
interface A {
    void display();
}

interface B extends A {
    default void display() {
        System.out.println("Interface B");
    }
}

interface C extends A {
    default void display() {
        System.out.println("Interface C");
    }
}

// D will not compile since it doesn't know which display() to use.
class D implements B, C {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        D obj = new D();
        obj.display();
    }
}
```

When you try to implement both B and C interfaces in class D, you'll encounter the Diamond Problem. This is because B and C are having their own implementations of the display() method and class D has 2 different definitions to inherit from.

This will result in a compile-time error because class D does not know which display() of B or C to use.

To resolve this, you must override the display method in the D class to remove the ambiguity:

```java
class D implements B, C {
    public void display() {
        B.super.display();
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        D obj = new D();
        obj.display();   // It will print: "Interface B"
    }
}
```

Or

```java
class D implements B, C {
    public void display() {
        C.super.display();
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        D obj = new D();
        obj.display();   // It will print: "Interface C"
    }
}
```

In each version, depending on which interface's super method is called in class D (B's or C's), that is the message from the `display()` method that will be printed.
<|end|>


