In this code, we're using the bitwise AND operator on `e`, `f`, and `g`. This operator compares each bit of the first operand to the corresponding bit of the second operand. If both bits are 1, the corresponding result bit is set to 1. Otherwise, the corresponding result bit is set to 0.

The resulting number is then assigned to both `h` and `i`.

Please note that you can use other bitwise operators (like OR `|`, XOR `^`, NOT `~`, shift operators `<<`, `>>`) depending on your specific needs.
