I've just been looking at modifying an Amplify App in order to achieve multi-region deployment. While doing so I was hoping to figure out more about how it works under the hood. From everything I've read the process seems to be -> build the website -> store in S3 -> create a Cloudformation stack -> deploy.
I can't see any of these resources being created though, am very confused over where the front-end code actually rests once built, and have wasted a few hours searching without any luck. I'm hoping someone is able to enlighten me. My two questions are:

1. What resources does Amplify actually use for the front-end/website, and why can't I find them?
2. Where does Amplify store the actual website (javascript, html, css etc)?
<|end|>
<|asst|>
AWS Amplify Console uses the following resources to create and manage your frontend website:

1. AWS Amplify App: This is the main resource created by Amplify Console for your web app. It represents your overall web project and orchestrates the rest of the underlying resources. It's configured with your source repository, build settings, and environment variables.

2. AWS CodeBuild Project: Amplify uses CodeBuild to build your website and generate static assets (javascript, HTML, CSS, etc). This process is defined by the build settings in your Amplify App.

3. Amazon S3 Bucket: Once your site is built, the static assets are uploaded to an S3 bucket provisioned by Amplify Console. This is where the live version of your website resides.

4. Amazon CloudFront Distribution: Amplify then creates a CloudFront distribution pointing to the S3 bucket where your static assets are stored. CloudFront serves as the CDN (Content Delivery Network) in front of your S3 bucket, providing fast, secure, and scalable delivery of your site to end users.

As to why you can't find these resources, it's because they're managed by Amplify Console and stored within AWS's managed account. This is an encapsulated environment which isolates your resources from your primary AWS account to ensure a more secure and predictable service. You do not have direct access to these underlying resources, but can manage them through the Amplify Console. The resources are also not visible in the AWS Management Console for services like S3 and CloudFront.

This also answers your second question: Amplify stores your website's static assets (javascript, HTML, CSS etc) in an S3 bucket managed by Amplify Console itself. However, you won't be able to see, access or modify this bucket directly via the S3 console because it is in AWS's managed account for Amplify.
<|end|>


