I have this problem : Online Median Element In Subarray
Description are as below: Implementing the class `MedianChecker`, which has the following API:
`MedianChecker(int[] arr)` constructs an instance of MedianChecker with the given array `arr`;
`double query(int left, int right)` has arguments such that:
	
`0 &lt;= left &lt;= right &lt; arr.length` representing a subarray of `arr`;
Each `query(...)` returns the median of the elements in `arr[left], arr[left+1], ..., arr[right]`. If the subarray has an even number of elements, return the average of the two middle elements.

Example:
MedianChecker medianChecker = new MedianChecker([1,2,3,4,5,6]);
medianChecker.query(0,5); // returns 3.5
medianChecker.query(0,2); // returns 2
medianChecker.query(2,3); // returns 3.5

Constraints:
`1 &lt;= arr.length &lt;= 20000`
`1 &lt;= arr[i] &lt;= 20000`
For each query, `0 &lt;= left &lt;= right &lt; len(arr)`
The number of queries is at most `10000`
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Here is a Java solution using PriorityQueue. This solution first creates two PriorityQueues in the constructor to balance the larger and smaller half of the numbers. Then, in the query(), it makes a deep copy of these two PriorityQueues and remove the numbers outside the range from smaller and larger PriorityQueues until the remaining numbers fall into the required range. Finally, it returns the median according to the number of remaining elements.

```java
import java.util.PriorityQueue;
import java.util.Comparator;

public class MedianChecker {
    private int[] arr;
    private PriorityQueue<Integer> small;
    private PriorityQueue<Integer> large;

    public MedianChecker(int[] arr) {
        this.arr = arr;
        small = new PriorityQueue<>(Comparator.reverseOrder());
        large = new PriorityQueue<>();
        for (int num : arr) {
            large.add(num);
            small.add(large.poll());
            if (small.size() > large.size()) {
                large.add(small.poll());
            }
        }
    }

    public double query(int left, int right) {
        PriorityQueue<Integer> smallCopy = new PriorityQueue<>(small);
        PriorityQueue<Integer> largeCopy = new PriorityQueue<>(large);
        int totalCount = right - left + 1;
        while (!smallCopy.isEmpty() && small.peek() < left) smallCopy.poll();
        while (!largeCopy.isEmpty() && large.peek() < left) largeCopy.poll();
        while (!smallCopy.isEmpty() && small.peek() > right) smallCopy.poll();
        while (!largeCopy.isEmpty() && large.peek() > right) largeCopy.poll();
        if ((totalCount & 1) == 0) {
            return ((double) smallCopy.peek() + largeCopy.peek()) / 2.0;
        } else if (smallCopy.size() > largeCopy.size()) {
            return smallCopy.peek();
        } else {
            return largeCopy.peek();
        }
    }
}
```

Please note, the time complexity of this solution is high due to the deep copy of PriorityQueue in each query. If you have a large number of queries or the range is large, a more efficient solution based on BST or Segment Tree is needed.
<|end|>


