Create a computational procedure in the JavaScript programming language with the requirement of recursively identifying and outputting every constituent element, regardless of how deeply they are nested, within a specified array. Take note that every individual entity in the array is distinct and may be another array itself. 

For example, given an input like:
var renownedWizards = ["Albus", ["Sirius", "Remus"], ["Severus", ["Minerva", "Hermione"]]]
Your program should output every individual element ("Albus", "Sirius", "Remus", "Severus", "Minerva", "Hermione") from the nested arrays. 

The increased difficulty of this problem comes with the requirement of handling nested arrays, which adds a layer of recursion to the problem.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Below is the JavaScript function that meets the stated requirements. This function, titled 'recursivePrintArrayElements', takes in an array as the parameter and recursively explores that array as well as any nested arrays that it might contain, printing all the elements individually.

```JavaScript
function recursivePrintArrayElements(arr) {
    for (let i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
        if (Array.isArray(arr[i])) {
            recursivePrintArrayElements(arr[i]);
        } else {
            console.log(arr[i]);
        }
    }
}
```

You can use this function like so:

```JavaScript
let renownedWizards = ["Albus", ["Sirius", "Remus"], ["Severus", ["Minerva", "Hermione"]]];
recursivePrintArrayElements(renownedWizards);
```

This code will execute and print "Albus", "Sirius", "Remus", "Severus", "Minerva", "Hermione", each on a new line. 

Here's how it works: 

- The function loops through the array elements.
- If an element is an array itself (which is determined by the Array.isArray() method), the function performs a recursive call and passes this array as the parameter.
- Otherwise, if the element is not an array (which means it's an individual element), the function prints this element via console.log().
