So if you read the docs [here](https://firebase.google.com/docs/firestore/transaction-data-contention), which says that:
> The server client libraries (C#, Go, Java, Node.js, PHP, Python, Ruby) use pessimistic concurrency controls to resolve data contention.
What I don't get, is the use case where I would use a Firestore client on the server side and implement an `UPDATE endpoint`. To avoid data races on this endpoint, we can use a `Firestore transaction` but can I also implement/consider an optimistic locking by adding a `Version` field on a document?
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Yes, you certainly can implement an optimistic locking strategy by adding a `Version` field to your documents. 

Essentially, when you go to update a document, you would first fetch the current version of the document, make your desired changes, increment the version by one, and then try to commit the change. If the version number in the Firestore has changed between when you fetched and attempted the update, the commit would fail, indicating that optimistic concurrency control (OCC) has prevented an outdated update.

However you would need to manually enforce this in your application code by reading the version field from the document, incrementing it, and ensuring that the version has not changed in between the read and the write inside a transaction.

Also note that Firestore’s built-in transaction support does use a form of OCC. When a document is included in a transaction, Firestore checks at commit time that the watched documents didn't change since they were read. If any watched document changed, the transaction fails and can be retried. So, depending on your specific use case, you might not even need a custom `Version` field.

Lastly, it's always crucial to correctly handle transaction failures and implement an adequate retry mechanism. Keep in mind that with OCC, it is common to have transaction conflicts during times of high contention, because any concurrent write to a document included in a transaction can cause that transaction to fail.
<|end|>


