Developing a fully functional web crawler in Python that can archive and categorize scholarly journals and research papers is a highly advanced task and can take a several pages of coding and sophisticated design. It involves several tasks such as requesting access to web pages, parsing HTML code, data extraction, data cleaning, and categorizing the collected data. This also involves respecting the website's robots.txt file which establishes what pages bots are allowed to crawl.

Below is a crude concept of how such a crawler might be started using Python and the libraries BeautifulSoup (for parsing HTML and navigating the parsed HTML tree structure) and requests (for making HTTP requests).

Please note, you will need to adjust this script to fit the structure of the web pages you are intending to scrape. There are also legal and ethical considerations to take into account when writing a web scraper -- always ensure that you have permission to scrape and store the information, and respect the website's robots.txt.

```Python
import requests
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup
import pandas as pd

URL = 'https://www.website.com'  # replace with your starting URL
page = requests.get(URL)
soup = BeautifulSoup(page.content, 'html.parser')

journal_list = []

# Replace 'div' and class_='journal' with appropriate tags identifying the articles or journals 
for journal_entry in soup.find_all('div', class_='journal'):
    title = journal_entry.find('h2')  # replace 'h2' with appropriate HTML tag for title
    author = journal_entry.find('p')  # replace 'p' with appropriate HTML tag for author
    pdf_link = journal_entry.find('a')  # replace 'a' with appropriate HTML tag for pdf link
    if title and author and pdf_link:
        journal_list.append({
            'Title': title.string,
            'Author': author.string,
            'PDF Link': pdf_link['href'],
        })

# Create a dataframe from the list of dictionaries
df = pd.DataFrame(journal_list)
df.to_csv('journal_archive.csv')
```

Remember this is a very basic blueprint and a web crawler for a large domain website will require more intricate crawling patter, handling for different types of web pages (search page, article pages, author info pages etc.) and so on. For large sites with many pages, you would also need to use a library like Scrapy, which is built to build more robust and faster crawlers.

