To display the individual information from the JSON data using HTML, first you need to fetch the data from the RESTful web service using JavaScript.

A dummy RESTful web service URL is used below. Replace this URL with the your actual RESTful web service URL.

```HTML
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Display User Information</title>
</head>
<body>
    <h2>User Information</h2>
    <p id="name"></p>
    <p id="age"></p>
    <p id="address"></p>

    <script>
        window.onload = function() {
            var xhr = new XMLHttpRequest();
            xhr.open('GET', 'http://dummy.restapiexample.com/api/v1/employee/1', true); // Replace with your RESTful service URL.
            xhr.onload = function() {
                if (this.status == 200) {
                    var user = JSON.parse(this.responseText);
                    document.getElementById('name').textContent = 'Name: ' + user.name;
                    document.getElementById('age').textContent = 'Age: ' + user.age;
                    document.getElementById('address').textContent = 'Address: ' + user.address;
                }
            };
            xhr.send();
        };
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

This script fetches data from the RESTful service when the page loads, parses the returned JSON with the `JSON.parse` method, and then dynamically updates the HTML elements with the IDs 'name', 'age', and 'address' to display the user's name, age, and address.

This is a very simple example and does not include any error handling. For production usage you should include error handling for situations like when the server cannot be reached or the returned data is not in the expected format. You might also be pulling data from multiple endpoints or have other requirements that would necessitate a more complex setup.
