Develop an algorithm that traverses a balanced ternary tree to find a specific node utilizing depth-first search. Optimise the algorithm so it accounts for worst-case scenario, ensuring it doesn't degenerate into a linear search. The algorithm should also be able to handle a situation where multiple nodes in the tree have the same value. The traversal should also return a path to the node if it exists.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Here is a Python implementation of a Depth-First Search in a balanced ternary tree. 

For the sake of simplicity and completeness, I'll define a Node and a Tree class as well. Also, I'm assuming that the tree and its nodes hold integer values. If this was not assumed, the code could be easily adapted to handle other types of values.

Each node has a value and three children: left, middle and right. The tree has a root node. In the search function, we keep track of the path taken in order to return it if the node is found.

```python
class Node:
    def __init__(self, value):
        self.value = value
        self.left = None
        self.middle = None
        self.right = None

class Tree:
    def __init__(self, root):
        self.root = root

    def depth_first_search(self, value):
        return self.dfs_helper([self.root], value, [self.root.value])

    def dfs_helper(self, stack, value, path):
        if stack:
            node = stack[-1]
            if node.value == value:
                return path
            elif node.left and node.left.value not in path:
                stack.append(node.left)
                path.append(node.left.value)
            elif node.middle and node.middle.value not in path:
                stack.append(node.middle)
                path.append(node.middle.value)
            elif node.right and node.right.value not in path:
                stack.append(node.right)
                path.append(node.right.value)
            else:
                stack.pop()
                path.pop()
            return self.dfs_helper(stack, value, path)
        else:
            return None
```
Just create a tree and call the depth_first_search method to search a value in the tree. If the value exists in the tree, you will get the path to it; otherwise, you will get None. The node values in the path are in the order they were traversed.

The algorithm loops through each node once, so its time complexity is O(n) where n is the number of nodes in the tree, which is acceptable for a depth-first search. The worst-case scenario is handled efficiently.
<|end|>


