```cpp
#include<vector>
#include<string>

bool below_zero(std::vector<std::string> operations) {
    int balance = 0;
    for(auto& op : operations) {
        balance += std::stoi(op);
        if(balance < 0) {
            return true;
        }
    }
    return false;
}
```
This C++ code keeps the logic the same as the Python version provided: it iterates through the list/vector of operations, adds the value of the operation to the balance, and checks if the balance is below zero. If it ever is, it immediately returns true. If it never is, it returns false after all operations are performed. 

Note that "std::stoi()" in C++ is equivalent to "int()" in Python. Since C++ is a statically-typed language, it is necessary to convert string type to int type before performing addition. The Python version does not have this issue, as Python is dynamically-typed.
