I'm using a MADDPG (RL algorithm) and trying to find out the memory footprint for each layer in it. Maddpg: [https://github.com/openai/maddpg](https://github.com/openai/maddpg)
The neural network is described here.

def mlp_model(input, num_outputs, scope, reuse=False, num_units=64, rnn_cell=None):
# This model takes as input an observation and returns values of all actions
with tf.variable_scope(scope, reuse=reuse):
    out = input
    out = layers.fully_connected(out, num_outputs=num_units, activation_fn=tf.nn.relu)
    out = layers.fully_connected(out, num_outputs=num_units, activation_fn=tf.nn.relu)
    out = layers.fully_connected(out, num_outputs=num_outputs, activation_fn=None)
    return out


I wanted to calculate the memory footprint when training for each layer.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
The memory footprint of a layer in a neural network is mainly determined by the number and precision of parameters it holds. 

In the `mlp_model()` function, there are three layers. Each layer is fully connected and thus has a weight and bias for each neuron, where each neuron connects to each neuron of the previous layer. 

For example, if you have `n` neurons in the previous layer, `m` neurons in the current layer, and you use `float32` data type for parameters, the memory footprint of the weights for this layer is `n * m * 4 bytes`. The bias will take an additional `m * 4 bytes`.

Based on this, we can calculate memory footprint of each layer:

- The first layer has `input_shape[1]` neurons in the previous layer (input) and `num_units` neurons in the first layer, so weights for this layer will take `input_shape[1] * num_units * 4 bytes`. Bias will take an additional `num_units * 4 bytes`.

- The second layer has `num_units` neurons in both previous and current layers, so weights will take `num_units * num_units * 4 bytes`. Bias will take additional `num_units * 4 bytes`.

- The last layer has `num_units` neurons in the previous layer and `num_outputs` neurons in the current layer, so weights for it will take `num_units * num_outputs * 4 bytes`. Bias will take `num_outputs * 4 bytes`.

Remember, these are storage requirements for the parameters of these layers. During forward and backward propagation, you will need additional memory to store intermediate results.

It's also important to remember that this is an oversimplification. Actual memory consumption can be influenced by various factors, such as specific implementation details in TensorFlow and the batch size. 

To get a more accurate picture of memory usage, you may want to use memory profiling tools (e.g., TensorBoard).
<|end|>


