I want to model some count data. I noticed that I have some under-dispersion (mean is 1.3, variance is 0.8), so I have seen some threads suggesting a quasi-poisson model. Is it possible to somehow compare these models and establish which one provides a better fit? I believe the quasi-poisson model does not have an associated AIC value with it, so I need to thing of another method.
Here is a histogram showing my outcome:
[](https://i.stack.imgur.com/G33Kc.png)
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Yes, model comparisons can be performed even when AIC is not available. There are several ways to evaluate and compare the performance of statistical models :

1. **Cross-validation:** Divide your data into training, validation, and test sets. Fit your models using the training data, adjust the parameters with the validation data, and then evaluate how well each model predicts the test data.

2. **Residual analysis:** Examine the residuals (the observed minus the predicted values) of your models. In general, the residuals should be normally distributed and centered around zero. Models with residuals that deviate from this pattern may not be providing a good fit to your data.

3. **Likelihood ratio test:** It can be used to compare nested models, i.e., models where one can be obtained from the other by imposing constraints on the parameters. This may not apply directly in your case (as Poisson and quasi-Poisson are not strictly nested), but could be potentially used with some adaptations.

4. **Deviance and Pearson Chi-Sq:** In the case of quasi-Poisson, one can use the deviance or Pearson chi-squared residuals as a measure of goodness-of-fit. The closer these values are to 1, the better the model fits the data. These values can be found in the summary output of a glm model in R.

A potential issue with under-dispersed count data, such as yours, is that standard models like Poisson or negative binomial might not fit well, due to the low variance. In this situation, alternative models such as the Hurdle or zero-inflated Poisson/negative binomial, might be a better choice. These models can handle both excessive zeros and under-dispersion in count data.
<|end|>


