Go (also known as Golang) is a statically typed, compiled language known for its simplicity and efficiency, while Python is an interpreted, dynamic language known for its ease of use and libraries. However, Go lacks the extensive natural language processing (NLP) libraries that Python supports, such as NLTK and Spacy. Therefore, direct translation of the above Python script to Go isn't feasible. 

Go libraries for NLP are more limited, and usually requires manually handling many of the functionalities readily available in libraries like NLTK or transform to APIs.

Here is an example of text processing in Go, but the capabilities are much more limited:

```go
package main

import (
	"strings"
	"io/ioutil"
	"fmt"
)

func PreprocessText(text string) []string {
	// Splits the text into words
	words := strings.Fields(text)

	// Converts all words to lowercase
	for i := range words {
		words[i] = strings.ToLower(words[i])
	}

	return words
}

func main() {
	// Read your text data
	data, err := ioutil.ReadFile("mydata.txt")
	if err != nil {
		panic(err)
	}

	// Preprocess the text
	preprocessedData := PreprocessText(string(data))

	// Displays the first 10 processed words, if they exist
	if len(preprocessedData) > 10 {
		fmt.Println(preprocessedData[:10])
	} else {
		fmt.Println(preprocessedData)
	}
}
```
The above Go code reads a text file, splits the text into words, converts the words to lowercase, and then prints the first 10 words. Please note this doesn't cover stopwords removal or lemmatization as that is relatively complex and needs additional packages or custom functionality in Golang. For advanced text processing tasks, Python with NLTK and Spacy is recommended.
