Develop an advanced JavaScript algorithm that accepts three integral numerical inputs and archives the most substantial value in a predetermined variable. Now, add functionality for handling negative numbers and exceptional cases where all three numbers are equal.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Here's a simple JavaScript algorithm to fulfill requirements:

```javascript
function maxNumber(num1, num2, num3){

  if(num1 === num2 && num2 === num3){
      return "Numbers are equal";
    }
  
  let maxValue = num1;
  
  if (num2 > maxValue){ 
    maxValue = num2;
  }

  if(num3 > maxValue){
    maxValue = num3;
  }

  return maxValue;  
}
```

In this function, it handles the exceptional case when all 3 numbers are equal by checking if num1 equals num2 and num2 equals num3 at the beginning. 

For the remaining cases, it assigns the first number to `maxValue` and iterates through the next two values to check if they are greater than `maxValue`. If any of the number is greater than `maxValue`, it gets reassigned to that number. By this, `maxValue` will always hold the maximum value among the three numbers, and it handles negative numbers as well.

You can call the function with three numbers as the argument to get the maximum value:

```javascript
console.log(maxNumber(-3,-2,-1));  //Output: -1
console.log(maxNumber(5,5,5));    //Output: Numbers are equal
console.log(maxNumber(10,20,20));  //Output: 20
```
<|end|>


