<|user|>
I have used IPC in Win32 code a while ago - critical sections, events, and semaphores.
How is the scene in the .NET environment?
Are there any tutorial explaining all available options and when to use and why?
<|end|>
<|asst|>
IPC, short for Inter-Process Communication, refers to several techniques and technologies that are used to share data among multiple threads in one or more processes. In .NET, many of these core techniques remain the same, but are covered under the System.Threading namespace and are designed to be easier to use and manage than their Win32 counterparts.

Here are some of the common IPC-related features and techniques that you may use in .NET:

1. `Mutex`: Mutexes are used to ensure that only one thread is performing a particular critical activity at any given time. This is often used to ensure that shared resources do not have contention.

2. `Semaphore`: Semaphores allow a limited number of threads to access a resource or pool of resources.

3. `Monitor`: Monitor is a more flexible alternative to Mutex that wraps both mutual exclusion and conditional variable functionality into a single class.

4. `EventWaitHandle`: Like an event in Win32, EventWaitHandle allows one or more threads to wait until they are signaled by another thread.

5. `ReaderWriterLockSlim`: This is an advanced lock that allows multiple threads to read data simultaneously, but ensures that only one thread can write data at the same time.

6. `Barrier`: A barrier is a threading construct that allows you to specify a point in your code where all participating threads must reach before any can continue.

7. `Delegates`: Delegates or callback methods can be used for inter-process communication in .NET. 

8. `Pipes`: Named pipes and anonymous pipes provide a way to pass data between processes similar to the way files are used.

9. `Remoting`: .NET remoting can be used to communicate between different application domains, processes or even different computers.

10. `Message Queuing (MSMQ)`: MSMQ can be used to pass messages between different applications in .NET.

11. `Windows Communication Foundation (WCF)`: WCF is a framework for building service-oriented applications. With WCF, you can send messages between services and clients in various ways.

You may find a variety of tutorials and resources online that cover these different options in more detail. MSDN is a great place to start, as it often provides comprehensive documentation on these different IPC techniques, and many other programming websites and forums have detailed examples and explanations as well. The exact tool you choose will depend on the scale and requirements of your project, as well as personal preference.
<|end|>


