Anybody know why I'm getting this and how to prevent it?

#!/usr/bin/env zsh

setopt nullglob
setopt extendedglob

for file in **/*; do
  if file -b $file | grep -q "text"; then
    raw=$(<$file)

    # Remove trailing whitespace
    raw=${raw//[[:blank:]]##$'\n'/$'\n'}

    # Other stuff like removing CR+LF works fine
    # raw=${raw//$'\r'}

    echo $file
    printf "%s\n\n" $raw > $file
  fi
done
<|end|>
<|asst|>
The script you're running is a script for removing trailing whitespaces from text files. The problem you're encountering lies in the following line of your script:

`printf "%s\n\n" $raw > $file`

This line is trying to write the content into the file while the file is still open and being read, and this can cause issues(or even data loss in some cases). 

Instead of reading and writing to the same file at the same time, you can write your processed data to a temporary file, and then replace your original file with the temporary file. Here's a modified version of your script:

```zsh
#!/usr/bin/env zsh

setopt nullglob
setopt extendedglob

for file in **/*; do
  if file -b $file | grep -q "text"; then
    raw=$(<$file)

    # Remove trailing whitespace
    raw=${raw//[[:blank:]]##$'\n'/$'\n'}

    # Other stuff like removing CR+LF works fine
    # raw=${raw//$'\r'}

    echo $file
    printf "%s\n\n" $raw > $file.tmp
    mv $file.tmp $file
  fi
done
```

Please remember that modifying files in-place is a dangerous operation especially when working with important files, always make sure to have a backup before running such operation on a directory. 

Also note that grep -q "text" might match files which you do not wish to process like binary files which happen to have the string "text" included in the file command output. It might be better to use a more precise tool or method for identifying the files you want to process.
<|end|>


