What is the optimal methodology for constructing a standard SQL Inner Join statement while ensuring syntactical accuracy and adhering to best practices, optimized for search efficiency?
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Here are the best practices for constructing an SQL Inner Join statement:

1. Select Only Necessary Fields: It is always good to retrieve only those columns which are really necessary. The SQL statement should avoid using "SELECT *". 

2. Use Aliases for Tables and Columns: Using aliases for tables and columns in your SQL statement makes it more readable. Aliases also eliminate the need for typing out long table names.

3. Use ON Clause to Specify Join Condition: The ON clause is used to specify the relationship between tables. It is good practice to always use it to improve readability and understanding of the relationship.

4. Use Indexed Columns for Join: Using indexed columns in the Join condition makes your Join operations more efficient.

So, the optimal SQL Inner Join statement based on the above points would look like this:

```sql
SELECT A.column1, B.column2
FROM table1 AS A
INNER JOIN table2 AS B ON A.common_field = B.common_field
```

In the case where you want to join more than two tables, remember to join tables on their indexed columns and keep your joins as simple as possible. 

```sql
SELECT A.column1, B.column2, C.column3
FROM table1 AS A
INNER JOIN table2 AS B ON A.common_field = B.common_field
INNER JOIN table3 AS C ON A.common_field = C.common_field
```

However, the actual optimization of an SQL statement depends on the specifics of the database schema, indexes available, the database server itself, and data distribution in the databases.

And remember, to check the performance of your SQL statements, use EXPLAIN ANALYZER tool of your SQL environment. This tool gives you a low-level understanding of how your SQL statement works. With this knowledge, you can then restructure your SQL statement to make it even more efficient.
<|end|>


