<|asst|>
To animate an SVG to mimic the motion of a ripple or wave is complex as it requires knowledge of both SVGs and CSS animations. To accomplish this, there are many resources online, but here's a simplified step by step guide to do this:

1. Convert your SVG into a Path:
SVG animations usually require your SVG to be in terms of path elements, that way, they can be easily manipulated using the `d` attribute of the svg element. There are online converters available where you can upload your SVG and it converts the shapes into SVG paths.

2. Include the SVG Path in HTML:
Embed your SVG code in your HTML file. It could be directly in the HTML file or referenced from an external file. Make sure to use the correct dimensions.

3. Apply CSS Animations:
Using CSS animations, you can animate the SVG path. For the undulating effect, use the keyframes rule with changing the `d` attribute for the wave motion.

Note: CSS animations for this could be complex, as manually inputting keyframes with different control points will be an arduous task. Using a JavaScript library like GSAP or a SVG animator tool like snap.svg, anime.js, or velocity.js could save you lots of work.

Here is a simple example using CSS for the animation.

```html
<svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="1000px" height="150px" version="1.1">
    <path id="wave" d=""/>  
</svg>

<style>

@keyframes wave_animation {
  0% {
    d: path('...');  /* starting shape */
  }
  50% {
    d: path('...');  /* Intermediate shape (representing the ripple effect)*/
  }
  100% {
    d: path('...');  /* Ending shape (same as starting shape)*/
  }
}

#wave {
  animation-name: wave_animation;
  animation-duration: 2s;
  animation-iteration-count: infinite;
}
<style>
```

Remember, this is a simple example and real-life use cases may require a more robust solution.
<|end|>


