I am working on an ASP.NET web application, it seems to be working properly when I try to debug it in Visual Studio. However when I emulate heavy load, IIS crashes without any trace -- log entry in the system journal is very generic, "The World Wide Web Publishing service terminated unexpectedly. It has done this 4 time(s)."
How is it possible to get more information from IIS to troubleshoot this problem?
<|end|>
<|asst|>
1. Enable Failed Request Tracing: IIS has a feature called Failed Request Tracing that can be used for troubleshooting. This captures traces on your requests, including time-taken data which can help you figure out what's happening during the times you're experiencing slowness.

2. Event Viewer: Go to Windows Logs > Application or System and see if there are any errors, warnings, or information events from w3wp or any from the Source of Windows Error Reporting.

3. IIS Logs: Enable the IIS logs and check them to see if they give any extra information. In some cases, you may require to enable additional logging. You can do this by going to IIS > Your Site > Logging > Select Fields, and then select the options you need.

4. DebugDiag: Install Debug Diagnostic Tool, the DebugDiag tool is designed to assist in troubleshooting issues such as hangs, slow performance, memory leaks or fragmentation, and crashes in any user-mode process.

5. Event Tracing for Windows (ETW): ETW is the go-to tracing utility built into the Windows kernel and is used by many Windows applications. It provides a detailed view of what is happening within an application at runtime.

6. PerfView: PerfView is a performance-analysis tool that helps isolate CPU and memory-related performance issues. 

7. Health Monitoring and Performance Counters: IIS Health Monitoring can provide important data and alerts when IIS is having problems, and Performance counters can help you to understand the trend.

Remember, debugging production-level issues often involves a high level of detailed tracing and logging. Always ensure that tracing and logging have minimal impact on the overall performance of your application. After troubleshooting, don't forget to turn off detailed error messages (such as trace, etc), they can expose your application to information disclosure security risks.
<|end|>


