        border: 1px solid #dddddd;
        text-align: left;
        padding: 8px;
    }
</style>
```

And javascript with a simple filter function that removes the row if its age is less than 30:
```javascript
<script>
    function filterRows() {
        let table, rows, ageCell, i;
        table = document.getElementById("myTable");
        rows = table.getElementsByTagName("tr");
        for (i = 0; i < rows.length; i++) {
            ageCell = rows[i].getElementsByTagName("td")[2];
            if (ageCell) {
                let age = parseInt(ageCell.innerHTML);
                if (age < 30) {
                    rows[i].style.display = "none";
                }
            }
        }
    }
    filterRows();  // call function
</script>
```

In real-world scenarios, the table would have multiple rows and the JavaScript code would be attached to a button or an event. For simplicity, the JavaScript code is run automatically when the page is loaded. The function `filterRows` hides all rows where age is less than 30.
