You might want to look into using auditing gems such as auditor or audited. These gems allow you to track all changes to a model including who made the changes. Another gem that you might find useful is the paper_trail gem, which also has a similar functionality.

If you want to monitor user behaviour more closely you could use analytic tools like Google Analytics or even better, use a more specialized tool like Mixpanel or woopra which can track individual user activities and actions in a detailed fashion.

You can also use logging gems like lograge or request-log-analyzer to collect and analyze request logs for more detailed insight.

Lastly, if you know exactly which controller/actions you want to track you can use custom events tracking with Ahoy gem which let's you track both visits and individual events in your application.

Please note that which solution you should choose depends on the specific requirements of your use case and the amount of details you need about user actions.
