Formulate a cascading style sheets (CSS) sequence involving an HTML component that manipulates transparency levels in order to exhibit a disappearing text effect that displays "Welcome to My Website", situated against a backdrop conveying a gradual transition between multiple color hues, a gradient.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Here's step by step solution using HTML and CSS:

HTML Content:
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
    <head>
        <link rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" href="styles.css">
    </head>
    <body>
        <div id="gradient">
            <h1 class="fadeEffect">Welcome to My Website</h1>
        </div>
    </body>
</html>
```

CSS Content (styles.css):
```css
#gradient {
    width: 100%;
    height: 100vh;
    background: linear-gradient(to right, red, orange, yellow, green, blue, indigo, violet);
    display: flex;
    justify-content: center;
    align-items: center;
}

.fadeEffect {
    font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
    color: white;
    font-size: 3em;
    animation: fade 3s infinite linear;
}

@keyframes fade {
    0% {opacity: 1;}
    50% {opacity: 0;}
    100% {opacity: 1;}
}
```

Here is the explanation of the CSS code:

1. The `#gradient` CSS rule defines the gradient transition as the background of the screen, from one colour to another in the specified direction.

2. The `.fadeEffect` CSS class is where the text fading effect occurs. It is given a solid color, and the `animation` property is used to attach the keyframes needed to achieve the fading effect. The `fade` animation which is defined using the `@keyframes` will control the opacity over time.

3. The `@keyframes` CSS rule is really what controls the disappearing and reappearing effect of your text. By controlling the opacity at different points in the animation (from 0 to 100% of the animation's duration), we're able to make the text seem like it's fading out and in.

Just make sure you link your CSS file properly to your HTML file. Replace `'styles.css'` with the actual path.

This just produces a simple fading effect. Depending on the complexity of the effect you're after, you may need to use JavaScript or a library like jQuery.
<|end|>


