I've got a local .mdf SQL database file that I am using for an integration testing project. Everything works fine on the initial machine I created the project, database, etc. on, but when I try to run the project on another machine I get the following:



I figure while I am investigating this problem I would also ask the community here to see if someone has already overcome this.

The exception occurs when I instantiate the new data context. I am using LINQ-to-SQL.


m_TransLogDataContext = new TransLogDataContext ();



Let me know if any additional info is needed. Thanks.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
There could be a few reasons why you are getting this error. I've listed some possible solutions:

1. Misconfigured connection string
Check if your connection string is properly configured and adaptable when switching between computers. You can find it in the app.config or web.config file. Maybe the SQL Server instance name is different on the new machine.

```xml
<connectionStrings>
    <add name="YourDataContext" 
         connectionString="Data Source=.\SQLEXPRESS;AttachDbFilename=|DataDirectory|\yourdb.mdf;Integrated Security=True;User Instance=True"
         providerName="System.Data.SqlClient" />
</connectionStrings>
```
Make sure the `.|DataDirectory|` path is correctly leading to the `.mdf` file location.

2. SQL Server Service Issue
Make sure the SQL Server (SQLEXPRESS) service is running on the other machine.

3. SQL Server version compatibility
SQL Server Express edition should be installed on the other machine and it should be the same or higher version than your `.mdf` file.

4. Permissions Issue
Check if the account (Network service, local system, etc.) running your application (or your web server like IIS) has sufficient permission to access the `.mdf` file.

5. User Instances Issue or Deprecated Feature
User instances in connection string (`User Instance=True`) is a feature designed for simplicity of deployment but it is deprecated. You may want to consider not using this feature, especially if your project is not dependent on it.

6. Detach .mdf file from SQL Server instance
If you manually attached it to your SQL Server instance on the first machine, you would need to detach it before using it in another application. It can be done through the SQL Server Management Studio.

7. Use SQL Server Management Studio to attach .mdf file
Instead of relying on your application to attach the `.mdf` file, you could use the SQL Server Management Studio to manually attach the database and then update your connection string to point to the database using a server/databasename reference. 

Take note: Always backup your `.mdf` file before making changes.
<|end|>


