I would like to intercept the event in a .NET Windows Forms TabControl when the user has changed tab by double-clicking the tab (instead of just single-clicking it).

Do you have any idea of how I can do that?
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Unfortunately, there's no built-in event for detecting double-click tab change in a TabControl. But you can subscribe to the MouseDoubleClick event and calculate if the double click happened on a tab. Here's how:

```csharp
public class CustomTabControl : TabControl
{
    public delegate void TabPageDoubleClickEventHandler(object sender, TabPageDoubleClickEventArgs e);
    public event TabPageDoubleClickEventHandler TabPageDoubleClick;
    
    protected override void OnMouseDoubleClick(MouseEventArgs e)
    {
        Rectangle mouseClickRectangle = new Rectangle(e.X, e.Y, 1, 1);
        for (int i = 0; i < TabCount; i++)
        {
            if (GetTabRect(i).IntersectsWith(mouseClickRectangle))
            {
                TabPageDoubleClick?.Invoke(this, new TabPageDoubleClickEventArgs(TabPages[i]));
                return;
            }
        }
        base.OnMouseDoubleClick(e);
    }
}

public class TabPageDoubleClickEventArgs : EventArgs
{
    public TabPageDoubleClickEventArgs(TabPage tabPage)
    {
        TabPage = tabPage;
    }
    
    public TabPage TabPage { get; private set; }
}
```
You can use the `CustomTabControl` instead of the regular `TabControl` and subscribe to the `TabPageDoubleClick` event that will be raised when you double-click a tab.

Here's how you would use it:

```csharp
customTabControl1.TabPageDoubleClick += CustomTabControl1_TabPageDoubleClick;

private void CustomTabControl1_TabPageDoubleClick(object sender, TabPageDoubleClickEventArgs e)
{
    // Handle event here. e.TabPage gives the double clicked tab page.
}
```
This should give you a double click event for tab changes.
