Here is a sample program in C that implements an arithmetic calculator with basic operations and some advanced mathematical functions. It also provides trigonometric and logarithmic calculations. Just keep in mind, this is a fundamental implementation and it doesn't have any error handling and other features that a full-feature calculator should have!

Please your compiler settings may need to include the math library during compilation - in case it doesn't do this by default.

```C
#include <stdio.h>
#include <math.h>

int main() {
    int choice;
    double num1, num2, result;

    printf("Choose operation:\n");
    printf("1. Addition\n2. Subtraction\n3. Multiplication\n4. Division\n5. Sin\n6. Cos\n7. Tan\n8. Log\n");
    scanf("%d", &choice);

    if (choice >= 1 && choice <= 4) {
        printf("Enter first operand: ");
        scanf("%lf", &num1);
        printf("Enter second operand: ");
        scanf("%lf", &num2);
    } else if (choice >= 5 && choice <= 8) {
        printf("Enter the number: ");
        scanf("%lf", &num1);
    }

    switch(choice) {
        case 1:
            result = num1 + num2;
            break;
        case 2:
            result = num1 - num2;
            break;
        case 3:
            result = num1 * num2;
            break;
        case 4:
            if (num2 != 0)
                result = num1 / num2;
            else {
                printf("Error! Division by zero.");
                return -1;  
            }
            break;
        case 5:
            result = sin(num1);
            break;
        case 6:
            result = cos(num1);
            break;
        case 7:
            result = tan(num1);
            break;
        case 8:
            if (num1 > 0)
                result = log(num1);
            else {
                printf("Error! Logarithm of negative value.");
                return -1;
            }
            break;
        default:
            printf("Error! Invalid operation.");
            return -1;
    }

    printf("Result: %.2lf\n", result);
    return 0;
}
```

This program first prompts the user to choose an operation, then asks for operands based on the operation type. Arithmetic operations are performed directly, whereas advanced mathematical operations use the corresponding functions from the math library.
