<|user|>
Using Java, write a program to detect a cycle in a linked list and return the length of the cycle.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Firstly, to detect a cycle in a linked list, we can use Floyd's cycle finding algorithm also known as Tortoise and Hare algorithm. Then to find length, we keep one pointer where it was when cycle was discovered and keep incrementing the other till they are same again.

In Java, the Linked List node can be defined as:

```java
class Node {
  int data;
  Node next;
  Node(int data) {
    this.data = data;
    this.next = null;
  }
}
```
Then, the program for detecting cycle and returning its size can be defined as:

```java
public class Main {

  class Node {
    int data;
    Node next;

    Node(int data) {
      this.data = data; 
      this.next = null;
    }
  }

  boolean hasCycle(Node head) {
    if (head == null || head.next == null) {
      return false;
    }

    Node slow = head;
    Node fast = head.next;
    while (slow != fast) {
      if (fast == null || fast.next == null) {
        return false;
      }
      slow = slow.next;
      fast = fast.next.next;
    }

    // If loop exists then find the length
    int length = 1;
    fast = fast.next;
    while (slow != fast) {
      fast = fast.next;
      length++;
    }

    // length of the cycle
    return length;
  }
}
```

In this program, slow and fast are two pointers pointing to the head of the linked list. We move slow pointer one step at a time whereas fast pointer two steps at a time. If there is a cycle in the linked list, the fast pointer eventually catch up to the slow pointer and they both will pointing to the same node. Afterwards, we move the fast pointer one step at a time in the cycle until it meet the slow pointer again to get the length of the cycle.

Please note this program only works correctly when there is a cycle in the list. You need to create a mechanism to insert and print nodes to see the program in action as that part is not included in this code.
<|end|>


