Design a well-structured cascading style sheet (CSS) script to aesthetically enhance hypermedia linkages, which are represented by uniform resource locators (URL), embedded within a pre-selected digital document that constitutes a fraction of the vast interconnected network known as the World Wide Web.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
The request seems quite sophisticated but it sounds like you want to style hyperlinks (URLs). Here's a simple example of how to style a hyperlink using CSS:

```css
/* This will target all the hyperlinks in your HTML document */
a {
    text-decoration: none; /* Removes the underline that appears by default on links */
    color: #0066ff; /* Change the default link color */
    background-color: #f2f2f2; /* Change the background color */
    padding: 5px; /* Add some padding */
    border-radius: 5px; /* Add rounded corners to the link */
    font-weight: bold; /* Make the text bold */
}

/* This will target the link when the mouse hovers over it */
a:hover {
    color: #ff6600; /* Change the link color when hovered */
    background-color: #d9d9d9; /* Change the background color when hovered */
    text-decoration: underline; /* Apply an underline when hovered */
}

/* This will target the link if it has been clicked (activated) */
a:active {
    color: #ff0000; /* Change link color when clicked */
}

/* This will target the link if it has been visited */
a:visited {
    color: #800080; /* Change link color when it has been visited */
}
```
Just remember this CSS should be placed within a `<style>` tag inside the `<head>` section of your HTML, or it can be linked externally using `<link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css">` where "styles.css" is the name of your CSS file.

We also have different states for our hyperlinks:

- a:link - a normal, unvisited link
- a:visited - a link the user has visited
- a:hover - a link when the user mouses over it
- a:active - a link the moment it is clicked

Change the values to suit your design needs.
<|end|>


