Create a C# program that takes an input of an array of integers, translates each number from digit format into written English words, and returns them as strings. The program must also handle negative numbers and numbers up to one million inclusively. Use this array: int[] numbers = {47, 981, 3521, -56, 1000000}
<|end|>
<|asst|>
The following is an example of a C# program that converts an array of integers into their equivalent English words using the Humanizer library. It first checks if the number is negative, if so it uses "minus" to represent the negative and converts the absolute value to its English equivalent. 

The Humanizer library in C# provides a function called `ToWords()` which transforms a number into string format words.

To use the Humanizer library, you first have to install it via NuGet package manager. You can do so by entering `Install-Package Humanizer` in the NuGet package manager console.

Here is the C# code:

```csharp
using System;
using Humanizer;

class Program
{
    // The main function
    static void Main()
    {
        // An array of integer numbers
        int[] numbers = { 47, 981, 3521, -56, 1000000 };

        // Iterate through each number in the array
        foreach (int number in numbers)
        {
            string numberAsWords;

            // Check if the number is negative
            if (number < 0)
            {
                // If it is negative, convert the absolute value to words and add 'minus'
                numberAsWords = "minus " + Math.Abs(number).ToWords();
            }
            else 
            {
                // If it is positive, just convert the number to words
                numberAsWords = number.ToWords();
            }

            // Print the number in word format
            Console.WriteLine(numberAsWords);
        }
    }
}
```

This will output:

```
forty-seven
nine hundred and eighty-one
three thousand five hundred and twenty-one
minus fifty-six
one million
```

Please note this code may not perfectly handle all numbers up to one million due to some limitations in the Humaniser library.
<|end|>


