What is the best way to configure iPlanet/Sun ONE be the HTTP/HTTPS front end to a JBoss/Tomcat application?

Are there any performance considerations?

How would this compare with the native integration between Apache httpd and Tomcat?
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Configuring iPlanet (known as Oracle iPlanet Web Server) or Sun ONE (known as Sun Java System Web Server) to act as the HTTP/HTTPS frontend to a JBoss/Tomcat application can be done using a reverse proxy or AJP connectors. 

Here's a way to achieve that:

1. Install and configure your iPlanet/Sun ONE server.
2. Make sure your JBoss/Tomcat are set up and running.
3. Set up a reverse proxy on the iPlanet/Sun ONE to redirect requests to JBoss/Tomcat.

You'd have to edit your `obj.conf` file (which you'd typically find in the server’s configuration files directory) to include something like this (for an application running on JBoss/Tomcat at http://localhost:8080/myapp):

```
<Object name="default">
    NameTrans fn="pfx2dir" from="/myapp" dir="/myapp" name="myapp"
    <Object name="myapp">
        Service fn="proxy-reverse" server="http://localhost:8080"
    </Object>
</Object>
```
For reverse proxies, when a request hits the iPlanet/Sun ONE server at http://myserver.com/myapp, it gets forwarded internally to http://localhost:8080/myapp.

For AJP connectors, you'd need to set up a JK connector, but this doesn't seem to be as straightforward.

Some Performance Considerations:

- Consider setting up a load balancer if you anticipate a high load, to distribute the load across several application server instances.
- Monitor your application server instances consistently.
- Consider clustering your JBoss instances for better reliability.

Comparing iPlanet/Sun ONE with Apache httpd:

- iPlanet/Sun ONE servers tend to be more suitable for enterprise-level Java applications due to their robustness, scalability and comprehensive Java EE support.
- Apache's httpd server is more flexible in terms of configuration and has a wide range of modules available. Also, Apache has native support for integration with Tomcat using AJP connectors.
- In terms of performance, this could depend on the specifics of your application and setup. Both have been used in high-load scenarios, and the performance would ultimately depend on many factors including network infrastructure, server hardware, and application architecture.

In general, if you're already heavily using Sun/Oracle products, such as Solaris and other Java systems, sticking with iPlanet/Sun ONE might be a better option, thanks to better integration. If you’re looking for a more generic, widely supported server that fits nicely with many diverse components, Apache HTTP Server might be a better fit.
<|end|>


