Is it true that the error rate of a 1-nearest neighbor classifier in training is zero and when there is infinite data, the MAP estimate will eventually become the same as the MLE estimate regardless of the chosen prior?
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Yes, it is true that the error rate of a 1-nearest neighbor classifier in training is zero. The model simply memorizes the training data, and hence, when a query is made with training data, it returns the correct label. The classifier assigns a label to a new observation by simply choosing the label of the closest observation in the training set. When the nearest neighbor is based on the training data, the classifier will always find an exact match (distance = 0), returning a 0% error rate.

For the second part of your question, as the sample size approaches infinity, the MAP (Maximum A Posteriori) estimation converges towards the MLE (Maximum Likelihood Estimation), given that the prior is true. This is due to the Law of large numbers, as the data will overwhelm the prior distribution, making the MAP estimate essentially equivalent to the MLE estimate. However, it's important to note that this is valid only if the true prior distribution is known. The convergence may not happen if the chosen prior is substantially incorrect.
<|end|>


