Create a Java function that converts a string, which can include a decimal or be in exponential notation, to a double value, while handling potential parsing exceptions.

String numString1 = "123.45";
String numString2 = "1.2345e2";
String numString3 = "NaN";
String numString4 = "1.45e-2";
<|end|>
<|asst|>
You can solve this problem by utilizing the `Double.parseDouble` method in the Java standard library, which can deal with standard decimal notation and exponential notation. You can add exception handling for situations when parseDouble fails due to faulty input.

Here is a simple implementation in Java:

```java
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String numString1 = "123.45";
        String numString2 = "1.2345e2";
        String numString3 = "NaN";
        String numString4 = "1.45e-2";
        
        System.out.println(convertStringToDouble(numString1));
        System.out.println(convertStringToDouble(numString2));
        System.out.println(convertStringToDouble(numString3));
        System.out.println(convertStringToDouble(numString4));
    }

    public static Double convertStringToDouble(String numString) {
        try {
            return Double.parseDouble(numString);
        } catch (NumberFormatException e) {
            System.out.println(numString + " cannot be converted to double. " + e.getMessage());
            return null;
        }
    }
}
```
This program will print:

```
123.45
123.45
NaN
0.0145
```
In cases where it cannot parse the double (for example, `convertStringToDouble("Hello World")`), it will output an error message to the console, and return `null`.
<|end|>


