<|asst|>
Looking at your HTML and CSS code, the structure seems fine and there are no inheritances present that can override your styles. CSS properties are also used properly and they don't contradict each other, nor do they create any side effects, at a first glance. Therefore, the most likely issue could be some unseen factors like external stylesheets or scripts that are affecting your elements in ways you aren't expecting.

Let's break down your code to see what could go wrong:

1. `#wrapper` is set to occupy the entirety of the screen with `100%` width and height. This, in turn, defines the boundaries for your inside `div` elements.

2. `#content` and `#additional` both are set to take `40%` of the `#wrapper` element's width, colored `red` and `blue` respectively. They are also floated to `right` and `left` respectively. These styles should not conflict and should divide your screen into `60%-40%` ratio with empty space on the left.

Things to consider:

- If the "expected style" you're referring to is not being reflected on the screen, it might be because of an override of these styles somewhere else in your CSS, which affects the id selectors - `#content` or `#additional`.

- Keep in mind that using `id` as a selector in CSS has a high specificity, so it will override other styles provided in the stylesheet. If your CSS file is linked after another CSS file modifying the same attributes, your styles would take precedence. Conversely, if the other CSS file is linked after yours, its styles would take precedence.

- Also, the inline style in your HTML code will take precedence over any external stylesheets. In your HTML, you've applied `style="float: right;"` to `#content` and `style="float: left;"` to `#additional`. Since these are the same as in your CSS file, there shouldn't be a problem.

- `float` properties can sometimes cause unexpected results such as elements overlapping or behaving unexpectedly, so make sure to check if that is causing your problem.

- If you're expecting your design to be responsive with respect to different screen sizes, then using percents (`%`) instead of fixed sizes (like `px`) is definitely the right approach. However, you don't have any media queries in your code, so your layout would remain the same regardless of the screen size.

Generally, debugging CSS involves using browser's built-in developer tools to inspect elements and see what styles are being applied or overridden. This is a handy tool to check and modify your styles real-time.
