Craft a multi-language modular webpage to bid farewell to users. The web page should include a centered heading that reads "Goodbye" in English, and two buttons to switch the language of "Goodbye" to either French or Spanish. The webpage should also include a form with input fields for the user's first name, last name, and email address. When the user submits the form, the page should send an AJAX request to a server, which will respond with a personalized farewell message that includes the user's name and is displayed under the heading. This response should be handled asynchronously without refreshing the entire page. 

Please ensure the webpage and scripts are efficient, scalable, and follow best practices for performance improvement. Proper error handling and browser compatibility should also be considered. The webpage should still function properly and provide an acceptable user experience even if the server does not respond or responds with an error.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Here's an outline of a solution using HTML, CSS, and Javascript (Using jQuery for AJAX request)

HTML:
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
   <title>Farewell Page</title>
   <link rel='stylesheet' type='text/css' href='styles.css'>
</head>
<body>
   <h1 id="farewell-heading" class="center">Goodbye</h1>
   <button onclick="changeLanguage('French')">French</button>
   <button onclick="changeLanguage('Spanish')">Spanish</button>

   <form id="farewell-form">
      <input type='text' id='first-name' placeholder='First Name'><br>
      <input type='text' id='last-name' placeholder='Last Name'><br>
      <input type='email' id='email' placeholder='Email'><br>
    <button type='submit'>Submit</button>
   </form>
   <p id="server-response"></p>

   <script src="jquery.min.js"></script>
   <script src="scripts.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
```

CSS (styles.css):
```css
.center {
  text-align: center;
}
```

Javascript (scripts.js):
```javascript
function changeLanguage(language) {
   let goodbye = "Goodbye";
   if(language === "French") goodbye = "Au revoir";
   if(language === "Spanish") goodbye = "Adiós";
   $('#farewell-heading').text(goodbye);
}

$('#farewell-form').on('submit', function(e) {
    e.preventDefault();
    let firstName = $('#first-name').val();
    let lastName = $('#last-name').val();
    let email = $('#email').val();
    $.ajax({
      url: '/farewell',
      type: 'POST',
      data: { firstName, lastName, email },
      success: function(data) {
          $('#server-response').text(data.message);
      },
      error: function(err) {
          $('#server-response').text('Sorry, there was a problem generating your farewell message. Please try again later.');
      }
    });
});
```

The server-side setup (notably the `/farewell` endpoint mentioned in the AJAX request) is dependent on what backend framework or platform you're using, if any. The example above assumes that the server route expects JSON data and responds with JSON data, with any farewell message keyed to `message`.

You might want to add additional error handling, for example verifying that the provided user input is valid before attempting to send an AJAX request. Similarly, this code assumes that the server handles any issues before they reach the client-side Javascript, but you could add additional error handling to the AJAX request if needed.

Please note that the AJAX is done by using jQuery, if you want to use plain javascript, you need to use XMLHttpRequest or Fetch API.
