Develop a Java software application that takes in two arbitrary sequence of characters and yields an alphabetically ordered list of distinct characters present in the longer string, also indicating the frequency of each character. Be sure to handle both upper and lowercase characters. 
String distinctCharacterSequence1 = "Hello";
String distinctCharacterSequence2 = "Worrrld!";
<|end|>
<|asst|>
This problem can be solved in Java by creating a method that does the following:

1. Concatenate both input sequences and convert them into lowercase for case-insensitive handling of characters.
2. Convert the resulted sequence into a char array and iterate over each character.
3. Use a HashMap to keep track of each distinct character and its frequency.
4. Convert the keys of the HashMap into a List and sort it alphabetically.
5. Display each character in the sorted list with its corresponding frequency.

Here's an example of how this could be coded up:

```java
import java.util.*;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String sequence1 = "Hello";
        String sequence2 = "Worrrld!";
        analyzeCharacters(sequence1, sequence2);
    }

    public static void analyzeCharacters(String sequence1, String sequence2) {
        // Get the longer sequence among the two inputs
        String longerSequence = sequence1.length() > sequence2.length() ? sequence1 : sequence2;
        longerSequence = longerSequence.toLowerCase();

        Map<Character, Integer> characterCount = new HashMap<>();
        for(char c : longerSequence.toCharArray()){
            // Skip non-alphabetical characters
            if(!Character.isLetter(c)) 
                continue;

            if(characterCount.containsKey(c)) {
                characterCount.put(c, characterCount.get(c)+1);
            } else {
                characterCount.put(c, 1);
            }
        }

        List<Character> keys = new ArrayList<>(characterCount.keySet());
        Collections.sort(keys);

        for(char c : keys){
            System.out.println("Character: '" + c + "' Frequency: " + characterCount.get(c));
        }
    }
}
```

Remember, this program will only take into account alphabetical characters and ignore non-alphabetical ones, such as "!". If you want to include all types of characters, you should remove the line that checks for alphabetical characters.
<|end|>


