Modify and debug the provided merge sort algorithm that should accept an array of whole numbers, including negative numbers and zero, as an input and arrange them in an order of ascending numerical value. The provided code has some errors which prevent correct sorting of the array.

Given Array: [34, 19, 42, -9, 2018, 0, 105]

```python
def mergeSort(nlist):
  print("Splitting ",nlist)

  if len(nlist)>1:
    mid = len(nlist)//2
    lefthalf = nlist[:mid]
    righthalf = nlist[mid:]

    mergeSort(lefthalf)
    mergeSort(righthalf)

    i=j=k=0       
    while i < len(lefthalf) and j < len(righthalf):
      if lefthalf[i] < righthalf[j]:
        nlist[k]=lefthalf[i]
        i=i+1
      else:
        nlist[k]=righthalf[j]
        j=j+1
      k=k+1

    while i < len(lefthalf):
      nlist[k]=lefthalf[i]
      i=i+1
      k=k+1

  else:
      print("Merging ",nlist)

nlist = [34, 19, 42, -9, 2018, 0, 105]
mergeSort(nlist)
print(nlist)
```
You need to identify the error and modify the merge sort algorithm to correctly accomplish its intended function. Once the sorting algorithm works as expected, provide time and space complexity of the algorithm in Big O notation.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
The problem with the provided code is that it never merges the right half once the left half has been completely merged. This issue can be resolved by adding another while loop similar to the one responsible for merging the left half:
```python
    while j < len(righthalf):
        nlist[k]=righthalf[j]
        j=j+1
        k=k+1
```
Explanation: The missing loop is necessary to append all remaining elements from the right half in case it has more elements than the left half. Without this loop, those elements would never be added to the final sorted array.

Here is the corrected full code:
```python
def mergeSort(nlist):
  if len(nlist)>1:
    mid = len(nlist)//2
    lefthalf = nlist[:mid]
    righthalf = nlist[mid:]

    mergeSort(lefthalf)
    mergeSort(righthalf)

    i=j=k=0       
    while i < len(lefthalf) and j < len(righthalf):
      if lefthalf[i] < righthalf[j]:
        nlist[k]=lefthalf[i]
        i=i+1
      else:
        nlist[k]=righthalf[j]
        j=j+1
      k=k+1

    while i < len(lefthalf):
      nlist[k]=lefthalf[i]
      i=i+1
      k=k+1

    while j < len(righthalf):
      nlist[k]=righthalf[j]
      j=j+1
      k=k+1

nlist = [34, 19, 42, -9, 2018, 0, 105]
mergeSort(nlist)
print(nlist)
```
The output of this corrected code will be: [-9, 0, 19, 34, 42, 105, 2018].

Analyzing the Complexity:
Time Complexity:
The merge sort algorithm is a divide and conquer algorithm. Its time complexity in all three cases (best case, average case, worst case) is O(n log n). This comes from the fact that it divides the input array into halves with every recursive call (which takes log n time), and then merges the sorted arrays together (which takes linear time, i.e. O(n)).

Space Complexity:
The space complexity of merge sort is O(n). This is because each recursion needs auxiliary space to hold the two halves of the arrays. As it happens in each recursive call, the space needed (taken up by the call stack) grows linearly with the size of the input. Hence, space complexity is O(n).
<|end|>


