Devise an application utilizing Vue.js framework that calls for an ISO code of a nation as an input, then fetches, analyses, and exhibits pertinent data associated with that particular country in a systematized and aesthetic layout, incorporating additional complexities such as error handling for invalid codes and sorting data categories.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
To solve this problem, you would need knowledge of Vue.js, JavaScript, and a good understanding of fetch API or axios (to handle HTTP requests). Following is an example of a simplified solution for the request.

First off, we'll need to install Vue.js using your terminal or command prompt:

`npm install -g @vue/cli`

Then you should create a new project:

`vue create my-project`

Move into the new project folder and add axios:

``` bash
cd my-project
npm install axios
```

Let's create a new Vue component called 'CountryInfo.vue', in the components folder.

```vue
<template>
  <div>
    <h1>{{ countryData.name }}</h1>
    <p>Population: {{ countryData.population }}</p>
    <!-- You can display more information about the country here, depends on API data structure -->
    <div v-if="error">{{ error }}</div>
  </div>
</template>

<script>
import axios from 'axios';

export default {
  data() {
    return {
      countryData: {},
      error: null,
    };
  },
  methods: {
    fetchData(isoCode) {
      axios
        .get(`https://restcountries.eu/rest/v2/alpha/${isoCode}`)
        .then(response => {
          this.countryData = response.data;
        })
        .catch(error => {
          this.error = `There was an error! ${error}. Please input a valid ISO country code.`;
        });
    },
  },
  created() {
    // Assuming the component gets the ISO code as a prop, else you can use a hard-coded value or a value from input.
    this.fetchData(this.isoCode);
  },
  props: {
    isoCode: {
      type: String,
      required: true,
    },
  },
};
</script>
```

This code fetches the data of the country specified by the ISO code (passed as a prop) when the component is created and handles any errors. You would need to carefully handle and display the received API data according to your requirements inside your template.

You can call this component in the parent component (App.vue) and pass ISO code as a prop.

```vue
<template>
  <div id="app">
    <CountryInfo isoCode="us"/> <!-- US country info will be fetched -->
  </div>
</template>

<script>
import CountryInfo from './components/CountryInfo.vue';

export default {
  components: {
    CountryInfo,
  },
};
</script>
```

Remember, this is rather basic solution and in a real world scenario you would probably want to improve it, for example by allowing user to enter the ISO code, and having some loading state while the data is being fetched.
