The following problem can be solved using Python programming language and its libraries `xml.etree.ElementTree` for parsing the XML document and `re` for regular expressions. 

```python
import xml.etree.ElementTree as ET
import re

data = '''
<doc>
  <employee>
    <name>John Doe</name>
  </employee>
  <employee>
    <name>Jane Doe</name>
  </employee>
  <employee>
    <name>Bob Smith</name>
  </employee>
</doc>
'''

tree = ET.ElementTree(ET.fromstring(data))
root = tree.getroot()

names = []
for employee in root.findall('employee'):
    name = employee.find('name').text
    if 'Doe' not in name:
        names.append(name)

print(names)
```
This script will print:
```shell
['Bob Smith']
```

The script works by parsing the xml data and creating a tree structure with nodes. It then finds all employee elements and retrieves the text of the name element. It checks if the name contains the string "Doe", and if it doesn't, it gets added to the names list. At the end, it prints all the names that don't have "Doe" in them.
