Produce a Ruby module to perform some basic statistics on an array of numbers.
[1, 2, 4, 9, 5]
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Here is a simple Ruby module that calculates the mean (average), median, mode, and range of an array of numbers:

```ruby
module Stats
  def self.mean(array)
    array.sum / array.length.to_f
  end

  def self.median(array)
    sorted = array.sort
    len = sorted.length
    (sorted[(len - 1) / 2] + sorted[len / 2]) / 2.0
  end

  def self.mode(array)
    mode_array = array.group_by{ |e| e }.map{ |k, v| [k, v.length] }.to_h
    max_value = mode_array.values.max
    mode_array.select { |k, v| v == max_value }.keys
  end

  def self.range(array)
    array.max - array.min
  end
end

numbers = [1, 2, 4, 9, 5]

puts "Mean: #{Stats.mean(numbers)}"
puts "Median: #{Stats.median(numbers)}"
puts "Mode: #{Stats.mode(numbers)}"
puts "Range: #{Stats.range(numbers)}"
```

Note that the `mode` method will return all modes if the array is multimodal.

This code is very basic and does not include error checking or handling edge cases. For example, it will raise an error if the input array is empty. It's just meant to illustrate the basic idea of how you could structure a module like this.
<|end|>


