Design and engineer an HTML document that incorporates a trio of sections, employing 'div' elements for delineation. The sections should be fluidly responsive to differing screen sizes.

Additionally, include JavaScript code fragments in your document to manipulate the DOM. The script should dynamically alternate the order of these sections every two seconds. A piece of erroneous code has been provided below for reference. Analyze its faults and correct them in your implementation.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Page Title</title>
    <style>
        .class1 { ... }
        .class2 { ... }
        .class3 { ... }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="class1">...</div>
    <div class="class2">...</div>
    <div class="class3">...</div>

    <script>
        function rotateDivs() {
            var div1 = document.getElementsByClassName("class1");
            var div2 = document.getElementsByClassName("class2");
            var div3 = document.getElementsByClassName("class3");
            // code to rotate order of divs
        }
        setInterval(rotateDivs, 2000);
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```
Ensure that your JavaScript code correctly and uniquely manipulates the order of the 'div' elements and carefully consider where in the markup your JavaScript should be placed for optimal performance and load times.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Firstly, the provided erroneous JavaScript code is not actually doing anything to alter the order of divs, and `getElementsByClassName()` function returns a NodeList of all elements with the specified class name. Since the divs are unique and you're retrieving them by class, we need to make sure each div has a unique id to correctly obtain and manipulate each one.

Secondly, placing JavaScript right before the closing `</body>` tag ensures that the script is downloaded and processed after the full HTML document is loaded, hence it contributes to a better performance and load time.

Here is the corrected HTML and JavaScript:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Page Title</title>
    <style>
        .section {
            width: 100%;
            box-sizing: border-box;
            padding: 15px;
        }
        .section:nth-child(1) {
            background-color: lightcoral;
        }
        .section:nth-child(2) {
            background-color: lightgreen;
        }
        .section:nth-child(3) {
            background-color: lightblue;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div id="container">
        <div id="div1" class="section">Content for section 1</div>
        <div id="div2" class="section">Content for section 2</div>
        <div id="div3" class="section">Content for section 3</div>
    </div>
    
    <script>
        function rotateDivs() {
            var container = document.getElementById("container");
            var div1 = document.getElementById("div1");
            var div2 = document.getElementById("div2");
            var div3 = document.getElementById("div3");
            
            if(container.lastChild.id == "div3") {
                container.insertBefore(div3, div1);
            } else if(container.lastChild.id == "div2") {
                container.insertBefore(div2, div1);
            } else {
                container.insertBefore(div1, div2);
            }
        }
        setInterval(rotateDivs, 2000);
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```
In this corrected code, the `section` class defines a width of 100% and box sizing of border-box to create a responsive design. The individual div elements are then each given a unique id so that they can be correctly manipulated by the JavaScript code. The `rotateDivs` function then orders the divs depending on the id of the last child of the container: depending on whether div3, div2, or div1 is the last child, the corresponding div is moved to the beginning of the container. This has the effect of rotating the divs every 2 seconds as specified.
<|end|>


