Suggest a change to render the following CSS code more efficient with SCSS features and by implementing a CSS sprite technique to decrease the number of server requests.

.image-box {
    display: block;
    width: 100px;
    height: 100px;
    background-image: url("logo.png");
}
<|end|>
<|asst|>
With SCSS, you can take advantage of variables and mixins to implement the CSS sprite technique more efficiently. Here is an example assuming that the sprite contains two images (logo1 and logo2).

```scss
// Setup sprite positions and dimensions
$sprite-width: 200px;
$sprite-height: 100px;

$sprite-logo1-x: 0;
$sprite-logo1-y: 0;

$sprite-logo2-x: 100px;
$sprite-logo2-y: 0;

// Setup a mixin for the common styles
@mixin sprite($x, $y) {
    display: block;
    width: 100px;
    height: 100px;
    background: url('sprite.png') no-repeat;
    background-position: -($x) -($y);
}

// Use the mixin for the actual classes
.image-box-logo1 {
    @include sprite($sprite-logo1-x, $sprite-logo1-y);
}

.image-box-logo2 {
    @include sprite($sprite-logo2-x, $sprite-logo2-y);
}
```

This code sets up variables for the sprite dimensions and positions. There's also a mixin for the shared styles (display, width and height, and common properties for the background). Then you use these mixins in your actual classes (`image-box-logo1` and `image-box-logo2` in the example). This way, you only load a single image (`sprite.png`), reducing the number of server requests.
<|end|>


