Dears,
I have applications that run in a docker which are from [https://github.com/REANNZ/etcbd-public](https://github.com/REANNZ/etcbd-public).
the certificate of Icinga tool has expired and when I tried to install a new SSL from a Certificate Authority the system regenerates another self-signed SSL with the same name as server.crt and in the same directory which creates conflict and stopped the container. whenever I delete it and add the new SSL then reload apache2 it comes back again.
I would like to know where this certificate comes from and how to prevent it.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
The server.crt file is likely being generated by a part of the application code or a startup script within the docker container. It might also be being dynamically generated by some underlying service each time the application starts or the container is run.

You can find where and how this certificate is being generated by doing a search in the container or application source code for 'server.crt'. Once you find the script or code snippet (maybe in the Dockerfile or in a shell script that it runs), you could either disable the self signed certificate generation (comment out the relevant code lines), or replace the self-signed certificate generation command with one that uses your new SSL certificate.

Here are the steps you might take:

1. You will first need to get the source code if you don't already have it.
   ```bash
   git clone https://github.com/REANNZ/etcbd-public.git
   ```
   
2. Enter the source directory.
   ```bash
   cd etcbd-public
   ```
   
3. Start searching for where the certificate is generated. You can use the 'grep' command.
   ```bash
   grep -rnw '.' -e "server.crt"
   ```

This command will recursively search in all the files for the string "server.crt" and prints out information about where it finds it.

4. Once you located the script or the specific line of code that generates the certificate, you can edit the file and either comment out the lines of code that generate the certificate or replace the command with one that uses your certificate.

Remember, if you modify the Dockerfile or any script that it calls, you'll need to rebuild the docker image and push it to the docker registry if you're running the containers in a docker-compose environment or orchestration system like Kubernetes.

Also, make sure to backup any file before you modify it, so you can revert to the original if needed.
