Problem:

I am using DBSCAN in sklearn on a dataset with over 10,000 samples. I want to extract the 100 samples (not just index but full data) that are closest to a specific core sample "q" (e.g. q=3). Here "q" refers to the q^th core sample. Can anyone assist me?

A:

&lt;code&gt;
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
from sklearn.cluster import DBSCAN
q, X = load_data()
assert type(X) == np.ndarray
dbs = DBSCAN()
&lt;/code&gt;
closest_100_samples = ... # put solution in this variable
BEGIN SOLUTION
&lt;code&gt;
<|end|>
<|asst|>
dbs.fit(X)
core_samples = dbs.components_
distances = np.linalg.norm(X - core_samples[q], axis=1)
closest_100_indices = np.argpartition(distances, 100)[:100]
closest_100_samples = X[closest_100_indices]
&lt;/code&gt;
END SOLUTION
<|end|>


