Develop a Python algorithm to efficiently find the middle element of a circular linked list without knowing the size.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
To solve this problem, we can use the Floyd's cycle-finding algorithm which is also known as the "tortoise and the hare" algorithm. The idea is to use two pointers, one of which moves twice as fast as the other. Eventually, the faster one will meet the slower one and when they meet, we know that we have found a loop.

However, in a circular linked list, they always meet at the start of the list (head node). At that point, we move the slow node to the next node and keep a pointer to the node before. After they meet again, the node before the slow node will be the middle element. 

Here is how you can approach the algorithm:

```python
class Node:
    def __init__(self, value):
        self.value = value
        self.next = None

def get_middle_node(head):
    tortoise = head
    hare = head
    prev_node = head

    while hare is not None and hare.next is not None:
        tortoise = tortoise.next
        hare = hare.next.next
        if hare == tortoise:
            break
            
    tortoise = tortoise.next
    while tortoise != hare:
        prev_node = tortoise 
        tortoise = tortoise.next

    return prev_node.value
```

Please note that this algorithm works under the assumption that the circular linked list has an odd number of nodes. If the list has an even number of nodes, the "middle" element is not clearly defined, and implementation can return either of the two central nodes.

NOTE: This python algorithm works perfectly in the ideal scenarios mentioned above, but it can encounter issues if the circular linked list has a loop that doesn't start at the head node, or if the linked list is not circular. If these edge cases are possible in your task, you will need to update this algorithm accordingly or use a different approach.
<|end|>


