Develop a multi-threaded java program that prints out "Hello World!" ensuring thread safety. The message should be broken into two parts - "Hello" and "World!" - printed by two separate threads. The thread printing "Hello" should always print before the thread that prints "World!".
<|end|>
<|asst|>
This is a thread synchronization problem which we can solve by using join() method that allows one thread to wait until another thread completes its execution. 

Here, is a simple code demonstrating this:

```java
public class HelloWorldMultiThreaded {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        // Create Thread 1
        Thread helloThread = new Thread(() -> System.out.print("Hello "));
        // Start Thread 1
        helloThread.start();

        try {
            // Join Thread 1, Thread 2 will wait until Thread 1 finishes
            helloThread.join();
        } catch (InterruptedException e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }

        // Create Thread 2
        Thread worldThread = new Thread(() -> System.out.println("World!"));
        // Start Thread 2
        worldThread.start();
    }

}
```

In this Java program, we create two threads. The first thread (helloThread) writes "Hello " to the console, and the second thread (worldThread) writes "World!". But before we start the second thread, we make sure the first thread has finished its execution using the join() method. This ensures that "Hello " is always printed before "World!".
<|end|>


