<|asst|>
The code you've given contains an error which regards string interpolation in JavaScript. In JavaScript, we don't use the interpolation like `$name`, but we should write it like `${name}` to replace the variable inside the string. 

Here is the fixed code:

```javascript
function greet(name) {
  let greeting = `Hello, ${name}!`;
  console.log(greeting);
  return greeting.length;
};

var length = greet('John');
console.log(length);
```

When you run `greet('John')`, it prints "Hello, John!" and returns the length of this string, which is then logged to the console.

The length of the resulting string "Hello, John!" is 12. In JavaScript, the length of a string includes all characters, including spaces and punctuation.
<|end|>


