<|user|>
I ended up writing a quick little script for this in Python, but I was wondering if there was a utility you could feed text into which would prepend each line with some text -- in my specific case, a timestamp.  Ideally, the use would be something like:


cat somefile.txt | prepend-timestamp



(Before you answer sed, I tried this:


cat somefile.txt | sed "s/^/`date`/"



But that only evaluates the date command once when sed is executed, so the same timestamp is incorrectly prepended to each line.)
<|end|>
<|asst|>
You can use awk or Perl for this.

With awk:


```bash
cat somefile.txt | awk '{ print strftime(), $0; fflush(); }'
```

With Perl:


```bash
cat somefile.txt | perl -MPOSIX -pne 'print strftime("%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S", localtime()), " ";'
```

With these commands, the timestamps will be different for each line in the output. That's because awk's strftime and Perl's strftime functions are getting called on each line of input, not just once when the pipeline is set up.

Note that the fflush() in the awk version is necessary to force awk to flush its output buffer after each line. If you don't include this and you're appending the output of the command to a file, you may find that lines don't get written out immediately. Perl does this automatically.
<|end|>


