I'm using the [ASP.NET Login Controls](http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/ms178329.aspx) and [Forms Authentication](http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/aa480476.aspx) for membership/credentials for an ASP.NET web application.  I've got pages such as  that are accessable to only Anonymous users.  When I click my login link from such a page, the login page has a  parameter in the address bar:

> [http://www.example.com/Login.aspx?ReturnUrl=PasswordRecovery.aspx](http://www.example.com/Login.aspx?ReturnUrl=PasswordRecovery.aspx)

And then after a successful login, users are returned to the  page specified in the  parameter to which they no longer have access.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
To avoid this unwanted redirection, you can handle the LoggedIn event of the Login control and override the default redirect behavior:

```C#
protected void Login1_LoggedIn(object sender, EventArgs e)
{
    if (!string.IsNullOrEmpty(Request.QueryString["ReturnUrl"]))
    {
        // User was redirected to the login page because they tried to access
        // a page requiring authentication. Let's override the default redirection
        // and send them to the default page for their role instead.
        string defaultUrl = GetDefaultUrlForLoggedInUser();
        Response.Redirect(defaultUrl);
    }
}
```

Here, `GetDefaultUrlForLoggedInUser` might be a method that checks the user's role and returns a URL corresponding to the default page for that role.

Note that the LoggedIn event fires after the user has been authenticated but before they are redirected to the `ReturnUrl`.

Also, be aware that using this approach will always redirect the user to the default page for their role after they log in. If you want users to be redirected to the `ReturnUrl` when they are logging in in response to being redirected from a page requiring authentication (i.e., they clicked on a link to that page while not logged in), you may want to use a more sophisticated check for when to redirect to the default page vs. when to use the `ReturnUrl`.
<|end|>


