I am looking for volatility surface parametrisation model used for treasury futures bond options. I know that most popular for options on equities its SVI, on FX its Vanna-Volga, on rates its SABR. What about bond options?
<|end|>
<|asst|>
There is not a singular accepted model for Treasury futures bond options, but some common models used include Black's Model or Black76 (a modified version of the Black-Scholes Model specifically for options on futures), the CIR Model (Cox-Ingersoll-Ross), and the Heston Model.

All these models can be used for pricing options and capturing volatility dynamics in the bond market. Note however that each model has its own assumptions and may suit certain market conditions better than others. Therefore, the choice of model often depends on the specifics of the bond option being priced (e.g. the term structure of the option, interest rate dynamics, etc.). 

Remember that no model can perfectly capture reality. Hence, the best model is often determined by the intended application, and may also be subject to validation and calibration based on market data to ensure its performance is as accurate as possible.
<|end|>


