I'm writing up a neural network using sigmoid as the activation function. According to one lecture, sigmoid simply squashes numbers onto the (0,1) interval. To model non-linear decision boundaries, you need high dimensional data. Another lecture, this one on sigmoid in neural nets context (MIT S.191), suggested sigmoid's non-linear behaviour is the reason why a neural net can model a non-linear decision boundary. So, I'm a bit confused. Does sigmoid facilitate modeling non-linear decision boundaries or does this come from high-dimensional data because you can use the sigmoid to produce a linear decision boundary w/o incident?
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Both the sigmoid function and high dimensional data contribute to the ability of a neural network to model non-linear decision boundaries. 

The sigmoid function by itself is nonlinear. When used as an activation function in a neural network model, it enables the model to capture the non-linear relationships between inputs and outputs, as the output of the sigmoid function is a non-linear transformation of its input.

However, without high-dimensional data, a model with a sigmoid function can still only generate relatively simple non-linear decision boundaries. Each neuron in a neural network using a sigmoid activation essentially performs a linear transformation (via its weighted inputs) followed by a non-linear transformation (the sigmoid function). Because of this, the complexity of the decision boundaries the model can generate is ultimately determined by the complexity of the input data - and high dimensional data can capture more complex patterns and nonlinearities than low dimensional data.

In deep learning, high-dimensional data (e.g., images, text encoded as word embeddings, etc.) and non-linear activations (e.g., sigmoid, tanh, ReLU etc.) are used together to create highly flexible models that can capture complex, non-linear decision boundaries.

So, the key point is that both the sigmoid function and high-dimensional data contribute to generating non-linear decision boundaries. The sigmoid function allows the model to generate non-linear decision boundaries even when the decision boundary in the input space is linear. The increased dimensionality of the data allows the generation of more complex non-linear decision boundaries.
<|end|>


