Create a React.js application that allows users to select a timezone and displays the current date and time in that timezone.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Here's a basic example of how this could be done using React.js and the `moment-timezone` package for handing timezone related functionality.

Firstly, you need to install `moment-timezone` via npm:

```
npm install moment-timezone --save
```

Now, you can start building your application:

```jsx
import React, { Component } from 'react';
import moment from 'moment-timezone';

class App extends Component {
  constructor(props) {
    super(props);
    this.state = { 
      selectedZone: "Pacific/Auckland",
      date: moment().tz("Pacific/Auckland").format('MMMM Do YYYY, h:mm:ss a')
    };
  }

  // List of all timezone which can be selected. For simplicity only few are added
  timezoneList = [
    "Pacific/Auckland",
    "Asia/Kolkata",
    "America/Los_Angeles",
    "Europe/Paris"
  ];

  // change selectedZone state and current date and time when a new timezone is selected
  handleChange = event => {
    this.setState({
      selectedZone: event.target.value,
      date: moment().tz(event.target.value).format('MMMM Do YYYY, h:mm:ss a')
    });
  };

  // update the date and time every second
  tick = () => {
    this.setState({
      date: moment().tz(this.state.selectedZone).format('MMMM Do YYYY, h:mm:ss a') 
    });
  };

  // whenever the App component mounts, call tick method every second
  componentDidMount(){
    this.interval = setInterval(this.tick, 1000);
  }

  // whenever the App component unmounts, clear the interval
  componentWillUnmount() {
    clearInterval(this.interval);
  }

  render() {
    return (
      <div>
        <select value={this.state.selectedZone} onChange={this.handleChange}>
          {this.timezoneList.map(zone => (
            <option key={zone} value={zone}>{zone}</option>
          ))}
        </select>

        <h2>{this.state.date}</h2>
      </div>
    );
  }
}

export default App;
```

In this example, every time you select a new timezone from the dropdown list, the state's `selectedZone` property will be changed and then current date and time will be displayed according to the selected timezone. The date and time update every second. This example only uses few time zones for sake of simplicity, but you could fill the `timezoneList` array with all of the timezones if you want. 

Please be aware that this is just a simple example and that it doesn't take into consideration various edge cases you might encounter in a production application.
<|end|>


