To achieve the pulse or glow effect, you can use the CSS Animations. First, embed your SVG in an HTML document. Second, apply a CSS style using keyframes for pulsing or glow effect.

Here is the step by step process:

1. Embed SVG in HTML:

```html
<div class="svg-container">
..svg code here..
</div>
```

2. Apply CSS:

For pulsing effect:

```css
@keyframes pulse {
0% {
  transform: scale(1);
}
50% {
  transform: scale(1.1);
}
100% {
  transform: scale(1);
}
}

.svg-container {
  animation: pulse 2s infinite; /* pulse animation */
}
```

For glow effect:

```css
@keyframes glow {
0% {
  filter: drop-shadow(0 0 5px #ff0000);
}
50% {
  filter: drop-shadow(0 0 20px #ff0000, 0 0 30px #ff8000);
}
100% {
  filter: drop-shadow(0 0 5px #ff0000);
}
}

.svg-container {
  animation: glow 2s infinite; /* glow animation */
}
```

Please note that the color and the size of the glow/pulse effect are adjustable, so you can modify it according to your needs. Keep in mind that the effect needs to be applied to the SVG container to get the desired results. 

Note: The glow animation effect may not work in some cases with SVG images or on some browsers because the `filter` property is still partially supported in CSS. Use the CSS `filter` property cautiously if you're looking for broad compatibility.

Remember to include these styles in your HTML file between style tags or link an external CSS file.
<|end|>


