Craft a recursive method in C# language specifically tailored to display all the prime numerals in the numerical range starting at 1 and ending at 100.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Here is a sample code that uses recursion in C# to find all the prime numbers in the range of 1 to 100:

```csharp
using System;

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        Console.WriteLine("Prime numbers between 1 and 100 are : ");
        DisplayPrimeNumbers(2, 100);
    }

    static void DisplayPrimeNumbers(int currentNumber, int maxLimit)
    {
        if (currentNumber <= maxLimit)
        {
            if (CheckPrime(currentNumber, currentNumber / 2))
            {
                Console.WriteLine("{0} ", currentNumber);
            }
            DisplayPrimeNumbers(currentNumber + 1, maxLimit);
        }
    }

    static bool CheckPrime(int number, int i)
    {
        if (i == 1)
        {
            return true;
        }
        else
        {
            if (number % i == 0)
            {
                return false;
            }
            else
            {
                return CheckPrime(number, i - 1);
            }
        }
    }
}
```

In this example: 

- Main() calls the method DisplayPrimeNumbers(2, 100) because we are checking prime numbers starting from 2 up to 100.
- The DisplayPrimeNumbers() checks if the current number is prime or not by calling CheckPrime() method. If it's prime, it prints the number.
- CheckPrime() checks if a number is prime by checking divisibility from currentNumber/2 down to 2 (Since no number is divisible by a number greater than its half, we start from there). 
- If it's divisible by any of these, it returns false, else it keeps checking with smaller numbers. If we reach 1 without finding any number that it's divisible by, we return true meaning the number is prime.
- The DisplayPrimeNumbers() then calls itself with the next number, repeating the same process till maxLimit. This is the recursive part of the function.
<|end|>


