Given a list of strings, write a Python program to identify all unique quintuplet of index values (i, j, k, l, m) within the list, ensuring that the fusion of the five words, which is words[i], words[j], words[k], words[l] and words[m] together forms an anagram of a given word. The catch here is that all words can repeat any number of times and order of index quintuplets matters i.e., (i,j,k,l,m) is different from (m,l,k,j,i).

words = ["cat", "act", "tac", "atc", "cta", "tca"]
given_word = "catcatcatcatcat"
<|end|>
<|asst|>
You can use permutations from itertools module in Python to obtain all the unique quintuplets of index values. To check if the concatenation of five words forms an anagram of the given word, each word is first sorted alphabetically and checked for equality.

```python
import itertools

def get_quintuplets(words, given_word):
    index_quintuplets = []
    sorted_given_word = sorted(given_word)
    
    # Get all quintuplets of indices
    all_quintuplets = list(itertools.permutations(range(len(words)), 5))
    
    for quintuplet in all_quintuplets:
        # Concatenate words at indices in quintuplet and sort them
        sorted_word = sorted(words[quintuplet[0]] + words[quintuplet[1]] + words[quintuplet[2]] +
                             words[quintuplet[3]] + words[quintuplet[4]])
        
        # If sorted word is same as sorted given word, append quintuplet to list
        if sorted_word == sorted_given_word:
            index_quintuplets.append(quintuplet)
            
    return index_quintuplets

words = ["cat", "act", "tac", "atc", "cta", "tca"]
given_word = "catcatcatcatcat"
print(get_quintuplets(words, given_word))
```

This Python program takes a list of words and a given word as input, finds all quintuplets of indices within the list and checks if the concatenation of the words at these indices forms an anagram of the given word. The result is a list of all quintuplets for which this condition is fulfilled.
