I am confronted with a task named "Decoding the Lock". The specifics of this task are as follows: A receptacle is safeguarded by a password. This password is a sequence of `n` numerals, where each numeral can be any of the first `k` numerals `0, 1, ..., k-1`.

When a password is entered, the latest `n` numerals entered will be automatically juxtaposed with the actual password.

For example, if the real password is `&amp;#34;345&amp;#34;`, and you enter `&amp;#34;012345&amp;#34;`, the receptacle will unlock because the real password matches the suffix of the password you inputted.

Provide any password of the minimal possible length that is assured to unlock the receptacle at some point during its input.

Example 1:
Input: n = 1, k = 2
Output: &amp;#34;01&amp;#34;
Note: &amp;#34;10&amp;#34; is also a valid response.

Example 2:
Input: n = 2, k = 2
Output: &amp;#34;00110&amp;#34;
Note: &amp;#34;01100&amp;#34;, &amp;#34;10011&amp;#34;, &amp;#34;11001&amp;#34; are also valid responses.

Please be aware:
The value of `n` will be within the range `[1, 4]`.

The value of `k` will be within the range `[1, 10]`.

The value of `k^n` will not surpass `4096`.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
This task can be solved by the De Bruijn sequence theory, so let's create a de Bruijn sequence of order `n` on a `k`-ary alphabet. 

Here is a Python solution:

```python
def password_crack(n, k):
    password = [0] * k * n
    sequence = []

    def generate(t, p):
        if t > n:
            if n % p == 0:
                for j in range(1, p + 1):
                    sequence.append(password[j])
        else:
            password[t] = password[t - p]
            generate(t + 1, p)
            for j in range(password[t - p] + 1, k):
                password[t] = j
                generate(t + 1, t)

    generate(1, 1)
    return "".join(str(i) for i in sequence)

```

This algorithm generates a de Bruijn sequence by constructing a directed graph consisting of k^n vertices, each representing a sequence of n symbols, and k^n directed edges which represent appending one symbol to a sequence of n symbols. Starting from an arbitrary vertex v consisting of n symbols, it continuously moves to the vertex consisting of the last n-1 symbols in v plus one new symbol, until it has visited all vertices. The sequence of visited vertices is a de Bruijn sequence.

For instance, `password_crack(2,2)` will return the string `"01100"`.
<|end|>


