Given two text strings a and b, find out the smallest length of the unique substring sequence not shared by these two.
a = "hijkl"
b = "acdpq"
<|end|>
<|asst|>
One approach for solving this problem is to use the concept of "set", a built-in data type in Python that stores multiple items in a single variable. Sets are unordered collections of unique elements which means we can put multiple elements into a set, yet when we retrieve them, we only get unique ones.

The below Python code uses set to solve the problem:

```python
a = "hijkl"
b = "acdpq"
set_a = set(a)
set_b = set(b)

# Get the unique values in each string by subtracting the intersection
unique_a = set_a - set_b
unique_b = set_b - set_a

# Concatenate the two sets of unique characters and find its length
len_unique = len(unique_a | unique_b)
print(len_unique)
```
This program first creates sets from both strings, then calculates the difference between these sets to get the unique characters in each string. After that, it finds the union of these unique sets (i.e., concatenates and removes duplicates) and returns its length. This length is the answer to our problem. 

Please note that this solution will work only if we care about unique characters. If we want to consider every single character from both strings (including duplicates), the solution will be different.
<|end|>


