Craft a command in MySQL to modify email information of client base contained in the designated data set. In addition to this, write a trigger in the database that logs the changes made to the email field in another table. The trigger should capture old value, new value and the timestamp of the modification.

Data set specification: customers
Parameter for Electronic Mail: email
Log table: email_log with fields id (auto increment), old_email, new_email, modified_timestamp.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
In MySQL, you can accomplish this by first performing an UPDATE command to modify the email information of a client then by creating a trigger to log changes to the email field.

Step 1: Modifying Email Information of a Client

```sql
UPDATE customers SET email = 'newemail@example.com' WHERE email = 'oldemail@example.com';
```
Replace 'newemail@example.com' with the updated email. 

Step 2: Creating the Trigger in the Database to Log Changes 

```sql
DELIMITER //
CREATE TRIGGER email_update_trigger
AFTER UPDATE ON customers
FOR EACH ROW 
BEGIN 
IF NEW.email != OLD.email THEN
   INSERT INTO email_log(old_email, new_email, modified_timestamp) 
   VALUES(OLD.email, NEW.email, NOW());
END IF;
END; //
DELIMITER ;
```
In this code, `NEW.email` and `OLD.email` refer to the new and old email values, respectively. This trigger will fire every time an UPDATE operation is performed on customers table only if the email has been changed. It will then insert a new record into the email_log table capturing the old email, new email, and modification timestamp.

Make sure you have necessary privileges to create and execute triggers in the database and that the MySQL version is above 5.0.2.
<|end|>


