Outline the sequence of actions required for the instantiation and application of the Singleton design pattern in Java, ensuring it creates and manages a singular instance of a class at all points during an application's runtime. Further, elucidate on how such mechanism facilitates the pattern's distinctive feature of limiting instantiation.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Here is the sequence of actions required in Java:

1. **Declaring a private static instance of the same class inside the class**: Singleton pattern involves creating and managing one instance of a specific class throughout the entire lifecycle of an application. This instance should be globally accessible, hence the static modifier.

```java
public class Singleton {
    private static Singleton instance;
}
```

2. **Making the constructor private to restrict instantiation**: The Singleton pattern assumes that we create an object only when it’s necessary. This is accomplished by making the constructor private, as it prevents external classes from creating new instances of the Singleton class.

```java
private Singleton() {}
```

3. **Providing a public static method that returns the singleton object**: This is the global access point for the singleton object. First time when this method is called, it creates a new singleton object and assigns the reference to the private instance variable. For the subsequent calls, it simply returns the already created singleton's reference.

```java
public static Singleton getInstance() {
    if (instance == null) {
        instance = new Singleton();
    }
    return instance;
}
```

So, the complete Singleton class looks like this:

```java
public class Singleton {
    private static Singleton instance;
    
    private Singleton() {}

    public static Singleton getInstance() {
        if (instance == null) {
            instance = new Singleton();
        }
        return instance;
    }
}
```

Singleton pattern ensures that every time we need an instance, it provides the same object created the first time around. Thus, limiting object creation to exactly one, which is a major advantage when the creation process is time-consuming, demands many resources, or if you want to use a single resource shared by various instances.

But note this approach works fine in single-threaded environments but when it comes to multithreaded scenarios, it can cause issues if multiple threads go inside the 'if' loop at the same time. In such a case, you might end up having multiple instances of your Singleton class. So to handle this scenario, you can use thread-safe Singleton pattern using synchronization.

The synchronized singleton would look like:

```java
public class Singleton {
    private static Singleton instance;
    private Singleton() {}

    public static synchronized Singleton getInstance() {
        if (instance == null) {
            instance = new Singleton();
        }
        return instance;
    }
}
```

The synchronized keyword ensures only one thread can access the method at a time, effectively preventing the creation of multiple instances. But, it can reduce performance due to the cost associated with the synchronization method. As an alternative, you might consider using the "double-checked locking" principle or "Initialization-on-demand holder idiom". This topic goes beyond your question, but you may research further if interested.
<|end|>


