Could you delineate the procedures required to facilitate a seamless integration of Google Cloud Firestore with my mobile software, particularly with the aim of guaranteeing data retention during periods of network unavailability?
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Absolutely! Firestore is Google Cloud's NoSQL database designed to provide seamless synchronization and extensive scalability, aiding on developing high-performance applications. Intensive steps are involved to integrate Firestore into your mobile software, which as you've pointed out, also allows offline data persistence.

Assuming you use either Android or iOS platform, generally you will follow these steps:

###Setup the development environment:
1. To work with cloud Firestore, you'll need to have Android Studio or XCode installed on your device. You can download Android Studio from [here](https://developer.android.com/studio) and XCode from the Apple store.

2. Create a new project within Android Studio or Xcode.
 
###Create Project on Firebase:
1. Visit [Firebase Console](https://console.firebase.google.com/) and sign in with your Google Account.
 
2. Click on "Add Project", provide a name for the Firebase project and follow the instructions.

###Connect the app to Firebase:
For Android:

1. In Firebase Console, click on the Android logo to create a new Android app. 

2. Fill the package name of the app, register the app and download the `google-services.json` file and move this file into your Android app module root directory.

3. Add Firebase SDK to your app by adding dependencies to your `build.gradle` files, both project-level and app-level files.

For iOS:

1. In the Firebase Console, click the iOS logo to create a new iOS app.

2. Fill out your iOS bundle ID, register the app and download the `GoogleService-Info.plist`.

3. Add this `GoogleService-Info.plist` into your iOS app in XCode, also add Firebase SDK by adding pod 'Firebase/Firestore' into the pod file.

###Enable Offline Data Persistence:
For Android:

1. In your main activity, you simply need to add this line of code to enable offline data persistence: `FirebaseFirestore.getInstance().setPersistenceEnabled(true);`.

For iOS:

1. In your AppDelegate, you can use this code to enable offline persistence: `Firestore.firestore().settings.isPersistenceEnabled = true`.

Now Firestore is integrated into your app and essentially setup to persist data offline.

Remember that Firestore synchronizes any changes when the device comes back online after a network outage. However, note that there are some performance considerations as outlined in Firestore's [official document](https://firebase.google.com/docs/firestore/manage-data/enable-offline) and depending your specific requirements, you may need to adjust settings accordingly.
<|end|>


