Considering the deployment of a machine learning model developed in R on a production environment using Amazon Web Services (AWS) Lambda, could you elaborate on the most beneficial strategies, considering not only scalability, data privacy measures, and cost-effectiveness, but also aspects such as error tolerance, data integrity, and the potential for future expansion and integration with other cloud-based platforms?
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Deploying a machine learning model developed in R on a production environment using AWS Lambda requires careful strategy. Here are some beneficial plans to consider:

1. Containerization: Even though AWS supports Python, Node.js, Ruby, Java, Go, .NET and PowerShell natively, there is no direct support for R. You may use custom runtime API provided by AWS to run your R script in Lambda. Another alternative way is to use Docker, it makes easy to package, distribute, and manage applications in any environment, and AWS Lambda has supported container images.

2. Scalability: AWS Lambda automatically scales the applications in response to the incoming request traffic. The performance of your ML model can be adjusted by configuring the memory settings. AWS automatically allocates CPU power, network bandwidth, and disk I/O proportionally.

3. Error-Tolerance: AWS Lambda comes with built-in fault tolerance. AWS Lambda maintains infrastructure redundancy to ensure that your code is executed. Lambda also integrates with AWS X-Ray to let developers analyze and debug serverless applications.

4. Cost-Effectiveness: AWS Lambda is a cost-effective service where you pay for the compute time you consume. There is no charge when your code is not running. You can even get started with an AWS free-tier offering.

5. Data Privacy & Integrity: Implement IAM policies to control access to your Lambda functions. AWS Lambda stores code within Amazon S3 and automatically encrypts it at rest in the AWS Lambda service. 

6. Serverless Architecture: AWS Lambda is a good fit for serverless architectures which let you build and run applications without thinking about servers.

7. Future Expansion & Integration: AWS Lambda integrates with other AWS services to process files and streaming data. It can also be used in data transformation for analytics solutions or for real-time file processing and so on – hence gives scope for future expansion.

8. Monitoring & Logging: Use Amazon CloudWatch to track metrics. For logging, AWS Lambda automatically integrates with CloudWatch Logs, providing centralized logs.

9. Incremental Updates: Having a CI/CD pipeline in place with AWS CodePipeline will ensure your ML model in R can be updated in a controlled manner.

10. Stateless Design: Keep your AWS Lambdas stateless. It helps with scaling, debugging, and generally reduces complexity.

11. Use of APIs: AWS API Gateway can serve as a 'door' to your Machine Learning model. It will let you control who, how, and when somebody can have access to your model.
<|end|>


