Could you elaborate on the distinctions between 'div' and 'span' elements in HTML, focusing on their default characteristics, impact on webpage layout, as well as usage scenarios?
<|end|>
<|asst|>
This problem doesn't require a programming solution as it is a theoretical question. 

The 'div' and 'span' are both HTML tags. They are generic container elements that do not represent anything. They can be used to style blocks of content, implement layout, and to group other elements.

1. 'div' element: 
- It is a block level element. It takes up the full width available and does not allow anything to sit next to it on the webpage. It starts on a new line and takes up the whole width.
- 'div' is used to layout block sections of a webpage, such as headers, footers, and website navigation bars.  
- 'div' could contain other block-level or inline elements. 

2. 'span' element: 
- 'span' is an inline level element. It only takes up the amount of width necessary and allows other elements to sit next to it on the same line. It does not start on a new line.
- 'span' is used within a block of text where you would want to give a section of text a different color, different font, or in general, a different appearance, but don't want it to break the flow of that text.
- 'span' only contains inline elements. Also, it has no effect on content or layout until styled using CSS.

In conclusion, the main differences between 'div' and 'span' tags are in their default behavior in webpage layout and where you would typically use them. For designing large blocks of content or large structural areas, 'div' is the best choice whereas for smaller inline changes to text or content within a block, 'span' is more suitable. Most primarily, these elements are used to improve the HTML structure and add styles through CSS.
<|end|>


