Analyze the following data in R using a custom algorithm that implements the quicksort technique to sort the data first without using any standard library functions for sorting. Then, identify the mean, median, and mode of the data. Validate your algorithm's output by comparing it with the outputs of the built-in functions for mean, median, and mode in R.

[Data]

[2, 3, 5, 6, 4, 1, 3, 6, 4]
<|end|>
<|asst|>
This requires writing R code that performs the desired operations. Below is the complete R code for this task:

```r
# Define function for quicksort
quicksort <- function(vec) {
  if (length(vec) <= 1) return(vec)
  pivot <- sample(vec, 1)
  left <- vec[vec < pivot]
  middle <- vec[vec == pivot]
  right <- vec[vec > pivot]
  c(quicksort(left), middle, quicksort(right))
}

# Define a function to calculate the mode
findMode <- function(v) {
  uniqv <- unique(v)
  uniqv[which.max(tabulate(match(v, uniqv)))]
}

# Initialize the numeric vector
data <- c(2, 3, 5, 6, 4, 1, 3, 6, 4)

# Quicksort
sorted <- quicksort(data)

# Mean
mean_output <- sum(sorted)/length(sorted)

# Median
n <- length(sorted)
median_output <- if (n %% 2 == 0) mean(sorted[n/2], sorted[n/2 + 1]) else sorted[n/2 + 1]

# Mode
mode_output <- findMode(sorted)

# Validate results
cat("Validate Results:\n")
cat("Mean:   ", mean(data) == mean_output, "\n") 
cat("Median: ", median(data) == median_output, "\n") 
cat("Mode:   ", findMode(data) == mode_output, "\n")
```

In this code, a function for quicksort is initially defined. For the purpose of mode, another function is defined. The data is sorted using quicksort function. Next, mean is calculated by summing all elements of the sorted data and dividing by the total number of elements. For median, the middle number is taken if the data length is odd, else the average of the two middle numbers is calculated. Further, the mode is calculated by calling the findMode function, and finally, the calculated mean, median, and mode are compared to those obtained by in-built R functions.
<|end|>


