In the context of object-oriented programming utilizing Java language, could you meticulously elucidate the step-by-step algorithmic process for removing a distinct node from a detailed unidirectional linked list data configuration?
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Sure. Removing a node from a linked-list can be accomplished in several steps. Here's the algorithmic process for removing a distinct node from a unidirectional linked list in Java:

1. Define our Node class if it isn't already:

```java
class Node
{
    int data;
    Node next;

    Node(int d)
    {
        data = d;
        next = null;
    }
}
```

2. Create the LinkedList class:

```java
public class LinkedList 
{
    Node head;  // head of the list
}
```

3. Then, add the method to delete a Node from the LinkedList (target is the key of the node to be deleted):

```java
void deleteNode(int target)
{
    // Store head node
    Node temp = head, prev = null;

    // If head node itself holds the key to be deleted
    if (temp != null && temp.data == key)
    {
        head = temp.next; // Change head
        return;
    }

    // Search for the key to be deleted, keep a track of the previous node
    // because we need to change temp.next
    while (temp != null && temp.data != target)
    {
        prev = temp;
        temp = temp.next;
    }    

    // If key was not found in the linked list
    if (temp == null) return;

    // Unlink the node from the linked list
    prev.next = temp.next;

    // Now, Java's garbage collector will eventually removes temp
}
```

The above function traverses the linked list until it finds the key. Once the key is found, it disconnects the node from the linked list by changing the "next" address of the previous node.

4. Let's test our function:

```java
public static void main(String[] args)
{
    LinkedList linkedlist = new LinkedList();
    
    linkedlist.head = new Node(1);
    Node second = new Node(2);
    Node third = new Node(3);
    
    linkedlist.head.next = second;
    second.next = third;  
    
    System.out.println("Linked list before deletion: ");
    printList(linkedlist);  // 1 -> 2 -> 3
    
    linkedlist.deleteNode(2);  // Call the deleteNode method
    
    System.out.println("Linked list after deletion of node 2: ");
    printList(linkedlist);  // 1 -> 3
}
```

We also need to define the printList() function:

```java
static void printList(LinkedList list)
{
    Node n = list.head;
    while (n != null)
    {
        System.out.print(n.data+" ");
        n = n.next;
    }
}
```

The above way of removing a node from a linked list completes the task in O(n) time complexity where n is the length of the linked list. In case of unidirectional linked list the key deletion might not be feasible in less than O(n) as one has to traverse the list to find the key.
<|end|>


