I start with an entity A with primary key A1, it has child collections B and C, but they are empty, because I haven't prefetched them.  I now get a new occurrence of A (A prime) with primary key A1 with the child collections B and C filled.

What is a good way to get the A and A prime to be the same object and to get A collections of B and C filled?
<|end|>
<|asst|>
This seems like a situation to implement a "lazy loading strategy" where collections B and C are loaded on demand. However, if you directly want A and A' to be the same object including the collections, you could directly assign B and C of A' to A. 

Here is a potential way to implement this:

1. If you are using ORM (Object Relational Mapping) like Hibernate or Entity Framework, you can enable lazy loading. This means that the child collections will not be accessed from the database until they are actually used, there by effectively updating A as and when the collections are accessed.

2. You can manually assign B' and C' to B and C respectively.
   ```
   A.B = Aprime.B;
   A.C = Aprime.C;
   ```
In this approach, you're essentially "overwriting" the original B and C collections with B' and C' collections.

3. Update the reference of object A to the newly created object A' if all other properties of A and A' are same. This approach directly makes A and A' identical including the collections.
    ```
    A = Aprime;
    ```
Note that all these approaches have trade-offs so it depends on what your specific requirements and usage patterns are when deciding which one to use. The first approach is a bit more "automatic" while the latter two require more explicit handling.
 
Also consider rethinking your fetching strategy if these situations occur often. For example, you can consider eager fetching where all references will be fetched.
<|end|>


