Im new to app development and was wondering if it would be possible to include another jdk. For example java 17 and run a jar that needs to be run in this exact version? I think termux has an api that you may use for these purposes but is there another possibility? These jars are only console based and without any gui.
I first tried to use the jar as a android library inside the app, which did not work since it was compiled in java version 17. I tried decompiling the jar and recompiling it with the version I was using. The problem is that all the libraries used are on other versions than I need them to be and so I could not recompile it. I also thought about writing the application in c# but I am not used to it at all, which would throw many new problems that I would be willing to take if it would be a possibility to work out my project.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Unfortunately, at the time of writing this, Android still does not support JDK 17. As of Android N, the runtime has been switched to ART (Android Runtime) which only supports up to Java 8 (although some features of Java 9 and above are beginning to appear in more recent Android versions).

Including another JDK within your app isn't really feasible. Android apps have to be cross-compiled into a specific bytecode that's understood by the Android Runtime, so you can't just bundle another JDK and expect ART to understand it.

The standard solutions are:

1) Downgrade your JAR's Java version: You already attempted to decompile the JAR and recompile it in Java 8 without success. Another possibility is to ask the developer of the JAR to compile it with Java 8, or find an older version of the same library that was compiled in an older Java version.

2) Use JNI (Java Native Interface) and perform the work in native (C/C++) code. This, however, may prove tricky if you are not familiar with this approach.

3) Another workaround is to build an API around your Java 17 application and then communicate from Android to your Java backend service. This would involve running your Java code on a server and getting results via network requests though, so it might not be suitable depending on what the application does.

Regarding using C#, if you're more comfortable with Java, you probably wouldn't gain much by switching languages. With Xamarin, you can use .NET libraries directly, but again, not Java ones, and you'd still be restricted by the range of .NET APIs that have been ported to run on Android.

Unless it's just a simple, one-off conversion, trying to adapt code that was written for one platform (like a JRE) to run on Android is going to require a significant amount of work. You'd be better off sticking with officially supported Java versions and dealing with any missing functionality by finding or writing equivalent Android code.
<|end|>


