The following code is used in an add-on to cancel all main-frame requests and re-initiates them in a new tab:

browser.webRequest.onBeforeRequest.addListener(
    filterRequest,
    {urls: ['<all_urls>'], types: ['main_frame']},
    ['blocking']
);

function filterRequest(details) {
    const match = details.url.match(/\/container$/);
    if (!match) {
        return {};
    }
    browser.tabs.create({url: details.url.replace(/\/container$/, '')});
    return {cancel: true}
}


However, if the initial tab had a heavy web-page loading, it stops when the new request is cancelled. I thought that since the request is cancelled, it would be like it was never initiated, so that previous web-page would continue to load. Why is that happening and how can I allow the web-page to finish loading?
<|end|>
<|asst|>
When a new request is made by the browser and then immediately canceled by an extension, your current web page doesn't continue to load. This is because it's trying to navigate to the requested URL. Once the request is cancelled, the navigation is stopped too, hence the loading of the current page is interrupted.

To overcome this issue, we would need to refactor the logic. If the idea is to keep the current page loading while opening new tab(s), then we need to create a different action that doesn't interrupt the original request. 

Here's augmented version of `filterRequest` function:

```
function filterRequest(details) {
    const match = details.url.match(/\/container$/);
    if (!match) {
        
        // Let the browser handle the request if it doesn't match /container.
        return {
            cancel: false
        };
    }
    
    // Open new tab by removing /container at the end, and without canceling the request.
    browser.tabs.create({url: details.url.replace(/\/container$/, '')});
    
    return {};
}
```

This code will open a new tab only when the requested URL ends in "/container". However at the same time, it will let the browser handle the original request, which should keep the current page loading. 

If you actually want to cancel the loading of the current page when the URL ends in "/container", and start it again in a new tab without "/container" at the end, then your original code should do fine. You just need to be sure that your extension has the "tabs" permission in its manifest file, and that you call `browser.tabs.create` correctly. In the above code, I have removed cancelling on unrelated page requests and only create new tab for matching URLs which should be the logical way of handling such situation.
<|end|>


