<|asst|>
First you will need to setup your react application. If you don't have a React application set up already, you can create one with `create-react-app`, which is a tool built by Facebook that generates a simple React application. You can install it and create a new application as follows:

Open up your terminal and run:
```bash
npx create-react-app react-api-app
```
This will create a new directory called `react-api-app` with a barebones react project.

For the second part of your question, I'll demonstrate an app that interacts with GitHub's user API. We'll have an input field where you can type a GitHub username and a button that when clicked, hits the API and displays basic profile information about the user (like their name, blog URL, and company).

Let's start with a simple component with a form:
```jsx
import React from "react";

class App extends React.Component {
  state = {
    username: "",
  };

  handleInputChange = (event) => {
    this.setState({ username: event.target.value });
  };

  handleSubmit = (event) => {
    event.preventDefault();
    console.log(this.state.username);
  };

  render() {
    return (
      <div>
        <form onSubmit={this.handleSubmit}>
          <input
            type="text"
            placeholder="GitHub username"
            value={this.state.username}
            onChange={this.handleInputChange}
          />
          <button type="submit">Submit</button>
        </form>
      </div>
    );
  }
}

export default App;
```

Now that we have the form set up, let's fetch some data! When the form is submitted, we're going to hit GitHub's API for some data on the submitted username. We'll do this in the handleSubmit function:

```jsx
import React from "react";
import axios from 'axios';

class App extends React.Component {
  state = {
    username: "",
    userData: {}
  };

  handleInputChange = (event) => {
    this.setState({ username: event.target.value });
  };

  handleSubmit = (event) => {
    event.preventDefault();
    axios.get(`https://api.github.com/users/${this.state.username}`)
    .then(response => { 
      this.setState({ userData: response.data });
    })
    .catch(error => {
      console.log(error); 
    });
 }

  render() {
    return (
      <div>
        <form onSubmit={this.handleSubmit}>
          <input
            type="text"
            placeholder="GitHub username"
            value={this.state.username}
            onChange={this.handleInputChange}
          />
          <button type="submit">Submit</button>
        </form>
        <hr/>
        {this.state.userData && (
          <div>
              <h3>{this.state.userData.name}</h3>
              <h4>{this.state.userData.company}</h4>
              <a href={this.state.userData.blog}>{this.state.userData.blog}</a>
          </div>
        )}
      </div>
    );
  }
}

export default App;
```

Also, install axios library for making API requests:
```bash
npm install axios
```

You can run your app with 
```bash
npm start
```
The app will run on a local server on your machine (normally on `localhost:3000`).

This is a very basic and simple way to fetch data from an API in a React app, but it gives you an idea of how to achieve this. Please also notice that we must handle errors that may occur while performing our request. Always make sure that you handle these types of possible errors when dealing with APIs.
<|end|>


