<|user|>
I got a doubt based on my understanding of following assumption,
1. For every CPU architecture the assembly language set will differ.
so, my doubt is how the common compiler/interpreter is converting it into .asm code because not all computers have same architecture!
Answer for this I guess that "While we are installing compiler in our system itself it gets to know about the computer architecture it's getting installed on and so it will convert C++/python/java to that corresponding CPU  .asm code"
So, if my above guess is correct then I understand while they design compiler the developer needs to integrate all CPU architecture's assembly set into compiler.
Note: My doubts would be silly, I never done any compiler course, am a ECE grad. Thanks in advance ;p
<|end|>
<|asst|>
You're actually on the right track with your assumptions.

1. Indeed, every CPU architecture has its own specific assembly language. This is because assembly language is a low-level programming language that is specific to a particular computer architecture. It is as close to the hardware as you can get with a language.

2. Now, when you install a compiler, it does indeed know what machine (architecture) it is being installed on. But it's not so much that it contains every possible CPU architecture's assembly language inside it. Instead, different versions of the compiler are made for different architectures. So, when you download a compiler, you will typically have to choose the version that matches your computer's architecture. In other words, the compiler is set up in advance to produce assembly code for a specific type of machine; it doesn't dynamically adjust to the machine it's installed on.

3. Then, when you compile say a C++ program, your compiler will generate assembly code that is specific to your machine's architecture. You can actually view this assembly code if you want to - compilers typically have an option to generate assembly output.

4. As for how these compilers are built to generate assembly code for different architectures, well, that's a deep and complicated topic on its own, and would be covered in-depth in a course on compiler construction. But in a nutshell, the compiler developers would need to know the assembly language of each target architecture very well, and write the compiler in such a way that is able to translate high-level language constructs to appropriate assembly code.

5. A separate piece of software called an assembler then translates the assembly code into machine code that can be run directly by the computer's CPU. Each CPU architecture needs its own specific assembler.
<|end|>


