We are using org.apache.kafka.clients.producer.KafkaProducer from `kafka-clients-1.0.0` for producing messages to broker.
Now, we need to write junit test case for this producer to send messages to mock kafka cluster
org.apache.kafka.clients.producer.MockProducer is there, but unable to use since both (KafkaProducer and MockProducer are impl of Producer)
: We need to spin up mock Kafka broker to execute junit test case.
: We need to initialize KakfaProducer with mock brokers and send messages to queue
<|end|>
<|asst|>
For mock testing Kafka, you may consider using the spring-kafka-test library which provides the class `Embedded Kafka Broker`. Here's an example of how your test class would look like:

Setting up Embedded Kafka Server:

```java
// Assuming a simple string producer
public class KafkaProducerTest {
    
    @Autowired
    private EmbeddedKafkaBroker embeddedKafka;

    private KafkaProducer<String, String> kafkaProducer;
    
    @Before
    public void setUp() {
        Map<String, Object> producerProps = new HashMap<>();
        producerProps.put(ProducerConfig.BOOTSTRAP_SERVERS_CONFIG, embeddedKafka.getBrokersAsString());
        producerProps.put(ProducerConfig.KEY_SERIALIZER_CLASS_CONFIG, StringSerializer.class);
        producerProps.put(ProducerConfig.VALUE_SERIALIZER_CLASS_CONFIG, StringSerializer.class);

        kafkaProducer = new KafkaProducer<>(producerProps);
    }

    @After
    public void clean() {
        kafkaProducer.close();
    }
    ...
}
```

Then, you can use this `kafkaProducer` instance for sending messages:

```java
@Test
public void testSendMessage() {
    // given
    String message = "test message";
    String topic = "test.topic";

    // when
    kafkaProducer.send(new ProducerRecord<>(topic, message));

    // Create Consumer to validate the sent message
    Map<String, Object> consumerProps = new HashMap<>();
    consumerProps.put(ConsumerConfig.BOOTSTRAP_SERVERS_CONFIG, embeddedKafka.getBrokersAsString());
    consumerProps.put(ConsumerConfig.GROUP_ID_CONFIG, "test.group");
    consumerProps.put(ConsumerConfig.KEY_DESERIALIZER_CLASS_CONFIG, StringDeserializer.class);
    consumerProps.put(ConsumerConfig.VALUE_DESERIALIZER_CLASS_CONFIG, StringDeserializer.class);
    KafkaConsumer<String, String> consumer = new KafkaConsumer<>(consumerProps);
    consumer.subscribe(Collections.singleton(topic));

    // then
    ConsumerRecords<String, String> records = consumer.poll(Duration.ofSeconds(5));
    Assert.assertEquals(1, records.count());
    for (ConsumerRecord<String, String> record : records) {
        Assert.assertEquals(message, record.value());
    }

    consumer.close();
}
```

Don't forget to annotate your JUnit test class with `@EmbeddedKafka`.

```java
@RunWith(SpringRunner.class)
@SpringBootTest
@EmbeddedKafka(topics = {"test.topic"}, partitions = 1)
public class KafkaProducerTest {
    ...
}
```

This way, you can create a real end-to-end test case where a Kafka producer sends messages to a test topic and a Kafka consumer fetches those messages for validation.
<|end|>


